{"title_page": "Blue cheese", "text_new": "{{For|the salad dressing and dipping sauce|blue cheese dressing}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[File:Bleu de Gex.jpg|thumb|[[Bleu de Gex]], a creamy, semi-soft blue cheese made in the [[Jura (d\u00e9partement)|Jura]] region of [[France]]]] \n\n'''Blue cheese''' or '''bleu cheese'''<ref>A common variant, using the French spelling of \"blue\"; [https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=bleu+cheese%2F(blue+cheese%2Bbleu+cheese)&case_insensitive=on&year_start=1920&year_end=2012&corpus=15&smoothing=20&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2C%28bleu%20cheese%20/%20%28blue%20cheese%20%2B%20bleu%20cheese%29%29%3B%2Cc0]</ref><ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', updated 1972, [https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/20192 ''s.v.'']</ref> is [[cheese]] made with cultures of the [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] ''[[Penicillium]]'', giving it blue spots or veins. This carries a distinct smell, either from that or various specially cultivated bacteria. Some blue cheeses are injected with [[spore]]s before the [[curds]] form, and others have spores mixed in with the curds after they form. Blue cheeses are typically aged in a temperature-controlled environment such as a [[cave]]. Blue cheese can be eaten by itself or can be spread, crumbled or melted into or over a range of other foods.\n\nThe characteristic flavor of blue cheeses tends to be sharp and salty. The smell of this food is due to both the mold and types of bacteria encouraged to grow on the cheese: for example, the bacterium ''[[Brevibacterium linens]]'' is responsible for the smell of many blue cheeses,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Deetae P |author2=Bonnarme P |author3=Spinnler HE |author4=Helinck S |title=Production of volatile aroma compounds by bacterial strains isolated from different surface-ripened French cheeses |journal=Appl. Microbiol. Biotechnol. |volume=76 |issue=5 |pages=1161\u201371 |date=October 2007 |pmid=17701035 |doi=10.1007/s00253-007-1095-5 }}</ref> as well as foot [[odor|odour]] and other human body odors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dixon |first1=Bernard |title=Cheese, toes, and mosquitoes |journal=BMJ |date=27 April 1996 |volume=312 |issue=7038 |pages=1105 |doi=10.1136/bmj.312.7038.1105 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBlue cheese is believed to have been discovered by accident when cheeses were stored in natural temperatures and moisture-controlled caves which happen to be favorable environments for many varieties of harmless mold. It was moist in the cave so the mold would form. According to legend, one of the first blue cheeses, [[Roquefort]], was discovered when a young boy, eating bread and [[ewes' milk]] cheese, abandoned his meal in a nearby cave after seeing a beautiful girl in the distance. When he returned months later, the mold (''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'') had transformed his cheese into Roquefort.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D06EFDA143BF930A15755C0A964948260&sec=health|title=Blue-veined Cheeses : The expanding choices|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 23, 1982 | first=Florence | last=Fabricant | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name=bw>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/stories/2001-12-30/something-is-rotten-in-roquefort|title=Something is rotten in Roquefort|publisher=[[Business Week]]|date=December 31, 2001}}</ref>\n\n[[Gorgonzola (cheese)|Gorgonzola]] is one of the oldest known blue cheeses, having been created around AD 879, though it is said that it did not contain blue veins until around the 11th century.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorgonzola, the cheese that lives|url=http://www.italianfoodexcellence.com/gorgonzola-the-cheese-that-lives/|website=Italian Food Excellence|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Castello\u00ae Gorgonzola|url=http://www.castellocheese.com/en-ca/our-cheeses/gorgonzola/|website=Castello|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> [[Stilton cheese|Stilton]] is a relatively new addition, becoming popular sometime in the early 1700s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stiltoncheese.co.uk/history_of_stilton|title=History of Stilton|last=|first=|date=|website=StiltonCheese.co.uk|publisher=|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref> Many varieties of blue cheese that originated subsequently, such as the 20th century [[Danablu]] and [[Cambozola]], were an attempt to fill the demand for Roquefort-style cheeses that were prohibitive  due to either cost or politics.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Production ==\n[[File:Bavaria blu 01 WikiCheese Lokal K.jpg|thumb|right|[[Cambozola]], a German variety of blue cheese]]\nSimilarly to other varieties of cheese, the process of making blue cheese consists of six standard steps. However, additional ingredients and processes are required to give this blue-veined cheese its particular properties. To begin with, the commercial scale production of blue cheese consists of two phases: the culturing of suitable spore-rich inocula and fermentation for maximum, typical flavor.<ref name=\":1\">Watts, j. C. Jr.. Nelson, J. H. (to Dairyland Food Laboratories, Inc.), U.S. Patent 3,072,488 (Jan. 8, 1963).</ref>\n\n=== ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum ===\nIn the first phase of production, a ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum is prepared prior to the actual production of blue cheese.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Nelson |first1=John Howard. |title=Production of Blue cheese flavor via submerged fermentation by Penicillium roqueforti |journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |date=July 1970 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=567\u2013569 |doi=10.1021/jf60170a024 }}</ref> Multiple methods can be used to achieve this. However, all methods involve the use of a [[freeze-dried]] ''Penicillium roqueforti'' culture. Although ''Penicillium roqueforti'' can be  found naturally, cheese producers nowadays use commercially manufactured ''Penicillium roqueforti.'' First, ''Penicillium roqueforti'' is washed from a pure culture agar plants which is later frozen.<ref name=\":3\" /> Through the freeze drying process, water from the frozen state is evaporated without the transition through the liquid state ([[Sublimation (phase transition)|sublimation]]). This retains the value of the culture and is activated upon the addition of water.\n\nSalt, sugar or both are added to [[Autoclave (industrial)|autoclaved]], [[Milk homogenization|homogenized]] milk via a sterile solution.  This mixture is then inoculated with ''Penicillium roqueforti''. This solution is first incubated for three to four days at {{convert|21-25|C}}. More salt and/or sugar is added and then aerobic incubation is continued for an additional one to two days.<ref name=\":1\" /> Alternatively, sterilized, homogenized milk and reconstituted non-fat solids or whey solids are mixed with sterile salt to create a fermentation medium. A spore-rich ''Penicillium roqueforti'' culture is then added. Next, modified milk fat is added which consists of milk fat with calf pre-gastric esterase.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nelson |first1=J.H. |last2=Jensen |first2=R.G. |last3=Pitas |first3=R.E. |title=Pregastric Esterase and other Oral Lipases\u2014A Review |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=March 1977 |volume=60 |issue=3 |pages=327\u2013362 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(77)83873-3 |pmid=321489 |doi-access=free }}</ref> This solution is prepared in advance by an enzyme hydrolysis of a milk fat emulsion. The addition of modified milk fat stimulates a progressive release of free fatty acids via lipase action which is essential for rapid flavor development in blue cheese.<ref name=\":3\" /> This inoculum produced by either methods is later added to the cheese curds.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Production and fermentation ===\n[[File:Gorgonzola 1.jpg|thumb|[[Gorgonzola]] cheese]]\nFirst, raw milk (either from cattle, goats or sheep) is mixed and [[Pasteurization|pasteurized]] at {{convert|72|C}} for 15 seconds.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite book |last1=Cantor |first1=M. D. |last2=van den Tempel |first2=T. |last3=Hansen |first3=T. K. |last4=Ard\u00f6 |first4=Y. |title=Cheese: Chemistry, Physics and Microbiology |volume=2 |date=2004 |publisher=Academic Press |pages=175\u2013198 |doi=10.1016/S1874-558X(04)80044-7 |chapter=Blue cheese |isbn=9780122636530 }}</ref> Then, acidification occurs: a [[starter culture]], such as ''[[Streptococcus Lactis|Streptococcus lactis]],'' is added in order to change [[lactose]] to [[lactic acid]], thus changing the acidity of the milk and turning it from liquid to solid.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://cheese.about.com/od/howcheeseismade/a/make_bluecheese.htm|title=What Makes Blue Cheese Blue?|work=The Spruce|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref> The next step is [[coagulation]], where [[rennet]], a mixture of [[Chymosin|rennin]] and other material found in the stomach lining of a calf is added to solidify the milk further.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Following this, thick curds are cut typically with a knife to encourage the release of liquid or [[whey]].<ref name=\"auto\" /> The smaller the curds are cut, the thicker and harder the resulting cheese will become.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nAfter the curds have been ladled into containers in order to be drained and formed into a full wheel of cheese, the ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum is sprinkled on top of the curds along with ''[[Brevibacterium linens]]''.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Then, the curds granules are knit in molds to form cheese loaves with a relatively open texture.<ref name=\":3\" /> Next, whey drainage continues for 10\u201348 hours in which no pressure is applied, but the molds are inverted frequently to promote this process.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Salt]] is then added to provide flavor as well as to act as a preservative so the cheese does not spoil through the process of [[Brining|brine salting]] or dry salting for 24\u201348 hours.<ref name=\":4\" /> The final step is ripening the cheese by aging it. When the cheese is freshly made, there is little to no blue cheese flavor development.<ref name=\":3\" /> Usually, a fermentation period of 60\u201390 days are needed before the flavor of the cheese is typical and acceptable for marketing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDuring this ripening period, the temperature and the level of humidity in the room where the cheese is aging is monitored to ensure the cheese does not spoil or lose its optimal flavor and texture.<ref name=\"auto\" /> In general, the ripening temperature is around eight to ten degrees Celsius with a relative humidity of 85\u201395%, but this may differ according to the type of blue cheese being produced.<ref name=\":4\" /> At the beginning of this ripening process, the cheese loaves are punctured to create small openings to allow air to penetrate and support the rich growth of the aerobic ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'' cultures, thus encouraging the formation of blue veins.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nThroughout the ripening process, the total ketone content is constantly monitored as the distinctive flavor and aroma of blue cheese arises from methyl [[ketones]] (including [[2-pentanone]], [[2-heptanone]], and [[2-nonanone]])<ref name=\"The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese a\">{{cite journal |last1=Patton |first1=Stuart |title=The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese and their Relation to its Flavor |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=September 1950 |volume=33 |issue=9 |pages=680\u2013684 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(50)91954-0 |doi-access=free }}</ref> which are a metabolic product of ''Penicillium roqueforti''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.webexhibits.org/butter/compounds-methylKetones.html|title=Methyl ketones : Butter|website=webexhibits.org}}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harte |first1=Bruce R. |last2=Stine |first2=C.M. |title=Effects of Process Parameters on Formation of Volatile Acids and Free Fatty Acids in Quick-Ripened Blue Cheese |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=August 1977 |volume=60 |issue=8 |pages=1266\u20131272 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(77)84021-6 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Once the specified level of total ketone production is attained, the blue cheese is sterilized at ultra high temperature/short time at {{convert|130|C}} for four seconds.<ref name=\":3\" /> This heat treatment also inactivates the ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]],'' inhibiting further fermentation.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Toxins from the production of blue cheese ==\n''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'', responsible for the greenish blue moldy aspect of blue cheese, produces several [[mycotoxin]]s. While mycotoxins like roquefortine, isofumigaclavine A, [[mycophenolic acid]] and [[ferrichrome]], are present at low levels, [[penicillic acid]] and PR toxin are unstable in the cheese. Because of the instability of PR toxin and lack of optimal environmental conditions (temperature, aeration) for the production of PR toxin and roquefortine, health hazards due to ''Penicillium roqueforti'' [[metabolite]]s are considerably reduced.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Medina |first1=Margarita |last2=Gaya |first2=Pilar |last3=Nu\u00f1ez |first3=M. |title=Production of PR Toxin and Roquefortine by Penicillium roqueforti Isolates from Cabrales Blue Cheese |journal=Journal of Food Protection |date=February 1985 |volume=48 |issue=2 |pages=118\u2013121 |doi=10.4315/0362-028X-48.2.118 |pmid=30934519 }}</ref> Additionally, mycotoxin contamination occurs at low levels and large quantities of cheese are rarely consumed, suggesting that hazard to human health is unlikely.&nbsp;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dobson |first1=Alan D. W. |title=Cheese |edition=4th |date=2017 |publisher=Academic Press |isbn=978-0-12-417012-4 |pages=595\u2013601 |doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-417012-4.00023-5 |chapter=Mycotoxins in Cheese }}</ref>\n\n== Physicochemical properties ==\n\n=== Structure ===\nThe main structure of the blue cheese comes from the aggregation of the casein. In milk, casein does not aggregate because of the outer layer of the particle, called the  \u201chairy layer.\u201d The hairy layer consists of \u03ba-casein, which are strings of [[polypeptide]]s that extend outward from the center of the casein micelle.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shukla|first1=Anuj|last2=Narayanan|first2=Theyencheri|last3=Zanchi|first3=Drazen|title=Structure of casein micelles and their complexation with tannins|journal=Soft Matter|date=2009|volume=5|issue=15|page=2884|url=http://www.esrf.eu/UsersAndScience/Publications/Highlights/2009/scm/scm02|accessdate=17 December 2017|doi=10.1039/b903103k|bibcode=2009SMat....5.2884S}}</ref>  The entanglement of the hairy layer between casein micelles decreases the [[entropy]] of the system because it constrains the micelles, preventing them from spreading out. Curds form, however, due to the function that the [[enzyme]], rennet, plays in removing the hairy layer in the casein micelle. Rennet is an enzyme that cleaves the \u03ba-casein off the casein micelle, thus removing the strain that occurs when the hairy layer entangles. The casein micelles are then able to aggregate together when they collide with each other, forming the curds that can then be made into blue cheese.\n[[File:2015-01-25 Jersey Blue - St\u00e4dtch\u00e4si Lichtensteig - der Schweizer - hu - 8005.jpg|thumb|235x235px|Characteristic blue veins in blue cheese.]]\n\n=== Mold growth  ===\n''Penicillium roqueforti'' and ''Penicillium glaucum'' are both molds that require the presence of oxygen to grow. Therefore, initial fermentation of the cheese is done by [[lactic acid bacteria]]. The lactic acid bacteria, however, are killed by the low [[pH]] and the secondary fermenters, ''Penicillium roqueforti'', take over and break the lactic acid down, maintaining a pH in the aged cheese above 6.0.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Diezhandino|last2=Fernandez|last3=Gonzalez|last4=McSweeney|last5=Fresno|title=Microbiological, physio-chemical and proteolytic changes in a Spanish blue cheese during ripening (Valdeon cheese).|journal=Food Chemistry|date=2015|volume=168|issue=1|doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2014.07.039|pmid=25172692|pages=134\u2013141}}</ref> As the pH rises again from the loss of [[lactic acid]], the enzymes in the molds responsible for [[lipolysis]] and [[proteolysis]] are more active and can continue to ferment the cheese because they are optimal at a pH of 6.0.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gilliot|last2=Jany|last3=Poirier|last4=Maillard|last5=Debaets|last6=Thierry|last7=Coton|last8=Coton|title=Functional diversity within the Penicillium roqueforti species|journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology|date=2017|volume=241|issue=1|pages=141\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.ijfoodmicro.2016.10.001|pmid=27771579}}</ref>\n\n''Penicillium roqueforti'' creates the characteristic blue veins in blue cheese after the aged curds have been pierced, forming air tunnels in the cheese. When given oxygen, the mold is able to grow along the surface of the curd-air interface.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fernandez-salguero|title=INTERNAL MOULD - RIPENED CHEESES: CHARACTERISTICS, COMPOSITION AND PROTEOLYSIS OF THE MAIN EUROPEAN BLUE VEIN VARIETIES|journal=Italian Journal of Food Science|date=2004|volume=16|issue=4}}</ref> The veins along the blue cheese are also responsible for the aroma of blue cheese itself. In fact, one type of bacteria in blue cheese, Brevibacterium linens, is the same bacteria responsible for foot and body odor. B. linens was previously thought to give cheeses their distinct orangish pigmentation, but studies show this not to be the case and blue cheese is an example of the lack of that orange pigmentation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wolfe |first1=Benjamin |title=digesting the science of fermented foods |url=http://microbialfoods.org/beyond-b-linens-how-cheese-rinds-get-their-color/ |website=microbialfoods.org |accessdate=2014-07-27}}</ref> In pressing the cheese, the curds are not tightly packed in order to allow for air gaps between them. After piercing, the mold can also grow in between the curds.\n[[File:Blue cheese plates.jpg|thumb|Blue cheese platter]]\n=== Flavor ===\n\nA portion of the distinct flavor comes from lipolysis (the breakdown of fat). The metabolism of the blue mold further breaks down fatty acids to form ketones to give blue cheese a richer flavor and aroma.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Polowsky |first1=Pat |title=Blue |url=https://www.cheesescience.org/blue.html |website=cheesescience.org}}</ref>\n\n== Regulation ==\n=== European Union ===\nIn the [[European Union]], many blue cheeses, such as [[Cabrales cheese|Cabrales]], [[Danish Blue Cheese|Danablu]], [[Gorgonzola]], [[Roquefort]] and [[Stilton cheese|Blue Stilton]], carry a [[protected designation of origin]], meaning they can bear the name only if they have been made in a particular region. Similarly, individual countries have protections of their own such as France's [[Appellation d'Origine Contr\u00f4l\u00e9e]] and Italy's [[Denominazione di Origine Protetta]]. Blue cheeses with no protected origin name are designated simply \"blue cheese\".\n\n=== Canada ===\n\nUnder the regulation of the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]], it requires manufacturers to produce blue cheese with a 47 maximum percentage of moisture and 27 percent minimum percentage of milk fat.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/c.r.c.,_c._870/page-45.html#docCont|title=Consolidated federal laws of canada, Food and Drug Regulations|last=Branch|first=Legislative Services|date=2019-06-17|website=laws-lois.justice.gc.ca|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Salt is allowed to be used as a preservative; however, the amount of the salt or combination of salts shall not exceed 200 parts per million of the milk and milk products used to make the cheese.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other than that the regulation of Canadian Food Inspection Agency does not limit producers to use bacterial cultures to aid further ripening and&nbsp;flavoring preparations other than cheese flavoring.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Properties ==\nGorgonzola, Stilton, and Roquefort are considered to be favored blue cheeses in many countries.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Companion to Food (3 ed.)|last=Davidson|first=Alan|last2=Jaine|first2=Tom|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780199677337|location=|pages=}}</ref> These cheeses all have a [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|protected designation of origin]] in which they may only be called their respective name if produced a certain way in a certain location.\n\n=== Gorgonzola ===\n{{Main|Gorgonzola}}\n\nGorgonzola blue cheese takes its name from the village of [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]] in Italy where it was first made.<ref name=\":0\" /> Belonging to the family of [[Stracchino]] cheeses, Gorgonzola is a whole milk, white, and \"uncooked\" cheese.<ref name=\":0\" /> This blue cheese has been inoculated with ''[[Penicillium glaucum]]'' which, during ripening, produces the characteristic of blue-green veins.<ref name=\":0\" /> The odor of Gorgonzola varies between natural and creamy Gorgonzola cheese.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Addeo|first=Francesco|last2=Piombino|first2=Paola|last3=Moio|first3=Luigi|date=May 2000|title=Odour-impact compounds of Gorgonzola cheese|journal=Journal of Dairy Research|volume=67|issue=2|pages=273\u2013285|doi=10.1017/S0022029900004106|pmid=10840681|issn=1469-7629}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moio |first1=Luigi |last2=Piombino |first2=Paola |last3=Addeo |first3=Francesco |title=Odour-impact compounds of Gorgonzola cheese |journal=Journal of Dairy Research |date=1 May 2000 |volume=67 |issue=2 |pages=273\u2013285 |doi=10.1017/S0022029900004106 |pmid=10840681 }}</ref> 63 components in natural Gorgonzola cheese and 52 components in creamy Gorgonzola cheese contribute to odor with 2-[[nonanone]], [[1-Octen-3-ol|1-octen-3-ol]], [[2-Heptanol|2-heptanol]], [[ethyl hexanoate]], [[methylanisole]] and [[2-Heptanone|2-heptanone]] being the prominent compounds for odor in both cheeses.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monti |first1=Lucia |last2=Pelizzola |first2=Valeria |last3=Povolo |first3=Milena |last4=Fontana |first4=Stefano |last5=Contarini |first5=Giovanna |title=Study on the sugar content of blue-veined 'Gorgonzola' PDO cheese |journal=International Dairy Journal |date=August 2019 |volume=95 |pages=1\u20135 |doi=10.1016/j.idairyj.2019.03.009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Stilton ===\n{{Main|Stilton cheese}}\n[[File:Homemade Stilton Blue Cheese in UK.jpg|thumb|Stilton blue cheese]]\nStilton blue cheese had been first produced in the village of [[Stilton]] in England. Different from [[Stichelton]], which is made from raw milk, Stilton cheese is made from [[Pasteurization|pasteurized milk]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition to being inoculated with ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'' to give it the blue vein characteristic, research has shown that other microbiota which are relatives of ''[[Lactococcus lactis]]'', ''[[Enterococcus faecalis]]'', ''[[Lactobacillus plantarum]]'', ''[https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/lactobacillus-curvatus Lactobacillus curvatus]'', ''[[Leuconostoc mesenteroides]]'', ''[[Staphylococcus equorum]]'', and [[Staphylococcus|''Staphylococcus'' sp]]. can also be found in Stilton cheese.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ercolini |first1=D. |last2=Hill |first2=P. J. |last3=Dodd |first3=C. E. R. |title=Bacterial Community Structure and Location in Stilton Cheese |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |date=1 June 2003 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=3540\u20133548 |doi=10.1128/AEM.69.6.3540-3548.2003 |pmid=12788761 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Some important microbiota contribute to the aromatic profile such as those of the ''[[Lactobacillus]]'' genus due to their production of [[Volatile organic compound|volatile compounds]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mugampoza |first1=Diriisa |last2=Gkatzionis |first2=Konstantinos |last3=Linforth |first3=Robert S.T. |last4=Dodd |first4=Christine E.R. |title=Acid production, growth kinetics and aroma profiles of Lactobacillus flora from Stilton cheese |journal=Food Chemistry |date=July 2019 |volume=287 |pages=222\u2013231 |doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2019.02.082 |pmid=30857693 }}</ref> During ripening, [[Fatty acid|free fatty acids]] increase in amount which contribute to the characteristic flavor of blue cheeses due to [[Lipolysis|fat breakdown]] by ''Penicillium roqueforti''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Madkor |first1=S. |last2=Fox |first2=P.F. |last3=Shalabi |first3=S.I. |last4=Metwalli |first4=N.H. |title=Studies on the ripening of stilton cheese: Lipolysis |journal=Food Chemistry |date=January 1987 |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=93\u2013109 |doi=10.1016/0308-8146(87)90058-6 }}</ref>\n\n=== Roquefort ===\n{{Main|Roquefort}}\n[[File:Wikicheese - Roquefort - 20150417 - 003.jpg|thumb|Roquefort cheese]]\nRoquefort blue cheese originates from the village of [[Roquefort-sur-Soulzon]], France.<ref name=\":0\" /> Its flavors come from the use of unpasteurized [[Sheep milk|sheep's milk]], inoculation with ''Penicillium roqueforti'', and the special conditions of the natural caves of Roquefort-sur-Soulzon in which they are ripened.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Penicillium roqueforti'' is the cause of the blue veins in Roquefort cheese. In addition to ''Penicillium roqueforti'', various yeasts are present, namely ''[[Debaryomyces hansenii]]'' and its non-sporulating form ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida famata]]'', and ''[[Kluyveromyces lactis]]'' and its non-sporulating form ''Candida sphaerica.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Besan\u00e7on |first1=X. |last2=Smet |first2=C. |last3=Chabalier |first3=C. |last4=Rivemale |first4=M. |last5=Reverbel |first5=J.P. |last6=Ratomahenina |first6=R. |last7=Galzy |first7=P. |title=Study of surface yeast flora of Roquefort cheese |journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology |date=September 1992 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201318 |doi=10.1016/0168-1605(92)90014-T |pmid=1476870 }}</ref> Similarly to other kinds of blue cheeses, Roquefort's flavor and odor can be attributed to the particular mixture of methyl ketones such as 2-heptanone, [[2-Pentanone|2-pentanone]], and 2-nonanone.<ref name=\"The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese a\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of blue cheeses]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Blue cheese}}\n\n{{Cheese}}\n{{Blue cheeses}}\n\n[[Category:Blue cheeses| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the salad dressing and dipping sauce|blue cheese dressing}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[File:Bleu de Gex.jpg|thumb|[[Bleu de Gex]], a creamy, semi-soft blue cheese made in the [[Jura (d\u00e9partement)|Jura]] region of [[France]]]] \n\n'''Blue cheese''' or '''bleu cheese'''<ref>A common variant, using the French spelling of \"blue\"; [https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=bleu+cheese%2F(blue+cheese%2Bbleu+cheese)&case_insensitive=on&year_start=1920&year_end=2012&corpus=15&smoothing=20&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2C%28bleu%20cheese%20/%20%28blue%20cheese%20%2B%20bleu%20cheese%29%29%3B%2Cc0]</ref><ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', updated 1972, [https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/20192 ''s.v.'']</ref> is [[cheese]] made with cultures of the [[mold]] ''[[Penicillium]]'', giving it blue spots or veins. This carries a distinct smell, either from that or various specially cultivated bacteria. Some blue cheeses are injected with [[spore]]s before the [[curds]] form, and others have spores mixed in with the curds after they form. Blue cheeses are typically aged in a temperature-controlled environment such as a [[cave]]. Blue cheese can be eaten by itself or can be spread, crumbled or melted into or over a range of other foods.\n\nThe characteristic flavor of blue cheeses tends to be sharp and salty. The smell of this food is due to both the mold and types of bacteria encouraged to grow on the cheese: for example, the bacterium ''[[Brevibacterium linens]]'' is responsible for the smell of many blue cheeses,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Deetae P |author2=Bonnarme P |author3=Spinnler HE |author4=Helinck S |title=Production of volatile aroma compounds by bacterial strains isolated from different surface-ripened French cheeses |journal=Appl. Microbiol. Biotechnol. |volume=76 |issue=5 |pages=1161\u201371 |date=October 2007 |pmid=17701035 |doi=10.1007/s00253-007-1095-5 }}</ref> as well as foot [[odor|odour]] and other human body odors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dixon |first1=Bernard |title=Cheese, toes, and mosquitoes |journal=BMJ |date=27 April 1996 |volume=312 |issue=7038 |pages=1105 |doi=10.1136/bmj.312.7038.1105 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBlue cheese is believed to have been discovered by accident when cheeses were stored in natural temperatures and moisture-controlled caves which happen to be favorable environments for many varieties of harmless mold. It was moist in the cave so the mold would form. According to legend, one of the first blue cheeses, [[Roquefort]], was discovered when a young boy, eating bread and [[ewes' milk]] cheese, abandoned his meal in a nearby cave after seeing a beautiful girl in the distance. When he returned months later, the mold (''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'') had transformed his cheese into Roquefort.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D06EFDA143BF930A15755C0A964948260&sec=health|title=Blue-veined Cheeses : The expanding choices|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 23, 1982 | first=Florence | last=Fabricant | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name=bw>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/stories/2001-12-30/something-is-rotten-in-roquefort|title=Something is rotten in Roquefort|publisher=[[Business Week]]|date=December 31, 2001}}</ref>\n\n[[Gorgonzola (cheese)|Gorgonzola]] is one of the oldest known blue cheeses, having been created around AD 879, though it is said that it did not contain blue veins until around the 11th century.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorgonzola, the cheese that lives|url=http://www.italianfoodexcellence.com/gorgonzola-the-cheese-that-lives/|website=Italian Food Excellence|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Castello\u00ae Gorgonzola|url=http://www.castellocheese.com/en-ca/our-cheeses/gorgonzola/|website=Castello|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> [[Stilton cheese|Stilton]] is a relatively new addition, becoming popular sometime in the early 1700s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stiltoncheese.co.uk/history_of_stilton|title=History of Stilton|last=|first=|date=|website=StiltonCheese.co.uk|publisher=|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref> Many varieties of blue cheese that originated subsequently, such as the 20th century [[Danablu]] and [[Cambozola]], were an attempt to fill the demand for Roquefort-style cheeses that were prohibitive  due to either cost or politics.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Production ==\n[[File:Bavaria blu 01 WikiCheese Lokal K.jpg|thumb|right|[[Cambozola]], a German variety of blue cheese]]\nSimilarly to other varieties of cheese, the process of making blue cheese consists of six standard steps. However, additional ingredients and processes are required to give this blue-veined cheese its particular properties. To begin with, the commercial scale production of blue cheese consists of two phases: the culturing of suitable spore-rich inocula and fermentation for maximum, typical flavor.<ref name=\":1\">Watts, j. C. Jr.. Nelson, J. H. (to Dairyland Food Laboratories, Inc.), U.S. Patent 3,072,488 (Jan. 8, 1963).</ref>\n\n=== ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum ===\nIn the first phase of production, a ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum is prepared prior to the actual production of blue cheese.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Nelson |first1=John Howard. |title=Production of Blue cheese flavor via submerged fermentation by Penicillium roqueforti |journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |date=July 1970 |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=567\u2013569 |doi=10.1021/jf60170a024 }}</ref> Multiple methods can be used to achieve this. However, all methods involve the use of a [[freeze-dried]] ''Penicillium roqueforti'' culture. Although ''Penicillium roqueforti'' can be  found naturally, cheese producers nowadays use commercially manufactured ''Penicillium roqueforti.'' First, ''Penicillium roqueforti'' is washed from a pure culture agar plants which is later frozen.<ref name=\":3\" /> Through the freeze drying process, water from the frozen state is evaporated without the transition through the liquid state ([[Sublimation (phase transition)|sublimation]]). This retains the value of the culture and is activated upon the addition of water.\n\nSalt, sugar or both are added to [[Autoclave (industrial)|autoclaved]], [[Milk homogenization|homogenized]] milk via a sterile solution.  This mixture is then inoculated with ''Penicillium roqueforti''. This solution is first incubated for three to four days at {{convert|21-25|C}}. More salt and/or sugar is added and then aerobic incubation is continued for an additional one to two days.<ref name=\":1\" /> Alternatively, sterilized, homogenized milk and reconstituted non-fat solids or whey solids are mixed with sterile salt to create a fermentation medium. A spore-rich ''Penicillium roqueforti'' culture is then added. Next, modified milk fat is added which consists of milk fat with calf pre-gastric esterase.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nelson |first1=J.H. |last2=Jensen |first2=R.G. |last3=Pitas |first3=R.E. |title=Pregastric Esterase and other Oral Lipases\u2014A Review |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=March 1977 |volume=60 |issue=3 |pages=327\u2013362 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(77)83873-3 |pmid=321489 |doi-access=free }}</ref> This solution is prepared in advance by an enzyme hydrolysis of a milk fat emulsion. The addition of modified milk fat stimulates a progressive release of free fatty acids via lipase action which is essential for rapid flavor development in blue cheese.<ref name=\":3\" /> This inoculum produced by either methods is later added to the cheese curds.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Production and fermentation ===\n[[File:Gorgonzola 1.jpg|thumb|[[Gorgonzola]] cheese]]\nFirst, raw milk (either from cattle, goats or sheep) is mixed and [[Pasteurization|pasteurized]] at {{convert|72|C}} for 15 seconds.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite book |last1=Cantor |first1=M. D. |last2=van den Tempel |first2=T. |last3=Hansen |first3=T. K. |last4=Ard\u00f6 |first4=Y. |title=Cheese: Chemistry, Physics and Microbiology |volume=2 |date=2004 |publisher=Academic Press |pages=175\u2013198 |doi=10.1016/S1874-558X(04)80044-7 |chapter=Blue cheese |isbn=9780122636530 }}</ref> Then, acidification occurs: a [[starter culture]], such as ''[[Streptococcus Lactis|Streptococcus lactis]],'' is added in order to change [[lactose]] to [[lactic acid]], thus changing the acidity of the milk and turning it from liquid to solid.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://cheese.about.com/od/howcheeseismade/a/make_bluecheese.htm|title=What Makes Blue Cheese Blue?|work=The Spruce|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref> The next step is [[coagulation]], where [[rennet]], a mixture of [[Chymosin|rennin]] and other material found in the stomach lining of a calf is added to solidify the milk further.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Following this, thick curds are cut typically with a knife to encourage the release of liquid or [[whey]].<ref name=\"auto\" /> The smaller the curds are cut, the thicker and harder the resulting cheese will become.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nAfter the curds have been ladled into containers in order to be drained and formed into a full wheel of cheese, the ''Penicillium roqueforti'' inoculum is sprinkled on top of the curds along with ''[[Brevibacterium linens]]''.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Then, the curds granules are knit in molds to form cheese loaves with a relatively open texture.<ref name=\":3\" /> Next, whey drainage continues for 10\u201348 hours in which no pressure is applied, but the molds are inverted frequently to promote this process.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Salt]] is then added to provide flavor as well as to act as a preservative so the cheese does not spoil through the process of [[Brining|brine salting]] or dry salting for 24\u201348 hours.<ref name=\":4\" /> The final step is ripening the cheese by aging it. When the cheese is freshly made, there is little to no blue cheese flavor development.<ref name=\":3\" /> Usually, a fermentation period of 60\u201390 days are needed before the flavor of the cheese is typical and acceptable for marketing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDuring this ripening period, the temperature and the level of humidity in the room where the cheese is aging is monitored to ensure the cheese does not spoil or lose its optimal flavor and texture.<ref name=\"auto\" /> In general, the ripening temperature is around eight to ten degrees Celsius with a relative humidity of 85\u201395%, but this may differ according to the type of blue cheese being produced.<ref name=\":4\" /> At the beginning of this ripening process, the cheese loaves are punctured to create small openings to allow air to penetrate and support the rich growth of the aerobic ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'' cultures, thus encouraging the formation of blue veins.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nThroughout the ripening process, the total ketone content is constantly monitored as the distinctive flavor and aroma of blue cheese arises from methyl [[ketones]] (including [[2-pentanone]], [[2-heptanone]], and [[2-nonanone]])<ref name=\"The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese a\">{{cite journal |last1=Patton |first1=Stuart |title=The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese and their Relation to its Flavor |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=September 1950 |volume=33 |issue=9 |pages=680\u2013684 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(50)91954-0 |doi-access=free }}</ref> which are a metabolic product of ''Penicillium roqueforti''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.webexhibits.org/butter/compounds-methylKetones.html|title=Methyl ketones : Butter|website=webexhibits.org}}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Harte |first1=Bruce R. |last2=Stine |first2=C.M. |title=Effects of Process Parameters on Formation of Volatile Acids and Free Fatty Acids in Quick-Ripened Blue Cheese |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |date=August 1977 |volume=60 |issue=8 |pages=1266\u20131272 |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(77)84021-6 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Once the specified level of total ketone production is attained, the blue cheese is sterilized at ultra high temperature/short time at {{convert|130|C}} for four seconds.<ref name=\":3\" /> This heat treatment also inactivates the ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]],'' inhibiting further fermentation.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Toxins from the production of blue cheese ==\n''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'', responsible for the greenish blue moldy aspect of blue cheese, produces several [[mycotoxin]]s. While mycotoxins like roquefortine, isofumigaclavine A, [[mycophenolic acid]] and [[ferrichrome]], are present at low levels, [[penicillic acid]] and PR toxin are unstable in the cheese. Because of the instability of PR toxin and lack of optimal environmental conditions (temperature, aeration) for the production of PR toxin and roquefortine, health hazards due to ''Penicillium roqueforti'' [[metabolite]]s are considerably reduced.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Medina |first1=Margarita |last2=Gaya |first2=Pilar |last3=Nu\u00f1ez |first3=M. |title=Production of PR Toxin and Roquefortine by Penicillium roqueforti Isolates from Cabrales Blue Cheese |journal=Journal of Food Protection |date=February 1985 |volume=48 |issue=2 |pages=118\u2013121 |doi=10.4315/0362-028X-48.2.118 |pmid=30934519 }}</ref> Additionally, mycotoxin contamination occurs at low levels and large quantities of cheese are rarely consumed, suggesting that hazard to human health is unlikely.&nbsp;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dobson |first1=Alan D. W. |title=Cheese |edition=4th |date=2017 |publisher=Academic Press |isbn=978-0-12-417012-4 |pages=595\u2013601 |doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-417012-4.00023-5 |chapter=Mycotoxins in Cheese }}</ref>\n\n== Physicochemical properties ==\n\n=== Structure ===\nThe main structure of the blue cheese comes from the aggregation of the casein. In milk, casein does not aggregate because of the outer layer of the particle, called the  \u201chairy layer.\u201d The hairy layer consists of \u03ba-casein, which are strings of [[polypeptide]]s that extend outward from the center of the casein micelle.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shukla|first1=Anuj|last2=Narayanan|first2=Theyencheri|last3=Zanchi|first3=Drazen|title=Structure of casein micelles and their complexation with tannins|journal=Soft Matter|date=2009|volume=5|issue=15|page=2884|url=http://www.esrf.eu/UsersAndScience/Publications/Highlights/2009/scm/scm02|accessdate=17 December 2017|doi=10.1039/b903103k|bibcode=2009SMat....5.2884S}}</ref>  The entanglement of the hairy layer between casein micelles decreases the [[entropy]] of the system because it constrains the micelles, preventing them from spreading out. Curds form, however, due to the function that the [[enzyme]], rennet, plays in removing the hairy layer in the casein micelle. Rennet is an enzyme that cleaves the \u03ba-casein off the casein micelle, thus removing the strain that occurs when the hairy layer entangles. The casein micelles are then able to aggregate together when they collide with each other, forming the curds that can then be made into blue cheese.\n[[File:2015-01-25 Jersey Blue - St\u00e4dtch\u00e4si Lichtensteig - der Schweizer - hu - 8005.jpg|thumb|235x235px|Characteristic blue veins in blue cheese.]]\n\n=== Mold growth  ===\n''Penicillium roqueforti'' and ''Penicillium glaucum'' are both molds that require the presence of oxygen to grow. Therefore, initial fermentation of the cheese is done by [[lactic acid bacteria]]. The lactic acid bacteria, however, are killed by the low [[pH]] and the secondary fermenters, ''Penicillium roqueforti'', take over and break the lactic acid down, maintaining a pH in the aged cheese above 6.0.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Diezhandino|last2=Fernandez|last3=Gonzalez|last4=McSweeney|last5=Fresno|title=Microbiological, physio-chemical and proteolytic changes in a Spanish blue cheese during ripening (Valdeon cheese).|journal=Food Chemistry|date=2015|volume=168|issue=1|doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2014.07.039|pmid=25172692|pages=134\u2013141}}</ref> As the pH rises again from the loss of [[lactic acid]], the enzymes in the molds responsible for [[lipolysis]] and [[proteolysis]] are more active and can continue to ferment the cheese because they are optimal at a pH of 6.0.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gilliot|last2=Jany|last3=Poirier|last4=Maillard|last5=Debaets|last6=Thierry|last7=Coton|last8=Coton|title=Functional diversity within the Penicillium roqueforti species|journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology|date=2017|volume=241|issue=1|pages=141\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.ijfoodmicro.2016.10.001|pmid=27771579}}</ref>\n\n''Penicillium roqueforti'' creates the characteristic blue veins in blue cheese after the aged curds have been pierced, forming air tunnels in the cheese. When given oxygen, the mold is able to grow along the surface of the curd-air interface.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fernandez-salguero|title=INTERNAL MOULD - RIPENED CHEESES: CHARACTERISTICS, COMPOSITION AND PROTEOLYSIS OF THE MAIN EUROPEAN BLUE VEIN VARIETIES|journal=Italian Journal of Food Science|date=2004|volume=16|issue=4}}</ref> The veins along the blue cheese are also responsible for the aroma of blue cheese itself. In fact, one type of bacteria in blue cheese, Brevibacterium linens, is the same bacteria responsible for foot and body odor. B. linens was previously thought to give cheeses their distinct orangish pigmentation, but studies show this not to be the case and blue cheese is an example of the lack of that orange pigmentation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wolfe |first1=Benjamin |title=digesting the science of fermented foods |url=http://microbialfoods.org/beyond-b-linens-how-cheese-rinds-get-their-color/ |website=microbialfoods.org |accessdate=2014-07-27}}</ref> In pressing the cheese, the curds are not tightly packed in order to allow for air gaps between them. After piercing, the mold can also grow in between the curds.\n[[File:Blue cheese plates.jpg|thumb|Blue cheese platter]]\n=== Flavor ===\n\nA portion of the distinct flavor comes from lipolysis (the breakdown of fat). The metabolism of the blue mold further breaks down fatty acids to form ketones to give blue cheese a richer flavor and aroma.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Polowsky |first1=Pat |title=Blue |url=https://www.cheesescience.org/blue.html |website=cheesescience.org}}</ref>\n\n== Regulation ==\n=== European Union ===\nIn the [[European Union]], many blue cheeses, such as [[Cabrales cheese|Cabrales]], [[Danish Blue Cheese|Danablu]], [[Gorgonzola]], [[Roquefort]] and [[Stilton cheese|Blue Stilton]], carry a [[protected designation of origin]], meaning they can bear the name only if they have been made in a particular region. Similarly, individual countries have protections of their own such as France's [[Appellation d'Origine Contr\u00f4l\u00e9e]] and Italy's [[Denominazione di Origine Protetta]]. Blue cheeses with no protected origin name are designated simply \"blue cheese\".\n\n=== Canada ===\n\nUnder the regulation of the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]], it requires manufacturers to produce blue cheese with a 47 maximum percentage of moisture and 27 percent minimum percentage of milk fat.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/c.r.c.,_c._870/page-45.html#docCont|title=Consolidated federal laws of canada, Food and Drug Regulations|last=Branch|first=Legislative Services|date=2019-06-17|website=laws-lois.justice.gc.ca|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Salt is allowed to be used as a preservative; however, the amount of the salt or combination of salts shall not exceed 200 parts per million of the milk and milk products used to make the cheese.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other than that the regulation of Canadian Food Inspection Agency does not limit producers to use bacterial cultures to aid further ripening and&nbsp;flavoring preparations other than cheese flavoring.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Properties ==\nGorgonzola, Stilton, and Roquefort are considered to be favored blue cheeses in many countries.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Companion to Food (3 ed.)|last=Davidson|first=Alan|last2=Jaine|first2=Tom|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780199677337|location=|pages=}}</ref> These cheeses all have a [[Geographical indications and traditional specialities in the European Union|protected designation of origin]] in which they may only be called their respective name if produced a certain way in a certain location.\n\n=== Gorgonzola ===\n{{Main|Gorgonzola}}\n\nGorgonzola blue cheese takes its name from the village of [[Gorgonzola, Milan|Gorgonzola]] in Italy where it was first made.<ref name=\":0\" /> Belonging to the family of [[Stracchino]] cheeses, Gorgonzola is a whole milk, white, and \"uncooked\" cheese.<ref name=\":0\" /> This blue cheese has been inoculated with ''[[Penicillium glaucum]]'' which, during ripening, produces the characteristic of blue-green veins.<ref name=\":0\" /> The odor of Gorgonzola varies between natural and creamy Gorgonzola cheese.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Addeo|first=Francesco|last2=Piombino|first2=Paola|last3=Moio|first3=Luigi|date=May 2000|title=Odour-impact compounds of Gorgonzola cheese|journal=Journal of Dairy Research|volume=67|issue=2|pages=273\u2013285|doi=10.1017/S0022029900004106|pmid=10840681|issn=1469-7629}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moio |first1=Luigi |last2=Piombino |first2=Paola |last3=Addeo |first3=Francesco |title=Odour-impact compounds of Gorgonzola cheese |journal=Journal of Dairy Research |date=1 May 2000 |volume=67 |issue=2 |pages=273\u2013285 |doi=10.1017/S0022029900004106 |pmid=10840681 }}</ref> 63 components in natural Gorgonzola cheese and 52 components in creamy Gorgonzola cheese contribute to odor with 2-[[nonanone]], [[1-Octen-3-ol|1-octen-3-ol]], [[2-Heptanol|2-heptanol]], [[ethyl hexanoate]], [[methylanisole]] and [[2-Heptanone|2-heptanone]] being the prominent compounds for odor in both cheeses.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monti |first1=Lucia |last2=Pelizzola |first2=Valeria |last3=Povolo |first3=Milena |last4=Fontana |first4=Stefano |last5=Contarini |first5=Giovanna |title=Study on the sugar content of blue-veined 'Gorgonzola' PDO cheese |journal=International Dairy Journal |date=August 2019 |volume=95 |pages=1\u20135 |doi=10.1016/j.idairyj.2019.03.009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Stilton ===\n{{Main|Stilton cheese}}\n[[File:Homemade Stilton Blue Cheese in UK.jpg|thumb|Stilton blue cheese]]\nStilton blue cheese had been first produced in the village of [[Stilton]] in England. Different from [[Stichelton]], which is made from raw milk, Stilton cheese is made from [[Pasteurization|pasteurized milk]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition to being inoculated with ''[[Penicillium roqueforti]]'' to give it the blue vein characteristic, research has shown that other microbiota which are relatives of ''[[Lactococcus lactis]]'', ''[[Enterococcus faecalis]]'', ''[[Lactobacillus plantarum]]'', ''[https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/lactobacillus-curvatus Lactobacillus curvatus]'', ''[[Leuconostoc mesenteroides]]'', ''[[Staphylococcus equorum]]'', and [[Staphylococcus|''Staphylococcus'' sp]]. can also be found in Stilton cheese.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ercolini |first1=D. |last2=Hill |first2=P. J. |last3=Dodd |first3=C. E. R. |title=Bacterial Community Structure and Location in Stilton Cheese |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |date=1 June 2003 |volume=69 |issue=6 |pages=3540\u20133548 |doi=10.1128/AEM.69.6.3540-3548.2003 |pmid=12788761 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Some important microbiota contribute to the aromatic profile such as those of the ''[[Lactobacillus]]'' genus due to their production of [[Volatile organic compound|volatile compounds]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mugampoza |first1=Diriisa |last2=Gkatzionis |first2=Konstantinos |last3=Linforth |first3=Robert S.T. |last4=Dodd |first4=Christine E.R. |title=Acid production, growth kinetics and aroma profiles of Lactobacillus flora from Stilton cheese |journal=Food Chemistry |date=July 2019 |volume=287 |pages=222\u2013231 |doi=10.1016/j.foodchem.2019.02.082 |pmid=30857693 }}</ref> During ripening, [[Fatty acid|free fatty acids]] increase in amount which contribute to the characteristic flavor of blue cheeses due to [[Lipolysis|fat breakdown]] by ''Penicillium roqueforti''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Madkor |first1=S. |last2=Fox |first2=P.F. |last3=Shalabi |first3=S.I. |last4=Metwalli |first4=N.H. |title=Studies on the ripening of stilton cheese: Lipolysis |journal=Food Chemistry |date=January 1987 |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=93\u2013109 |doi=10.1016/0308-8146(87)90058-6 }}</ref>\n\n=== Roquefort ===\n{{Main|Roquefort}}\n[[File:Wikicheese - Roquefort - 20150417 - 003.jpg|thumb|Roquefort cheese]]\nRoquefort blue cheese originates from the village of [[Roquefort-sur-Soulzon]], France.<ref name=\":0\" /> Its flavors come from the use of unpasteurized [[Sheep milk|sheep's milk]], inoculation with ''Penicillium roqueforti'', and the special conditions of the natural caves of Roquefort-sur-Soulzon in which they are ripened.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Penicillium roqueforti'' is the cause of the blue veins in Roquefort cheese. In addition to ''Penicillium roqueforti'', various yeasts are present, namely ''[[Debaryomyces hansenii]]'' and its non-sporulating form ''[[Candida (fungus)|Candida famata]]'', and ''[[Kluyveromyces lactis]]'' and its non-sporulating form ''Candida sphaerica.''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Besan\u00e7on |first1=X. |last2=Smet |first2=C. |last3=Chabalier |first3=C. |last4=Rivemale |first4=M. |last5=Reverbel |first5=J.P. |last6=Ratomahenina |first6=R. |last7=Galzy |first7=P. |title=Study of surface yeast flora of Roquefort cheese |journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology |date=September 1992 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201318 |doi=10.1016/0168-1605(92)90014-T |pmid=1476870 }}</ref> Similarly to other kinds of blue cheeses, Roquefort's flavor and odor can be attributed to the particular mixture of methyl ketones such as 2-heptanone, [[2-Pentanone|2-pentanone]], and 2-nonanone.<ref name=\"The Methyl Ketones of Blue Cheese a\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of blue cheeses]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Blue cheese}}\n\n{{Cheese}}\n{{Blue cheeses}}\n\n[[Category:Blue cheeses| ]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_cheese"}
