mer Paralympics|2012]], [[Boccia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|2016]]), heart failure.<ref>[https://globoesporte.globo.com/paralimpiadas/noticia/aos-39-anos-morre-dirceu-pinto-bicampeao-paralimpico-de-bocha.ghtml Aos 39 anos, morre Dirceu Pinto, dono de quatro ouros paral\u00edmpicos na bocha] {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n*[[Bucky Pizzarelli]], 94, American jazz guitarist, COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/04/bucky-pizzarelli-nj-jazz-legend-dead-at-94-from-coronavirus.html Bucky Pizzarelli, N.J. jazz legend, dead at 94 from coronavirus]</ref>\n*[[Dieter Reith]], 82, German pianist and organist.<ref>[http://www.dieter-reith.de/ Dieter Reith Musikproduktion] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n*[[Harold Rubin]], 87, South African-born Israeli jazz clarinettist.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.co.il/gallery/music/.premium-1.8731941 \u05de\u05ea \u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3 \u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05df, \u05de\u05d7\u05dc\u05d5\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2'\u05d6 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d5\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc] {{in lang|he}}</ref>\n*[[Gerardo Ruiz Esparza]], 70, Mexican politician, [[Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (Mexico)|Secretary of Communications and Transportation]] (2012\u20132018), stroke.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Fallece-Ruiz-Esparza-ex-secretario-de-Comunicaciones-y-Transportes-20200401-0119.html Ruiz Esparza, former Secretary of Communications and Transportation, dies] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Adam Schlesinger]], 52, American musician ([[Fountains of Wayne]], [[Ivy (band)|Ivy]]) and songwriter (\"[[That Thing You Do (song)|That Thing You Do]]\"), [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics|Emmy]] winner ([[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012]], [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards|2013]], [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019]]), COVID-19.<ref>[https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-dead-dies-1203552130/ Adam Schlesinger Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 52]</ref>\n*[[John Tydeman]], 84, English radio producer and theatre director.<ref>[http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/240733/tydeman Tydeman]</ref>\n*[[Dora Werzberg]], 99, French nurse and social worker.<ref>[https://hac.bard.edu/amor-mundi/in-memoriam-dora-amelan-2020-04-03 In Memoriam: Dora Amelan]</ref>\n*[[Mahmoud Zakzouk]], 86, Egyptian academic and politician, [[Ministry of Awqaf (Egypt)|Minister of Awqaf]] (1995\u20132011).<ref>[https://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/1722773 \u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a \u0632\u0642\u0632\u0648\u0642 \u0648\u0632\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0628\u0642 \u0639\u0646 87 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u064b\u0627] {{in lang|ar}}</ref>\n\n==Previous months==\n*[[Deaths in January 2020]]\n*[[Deaths in February 2020]]\n*[[Deaths in March 2020]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of deaths due to coronavirus disease 2019]]\n*[[Lists of deaths by year]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/tone/obituaries ''The Guardian'', UK obituaries]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/ ''The Telegraph'' obituaries]\n*[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/obituaries/ Obituaries, ''Chicago Tribune'']\n*[https://latimes.com/news/obituaries/ Obituaries, ''Los Angeles Times'']\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/pages/obituaries/index.html ''The New York Times'', US obituaries]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/obituaries/ ''The Washington Post'' obituaries]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/obituaries ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', Australian obituaries]\n\n{{Navbox deaths}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020, Deaths in}}\n[[Category:2020 deaths| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of deaths in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Refsworldlee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2:-space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deaths_in_2020"}
{"title_page": "Acorn", "text_new": "{{For|the squash|Acorn squash}}{{Other uses}}\n[[Image:Acorns small to large.jpg|thumb|Acorns from small to large of the Willow Oak, ''Quercus phellos'' (very small, at center); the Southern Red Oak, ''Quercus falcata''; the White Oak, ''Quercus alba''; the Scarlet Oak, ''Quercus coccinea''; from southern Greenville County, SC, USA. Scale bar at upper right is 1&nbsp;cm.]]\n[[File:Acorn diagram.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the anatomy of an acorn: A.) [[Calybium and cupule|Cupule]] B.) [[Pericarp]] (fruit wall) C.) Seed coat ([[Testa (botany)|testa]]) D.) [[Cotyledons]] (2) E.) [[Plumule]] F.) [[Radicle]] G.) Remains of [[Gynoecium|style]]. Together D., E., and F. make up the embryo.]]\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Acorn, raw\n| water=27.9 g\n| kJ=1619\n| protein=6.15 g\n| fat=23.85 g\n| satfat=3.102 g\n| monofat = 15.109 g\n| polyfat = 4.596 g\n| carbs=40.75 g\n| calcium_mg=41\n| copper_mg = .621\n| iron_mg=0.79\n| magnesium_mg=62\n| phosphorus_mg=79\n| potassium_mg=539\n| sodium_mg=0\n| manganese_mg=1.337\n| zinc_mg=0.51\n| vitC_mg=0.0\n| thiamin_mg=0.112\n| riboflavin_mg=0.118\n| niacin_mg=1.827\n| pantothenic_mg=0.715\n| vitB6_mg=0.528\n| folate_ug=87\n| vitA_ug=2\n| vitA_IU=39\n| retinol_ug=0\n<!-- amino acids -->\n| tryptophan=0.074 g\n| threonine=0.236 g\n| isoleucine=0.285 g\n| leucine=0.489 g\n| lysine=0.384 g\n| methionine=0.103 g\n| cystine=0.109 g\n| phenylalanine=0.269 g\n| tyrosine=0.187 g\n| valine=0.345 g\n| arginine=0.473 g\n| histidine=0.170 g\n| alanine=0.350 g\n| aspartic acid=0.635 g\n| glutamic acid=0.986 g\n| glycine=0.285 g\n| proline=0.246 g\n| serine=0.261 g\n| right=1\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=12058&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nThe '''acorn''', or '''oaknut''', is the [[nut (fruit)|nut]] of the [[oak]]s and their close relatives (genera ''[[Quercus]]'' and ''[[Lithocarpus]]'', in the family [[Fagaceae]]). It usually contains a single [[seed]] (occasionally two seeds), enclosed in a tough, leathery [[Nutshell|shell]], and borne in a cup-shaped [[Calybium|cupule]]. Acorns are {{convert|1\u20136|cm|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|0.8\u20134|cm|abbr=on}} broad. Acorns take between 6 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see  [[List of Quercus species|the list of Quercus species]] for details of oak classification, in which acorn [[morphology (biology)|morphology]] and [[phenology]] are important factors.\n\n==Ecological role==\nAcorns play an important role in [[forest ecology]] when oaks are the dominant species or are plentiful.<ref name=USDA>{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=1 to 368|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.|asin=B000PMY1P8}}</ref> The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=After Lean Acorn Crop in Northeast, Even People May Feel the Effects|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/03/nyregion/boom-and-bust-in-acorns-will-affect-many-creatures-including-humans.html|accessdate=4 December 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 December 2011|author=King, Richie S. |quote=there is nothing unusual about large fluctuations in the annual number of acorns.}}</ref> Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed [[mast (botany)|mast]].\n\nWildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as [[jay]]s, [[pigeon]]s, some [[duck]]s, and several species of [[woodpecker]]s. Small [[mammal]]s that feed on acorns include [[mouse|mice]], [[squirrel]]s and several other [[rodent]]s.\n\n[[File:Ponies eating acorns on Parkhill Lawn, New Forest - geograph.org.uk - 251840.jpg|thumb|220px|right|[[Pony|Ponies]] eating acorns.  Acorns can cause painful death in equines, especially if eaten to excess.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horsetalk.co.nz/2013/11/23/acorns-fatally-poison-50-ponies-english-forest/#axzz40efTYqgN |title=Acorns fatally poison 50 ponies in English forest |publisher=Horsetalk.co.nz |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.horse-advice.com/equestrian/equine-veterinary/acorns-poisonous.shtml |title=ACORN POISONING \u2013 Are Acorns Poisonous To Horses? |publisher=Horse-advice.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewayofhorses.com/10_08_acorns.html |title=Acorns, Oaks and Horses: Tannin Poisoning |publisher=The Way of Horses |date=2002-09-15 |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>]]\nLarge mammals such as pigs, bears, and [[deer]] also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.<ref>{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=276\u2013291|chapter=Mammals of California Oak Habitats-Management Implications|author= Barrett, Reginald H. |chapter-url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.}}</ref> In Spain, Portugal and the [[New Forest]] region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in ''[[Dehesa (pastoral management)|dehesas]]'' (large oak [[grove (nature)|grove]]s) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns. Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their [[tannins]], such as horses and cattle.<ref>{{cite web|title=A bumper crop of acorns causes concern for those with horses|url=http://www.countryfile.com/news/bumper-crop-acorns-causes-concern-those-horses|website=Countryfile.com|publisher=Immediate Media Company|date=19 October 2011|accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Barringer\">{{cite web|title=Acorns Can be Deadly |url=http://www.caf.wvu.edu/~forage/acorns/acorns.htm |work=West Virginia University Extension Service |first=Sam |last=Barringer |accessdate=27 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227141549/http://www.caf.wvu.edu/~forage/acorns/acorns.htm |archivedate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[larva]]e of some [[moth]]s and [[weevil]]s also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.<ref>Brown, Leland R. (1979) ''Insects Feeding on California Oak Trees''in ''Proceedings of the Symposium on Multiple-Use Management of California's Hardwood Resources'', Timothy Plum and Norman Pillsbury (eds.).</ref>\n\nAcorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached. Acorns are also rich in nutrients. Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of [[protein]], [[carbohydrate]]s and [[fat]]s, as well as the minerals [[calcium]], [[phosphorus]] and [[potassium]], and the [[vitamin]] [[niacin]]. Total [[food energy]] in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s02dn.html |title=Nutrition Facts for Acorn Flour |publisher=Nutritiondata.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>\n\nAcorns also contain bitter [[tannin]]s, the amount varying with the species. Since tannins, which are plant [[polyphenol]]s, interfere with an animal's ability to [[metabolize]] protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain. Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins. When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause [[ulceration]] and [[kidney]] failure.<ref name=\"Barringer\"/>\n\nAnimals that [[cache (biology)|cache]] acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has [[percolate]]d through them to [[Leaching (chemical science)|leach]] out the tannins. Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods. Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.\n\nSpecies of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, [[astringent]], and potentially irritating if eaten raw. This is particularly true of the acorns of American [[Quercus rubra|red oaks]] and [[Pedunculate oak|English oaks]]. The acorns of [[white oak]]s, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.\n\nTannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown. Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A practical guide to edible & useful plants : including recipes, harmful plants, natural dyes & textile fibers|last=1950-|first=Tull, Delena|date=1987|publisher=Texas Monthly Press|isbn=9780877190226|location=Austin, Tex.|oclc=15015652}}</ref> Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself. For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thespruce.com/cold-leaching-and-preserving-acorn-flour-4007438|title=Two Ways to Make Cold Leached Acorn Flour - Learn How with this Guide|work=The Spruce|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nBeing rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or [[mold]]er easily and must be carefully stored. Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.\n\nAcorns of the white oak group, ''Leucobalanus'', typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.\n\n===Dispersal agents===\n[[File:Quercus robur - sprouting acorn.jpg|thumb|left|Sprouting acorn of ''[[Quercus robur]]''.]]\n\nAcorns are too heavy for [[wind dispersal]], so they require other ways to spread. Oaks therefore depend on [[Biological dispersal|biological seed dispersal]] agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of {{convert|20\u201330|m|abbr=on}} from the parent tree{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}.\n\nMany animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as [[squirrels]] and [[jays]] serve as seed dispersal agents. Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.\n\nEven though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to consume them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores. A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.\n\nScatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle. The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.\n\nAcorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family. Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible [[lignin]]s that form the root.<ref>{{citation|last=Janzen|first= Daniel H. |year=1971|title=Seed Predation by Animals|journal=Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics|editor=Richard F. Johnson, Peter W. Frank and Charles Michner|jstor= 2096937|doi=10.1146/annurev.es.02.110171.002341|volume=2|pages= 465\u2013492 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nIn some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary [[Staple food|staple]], though they have largely been replaced by [[Food grain|grain]]s and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.\n\nSeveral cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nativetech.org/recipes/recipe.php?recipeid=115 |title=Indigenous Food and Traditional Recipes |publisher=NativeTech |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siouxme.com/acorn.html |title=Cooking With Acorns |publisher=Siouxme.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>\n\n===As food===\n\nAcorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.<ref>{{citation |first=D. A. |last=Bainbridge |title=Use of acorns for food in California: past, present and future |publisher=Symposium on Multiple-use Management of California's Hardwoods |date=12\u201314 November 1986 |location=San Luis Obispo, CA. |url=http://www.ecocomposite.org/native/UseOfAcornsForFoodInCalifornia.doc |access-date=1 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027113825/http://ecocomposite.org/native/UseOfAcornsForFoodInCalifornia.doc |archive-date=27 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For instance, the [[Ancient Greek cuisine|Ancient Greek]] lower classes and the Japanese (during the [[J\u014dmon]] period)<ref name=\"HabuJunko2004\">{{cite book|author1=Junko Habu|author2=Habu Junko|title=Ancient Jomon of Japan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=vGnAbTyTynsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=acorns&f=false|date=29 July 2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-77670-7}}</ref> would eat acorns, especially in times of famine.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} In ancient [[Iberia]] they were a staple food, according to [[Strabo]]. Despite this history, acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts. However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter [[tannin]]s in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours. In antiquity, [[Pliny the Elder]] noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.<ref name=\"Met\">{{cite web|last1=Alphonso|first1=Christina|title=Acres of Acorns|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/blogs/in-season/2015/acres-of-acorns|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|accessdate=15 April 2017|date=5 November 2015}}</ref> Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns. Varieties preferred by American Indians such as ''[[Quercus kelloggii#Uses|Quercus kelloggii]]'' (California black oak) may be easier to prepare or more palatable.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Acorns-Food for Modern Man|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=360\u2013361|author= Derby, Jeanine A. |chapter-url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea, an edible jelly named ''[[dotorimuk]]'' is made from acorns, and ''[[dotori guksu]]'' are Korean noodles made from acorn flour or starch. In the 17th century, a juice extracted from acorns was administered to habitual drunkards to cure them of their condition or else to give them the strength to resist another bout of drinking.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nAcorns have frequently been used as a [[coffee substitute]], particularly when [[coffee]] was unavailable or rationed. The [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]] in the [[American Civil War]] and [[Germany|Germans]] during [[World War II]] (when it was called ''[[Ersatz]]'' coffee), which were cut off from coffee supplies by [[Union blockade|Union]] and Allied [[blockade]]s respectively, are particularly notable past instances of this use of acorns.\n\n===Use by Native Americans===\n[[File:Acorn mortar holes friant ca.jpg|thumb|Mortar holes for pounding acorns into flour, [[Lost Lake, California]]]]\nAcorns were a traditional food of many [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] peoples of North America, and served an especially important role for [[Indigenous peoples of California|Californian Native Americans]], where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.<ref>{{Citation|doi=10.1525/aa.1964.66.3.02a00360|title= (Review of) Ecological Determinants of Aboriginal California Populations, by Martin A. Baumhoff|year=1964|last1=Suttles|first1=Wayne|journal=American Anthropologist|volume=66|issue=3|pages=676 <!-- note that this article is a review of the Baumhoff article -->}}</ref> One ecology researcher of [[Yurok people|Yurok]] and [[Karuk people|Karuk]] heritage reports that \"his traditional acorn preparation is a simple soup, cooked with hot stones directly in a basket,\" and says he enjoys acorns eaten with \"grilled [[salmon]], [[Huckleberry|huckleberries]] or [[seaweed]].\"<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Prichep\n| first = Deena\n| title = Nutritious Acorns Don't Have To Just Be Snacks For Squirrels\n| work = The Salt : NPR\n| accessdate = 2014-11-03\n| date = 2014-11-02\n| url = https://www.npr.org/blogs/thesalt/2014/10/24/358527018/nutritious-acorns-dont-have-to-just-be-snacks-for-squirrels\n}}</ref>\nUnlike many other plant foods, acorns do not need to be eaten or processed right away, but may be stored for a long time, much as [[squirrels]] do. In years that oaks produced many acorns, Native Americans sometimes collected enough acorns to store for two years as insurance against poor acorn production years.\n\nAfter drying them in the sun to discourage [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] and [[germination]], women took acorns back to their villages and cached them in hollow trees or structures on poles, to keep them safe from mice and squirrels. The stored acorns could then be used when needed, particularly during the winter when other resources were scarce. Those acorns that germinated in the fall were shelled and pulverized before those that germinate in spring. Because of their high fat content, stored acorns can become rancid. Molds may also grow on them.\n\nThe lighting of ground fires killed the larvae of [[Blastobasis glandulella|acorn moth]]s and [[acorn weevil]]s by burning them during their dormancy period in the soil.  The pests can infest and consume more than 95% of an oak's acorns. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nFires also released the nutrients bound in dead leaves and other plant debris into the soil, thus fertilizing oak trees while clearing the ground to make acorn collection easier. Most North American oaks tolerate light fires, especially when consistent burning has eliminated woody fuel accumulation around their trunks. Consistent burning encouraged oak growth at the expense of other trees less tolerant of fire, thus keeping oaks dominant in the landscapes. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nOaks produce more acorns when they are not too close to other oaks and thus competing with them for sunlight, water and soil nutrients. The fires tended to eliminate the more vulnerable young oaks and leave old oaks which created open [[oak savanna]]s with trees ideally spaced to maximize acorn production.\n\n===In culture===\n====Art====\nA [[Motif (art)|motif]] in [[Roman architecture]], also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an [[Ornament (architecture)|ornament]] on [[cutlery]], furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on [[finial]]s at [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n====Contemporary use as symbol====\nThe acorn is the symbol for the [[National Trails]] of [[England and Wales]], and is used for the [[waymarking|waymarks]] on these paths.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Trail Acorn|url=http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/hadrianswall/publications.asp?PageId=276|work=National Trails|accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the [[University of Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Connecticut|url=http://uconn.edu/|accessdate=5 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101104073123/http://www.uconn.edu/| archivedate= 4 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAcorns are also used as [[Charge (heraldry)|charges]] in [[heraldry]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''acorn'' (earlier ''akerne'', and ''acharn'') is related to the [[gothic language|Gothic]] name ''akran'', which had the sense of \"fruit of the unenclosed land\".<ref>{{OEtymD|acorn}}</ref> The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak. [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]] spoke of \"achornes of okes\" in the 14th century. By degrees, popular [[etymology]] connected the word both with \"corn\" and \"oak-horn\", and the spelling changed accordingly.<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Acorn|volume=1|pages=152\u2013153}} This cites the ''New English Dictionary'', now the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''</ref>  The current spelling (emerged 15c.-16c.), derives from association with ''ac'' (Old English: \"oak\") + ''corn''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Online Etymology Dictionary|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=acorn&searchmode=none|website=www.etymonline.com|accessdate=15 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\n1410EcudQ.svg|Acorn in heraldry\nAcorn Britain National Trails Symbol.svg|Acorn waymark for [[National Trails]]\nPeacePalaceSculpture-Acorns-24042014.jpg|Copper acorns at the [[Peace Palace]], The Hague.\nPhotograph with text showing a Chuckachancy woman preparing acorns for grinding, California. This is from a survey... - NARA - 296297 (cropped).jpg|[[Yokuts people|Chuckachancy]] women pause in their work preparing acorns for grinding, California, ca. 1920\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Knopper gall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links and further reading==\n{{Commons|Acorns}}\n* [http://www.nativetech.org/recipes/recipe.php?recipeid=115 Nupa Acorn Soup] (Miwokan recipe)\n* [http://www.siouxme.com/acorn.html Cooking With Acorns: A Major North American Indian Food]\n* {{cite web |first=Terry |last=Krautwurst |date=September\u2013October 1988 |title=A Fall Field Guide Nuts |url=http://www.motherearthnews.com/Nature-Community/1988-09-01/A-Fall-Field-Guide-to-Nuts.aspx |work=[[Mother Earth News]] |accessdate=20 October 2009}}\n* Julia F. Parker and Beverly R. Ortiz, ''It Will Live Forever: Traditional Yosemite Indian Acorn Preparation'', Heyday Books, 2nd revised edition (1 September 1996), trade paperback, 160 pages, {{ISBN|0-930588-45-2}}, {{ISBN|978-0-930588-45-8}}\n* ''[http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, 26\u201328 June]'' USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044, Berkeley, California, 1980, edited by Timothy R. Plumb, 368 pages\n\n{{Nuts}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Quercus]]\n[[Category:Edible nuts and seeds]]\n[[Category:Ornaments]]\n[[Category:Plants used in Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Post-Columbian Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Heraldic charges]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the squash|Acorn squash}}{{Other uses}}\n[[Image:Acorns small to large.jpg|thumb|Acorns from small to large of the Willow Oak, ''Quercus phellos'' (very small, at center); the Southern Red Oak, ''Quercus falcata''; the White Oak, ''Quercus alba''; the Scarlet Oak, ''Quercus coccinea''; from southern Greenville County, SC, USA. Scale bar at upper right is 1&nbsp;cm.]]\n[[File:Acorn diagram.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the anatomy of an acorn: A.) [[Calybium and cupule|Cupule]] B.) [[Pericarp]] (fruit wall) C.) Seed coat ([[Testa (botany)|testa]]) D.) [[Cotyledons]] (2) E.) [[Plumule]] F.) [[Radicle]] G.) Remains of [[Gynoecium|style]]. Together D., E., and F. make up the embryo.]]\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Acorn, raw\n| water=27.9 g\n| kJ=1619\n| protein=6.15 g\n| fat=23.85 g\n| satfat=3.102 g\n| monofat = 15.109 g\n| polyfat = 4.596 g\n| carbs=40.75 g\n| calcium_mg=41\n| copper_mg = .621\n| iron_mg=0.79\n| magnesium_mg=62\n| phosphorus_mg=79\n| potassium_mg=539\n| sodium_mg=0\n| manganese_mg=1.337\n| zinc_mg=0.51\n| vitC_mg=0.0\n| thiamin_mg=0.112\n| riboflavin_mg=0.118\n| niacin_mg=1.827\n| pantothenic_mg=0.715\n| vitB6_mg=0.528\n| folate_ug=87\n| vitA_ug=2\n| vitA_IU=39\n| retinol_ug=0\n<!-- amino acids -->\n| tryptophan=0.074 g\n| threonine=0.236 g\n| isoleucine=0.285 g\n| leucine=0.489 g\n| lysine=0.384 g\n| methionine=0.103 g\n| cystine=0.109 g\n| phenylalanine=0.269 g\n| tyrosine=0.187 g\n| valine=0.345 g\n| arginine=0.473 g\n| histidine=0.170 g\n| alanine=0.350 g\n| aspartic acid=0.635 g\n| glutamic acid=0.986 g\n| glycine=0.285 g\n| proline=0.246 g\n| serine=0.261 g\n| right=1\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=12058&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nThe '''acorn''', or '''oaknut''', is the [[nut (fruit)|nut]] of the [[oak]]s and their close relatives (genera ''[[Quercus]]'' and ''[[Lithocarpus]]'', in the family [[Fagaceae]]). It usually contains a single [[seed]] (occasionally two seeds), enclosed in a tough, leathery [[Nutshell|shell]], and borne in a cup-shaped [[Calybium|cupule]]. Acorns are {{convert|1\u20136|cm|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|0.8\u20134|cm|abbr=on}} broad. Acorns take between 6 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see  [[List of Quercus species|the list of Quercus species]] for details of oak classification, in which acorn [[morphology (biology)|morphology]] and [[phenology]] are important factors.\n\n==Ecological role==\nAcorns play an important role in [[forest ecology]] when oaks are the dominant species or are plentiful.<ref name=USDA>{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=1 to 368|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.|asin=B000PMY1P8}}</ref> The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=After Lean Acorn Crop in Northeast, Even People May Feel the Effects|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/03/nyregion/boom-and-bust-in-acorns-will-affect-many-creatures-including-humans.html|accessdate=4 December 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 December 2011|author=King, Richie S. |quote=there is nothing unusual about large fluctuations in the annual number of acorns.}}</ref> Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed [[mast (botany)|mast]].\n\nWildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as [[jay]]s, [[pigeon]]s, some [[duck]]s, and several species of [[woodpecker]]s. Small [[mammal]]s that feed on acorns include [[mouse|mice]], [[squirrel]]s and several other [[rodent]]s.\n\n[[File:Ponies eating acorns on Parkhill Lawn, New Forest - geograph.org.uk - 251840.jpg|thumb|220px|right|[[Pony|Ponies]] eating acorns.  Acorns can cause painful death in equines, especially if eaten to excess.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horsetalk.co.nz/2013/11/23/acorns-fatally-poison-50-ponies-english-forest/#axzz40efTYqgN |title=Acorns fatally poison 50 ponies in English forest |publisher=Horsetalk.co.nz |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.horse-advice.com/equestrian/equine-veterinary/acorns-poisonous.shtml |title=ACORN POISONING \u2013 Are Acorns Poisonous To Horses? |publisher=Horse-advice.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewayofhorses.com/10_08_acorns.html |title=Acorns, Oaks and Horses: Tannin Poisoning |publisher=The Way of Horses |date=2002-09-15 |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>]]\nLarge mammals such as pigs, bears, and [[deer]] also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.<ref>{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=276\u2013291|chapter=Mammals of California Oak Habitats-Management Implications|author= Barrett, Reginald H. |chapter-url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.}}</ref> In Spain, Portugal and the [[New Forest]] region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in ''[[Dehesa (pastoral management)|dehesas]]'' (large oak [[grove (nature)|grove]]s) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns. Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their [[tannins]], such as horses and cattle.<ref>{{cite web|title=A bumper crop of acorns causes concern for those with horses|url=http://www.countryfile.com/news/bumper-crop-acorns-causes-concern-those-horses|website=Countryfile.com|publisher=Immediate Media Company|date=19 October 2011|accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Barringer\">{{cite web|title=Acorns Can be Deadly |url=http://www.caf.wvu.edu/~forage/acorns/acorns.htm |work=West Virginia University Extension Service |first=Sam |last=Barringer |accessdate=27 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227141549/http://www.caf.wvu.edu/~forage/acorns/acorns.htm |archivedate=27 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[larva]]e of some [[moth]]s and [[weevil]]s also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.<ref>Brown, Leland R. (1979) ''Insects Feeding on California Oak Trees''in ''Proceedings of the Symposium on Multiple-Use Management of California's Hardwood Resources'', Timothy Plum and Norman Pillsbury (eds.).</ref>\n\nAcorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached. Acorns are also rich in nutrients. Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of [[protein]], [[carbohydrate]]s and [[fat]]s, as well as the minerals [[calcium]], [[phosphorus]] and [[potassium]], and the [[vitamin]] [[niacin]]. Total [[food energy]] in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s02dn.html |title=Nutrition Facts for Acorn Flour |publisher=Nutritiondata.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>\n\nAcorns also contain bitter [[tannin]]s, the amount varying with the species. Since tannins, which are plant [[polyphenol]]s, interfere with an animal's ability to [[metabolize]] protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain. Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins. When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause [[ulceration]] and [[kidney]] failure.<ref name=\"Barringer\"/>\n\nAnimals that [[cache (biology)|cache]] acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has [[percolate]]d through them to [[Leaching (chemical science)|leach]] out the tannins. Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods. Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.\n\nSpecies of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, [[astringent]], and potentially irritating if eaten raw. This is particularly true of the acorns of American [[Quercus rubra|red oaks]] and [[Pedunculate oak|English oaks]]. The acorns of [[white oak]]s, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.\n\nTannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown. Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A practical guide to edible & useful plants : including recipes, harmful plants, natural dyes & textile fibers|last=1950-|first=Tull, Delena|date=1987|publisher=Texas Monthly Press|isbn=9780877190226|location=Austin, Tex.|oclc=15015652}}</ref> Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself. For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thespruce.com/cold-leaching-and-preserving-acorn-flour-4007438|title=Two Ways to Make Cold Leached Acorn Flour - Learn How with this Guide|work=The Spruce|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nBeing rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or [[mold]]er easily and must be carefully stored. Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.\n\nAcorns of the white oak group, ''Leucobalanus'', typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.\n\n===Dispersal agents===\n[[File:Quercus robur - sprouting acorn.jpg|thumb|left|Sprouting acorn of ''[[Quercus robur]]''.]]\n\nAcorns are too heavy for [[wind dispersal]], so they require other ways to spread. Oaks therefore depend on [[Biological dispersal|biological seed dispersal]] agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of {{convert|20\u201330|m|abbr=on}} from the parent tree{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}.\n\nMany animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as [[squirrels]] and [[jays]] serve as seed dispersal agents. Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.\n\nEven though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to consume them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores. A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.\n\nScatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle. The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.\n\nAcorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family. Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible [[lignin]]s that form the root.<ref>{{citation|last=Janzen|first= Daniel H. |year=1971|title=Seed Predation by Animals|journal=Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics|editor=Richard F. Johnson, Peter W. Frank and Charles Michner|jstor= 2096937|doi=10.1146/annurev.es.02.110171.002341|volume=2|pages= 465\u2013492 }}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nIn some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary [[Staple food|staple]], though they have largely been replaced by [[Food grain|grain]]s and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.\n\nSeveral cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nativetech.org/recipes/recipe.php?recipeid=115 |title=Indigenous Food and Traditional Recipes |publisher=NativeTech |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siouxme.com/acorn.html |title=Cooking With Acorns |publisher=Siouxme.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-06}}</ref>\n\n===As food===\n\nAcorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.<ref>{{citation |first=D. A. |last=Bainbridge |title=Use of acorns for food in California: past, present and future |publisher=Symposium on Multiple-use Management of California's Hardwoods |date=12\u201314 November 1986 |location=San Luis Obispo, CA. |url=http://www.ecocomposite.org/native/UseOfAcornsForFoodInCalifornia.doc |access-date=1 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027113825/http://ecocomposite.org/native/UseOfAcornsForFoodInCalifornia.doc |archive-date=27 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For instance, the [[Ancient Greek cuisine|Ancient Greek]] lower classes and the Japanese (during the [[J\u014dmon]] period)<ref name=\"HabuJunko2004\">{{cite book|author1=Junko Habu|author2=Habu Junko|title=Ancient Jomon of Japan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=vGnAbTyTynsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=acorns&f=false|date=29 July 2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-77670-7}}</ref> would eat acorns, especially in times of famine.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}} In ancient [[Iberia]] they were a staple food, according to [[Strabo]]. Despite this history, acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts. However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter [[tannin]]s in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours. In antiquity, [[Pliny the Elder]] noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.<ref name=\"Met\">{{cite web|last1=Alphonso|first1=Christina|title=Acres of Acorns|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/blogs/in-season/2015/acres-of-acorns|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|accessdate=15 April 2017|date=5 November 2015}}</ref> Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns. Varieties preferred by American Indians such as ''[[Quercus kelloggii#Uses|Quercus kelloggii]]'' (California black oak) may be easier to prepare or more palatable.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Acorns-Food for Modern Man|title=Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, June 26\u201328|year=1980|publisher=USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044|pages=360\u2013361|author= Derby, Jeanine A. |chapter-url=http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf|editor=Plumb, Timothy R.}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea, an edible jelly named ''[[dotorimuk]]'' is made from acorns, and ''[[dotori guksu]]'' are Korean noodles made from acorn flour or starch. In the 17th century, a juice extracted from acorns was administered to habitual drunkards to cure them of their condition or else to give them the strength to resist another bout of drinking.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nAcorns have frequently been used as a [[coffee substitute]], particularly when [[coffee]] was unavailable or rationed. The [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]] in the [[American Civil War]] and [[Germany|Germans]] during [[World War II]] (when it was called ''[[Ersatz]]'' coffee), which were cut off from coffee supplies by [[Union blockade|Union]] and Allied [[blockade]]s respectively, are particularly notable past instances of this use of acorns.\n\n===Use by Native Americans===\n[[File:Acorn mortar holes friant ca.jpg|thumb|Mortar holes for pounding acorns into flour, [[Lost Lake, California]]]]\nAcorns were a traditional food of many [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] peoples of North America, and served an especially important role for [[Indigenous peoples of California|Californian Native Americans]], where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.<ref>{{Citation|doi=10.1525/aa.1964.66.3.02a00360|title= (Review of) Ecological Determinants of Aboriginal California Populations, by Martin A. Baumhoff|year=1964|last1=Suttles|first1=Wayne|journal=American Anthropologist|volume=66|issue=3|pages=676 <!-- note that this article is a review of the Baumhoff article -->}}</ref> One ecology researcher of [[Yurok people|Yurok]] and [[Karuk people|Karuk]] heritage reports that \"his traditional acorn preparation is a simple soup, cooked with hot stones directly in a basket,\" and says he enjoys acorns eaten with \"grilled [[salmon]], [[Huckleberry|huckleberries]] or [[seaweed]].\"<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Prichep\n| first = Deena\n| title = Nutritious Acorns Don't Have To Just Be Snacks For Squirrels\n| work = The Salt : NPR\n| accessdate = 2014-11-03\n| date = 2014-11-02\n| url = https://www.npr.org/blogs/thesalt/2014/10/24/358527018/nutritious-acorns-dont-have-to-just-be-snacks-for-squirrels\n}}</ref>\nUnlike many other plant foods, acorns do not need to be eaten or processed right away, but may be stored for a long time, much as [[squirrels]] do. In years that oaks produced many acorns, Native Americans sometimes collected enough acorns to store for two years as insurance against poor acorn production years.\n\nAfter drying them in the sun to discourage [[mold]] and [[germination]], women took acorns back to their villages and cached them in hollow trees or structures on poles, to keep them safe from mice and squirrels. The stored acorns could then be used when needed, particularly during the winter when other resources were scarce. Those acorns that germinated in the fall were shelled and pulverized before those that germinate in spring. Because of their high fat content, stored acorns can become rancid. Molds may also grow on them.\n\nThe lighting of ground fires killed the larvae of [[Blastobasis glandulella|acorn moth]]s and [[acorn weevil]]s by burning them during their dormancy period in the soil.  The pests can infest and consume more than 95% of an oak's acorns. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nFires also released the nutrients bound in dead leaves and other plant debris into the soil, thus fertilizing oak trees while clearing the ground to make acorn collection easier. Most North American oaks tolerate light fires, especially when consistent burning has eliminated woody fuel accumulation around their trunks. Consistent burning encouraged oak growth at the expense of other trees less tolerant of fire, thus keeping oaks dominant in the landscapes. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nOaks produce more acorns when they are not too close to other oaks and thus competing with them for sunlight, water and soil nutrients. The fires tended to eliminate the more vulnerable young oaks and leave old oaks which created open [[oak savanna]]s with trees ideally spaced to maximize acorn production.\n\n===In culture===\n====Art====\nA [[Motif (art)|motif]] in [[Roman architecture]], also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an [[Ornament (architecture)|ornament]] on [[cutlery]], furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on [[finial]]s at [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n====Contemporary use as symbol====\nThe acorn is the symbol for the [[National Trails]] of [[England and Wales]], and is used for the [[waymarking|waymarks]] on these paths.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Trail Acorn|url=http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/hadrianswall/publications.asp?PageId=276|work=National Trails|accessdate=9 October 2010}}</ref> The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the [[University of Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Connecticut|url=http://uconn.edu/|accessdate=5 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101104073123/http://www.uconn.edu/| archivedate= 4 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAcorns are also used as [[Charge (heraldry)|charges]] in [[heraldry]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''acorn'' (earlier ''akerne'', and ''acharn'') is related to the [[gothic language|Gothic]] name ''akran'', which had the sense of \"fruit of the unenclosed land\".<ref>{{OEtymD|acorn}}</ref> The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak. [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]] spoke of \"achornes of okes\" in the 14th century. By degrees, popular [[etymology]] connected the word both with \"corn\" and \"oak-horn\", and the spelling changed accordingly.<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Acorn|volume=1|pages=152\u2013153}} This cites the ''New English Dictionary'', now the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''</ref>  The current spelling (emerged 15c.-16c.), derives from association with ''ac'' (Old English: \"oak\") + ''corn''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Online Etymology Dictionary|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=acorn&searchmode=none|website=www.etymonline.com|accessdate=15 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\n1410EcudQ.svg|Acorn in heraldry\nAcorn Britain National Trails Symbol.svg|Acorn waymark for [[National Trails]]\nPeacePalaceSculpture-Acorns-24042014.jpg|Copper acorns at the [[Peace Palace]], The Hague.\nPhotograph with text showing a Chuckachancy woman preparing acorns for grinding, California. This is from a survey... - NARA - 296297 (cropped).jpg|[[Yokuts people|Chuckachancy]] women pause in their work preparing acorns for grinding, California, ca. 1920\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Knopper gall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links and further reading==\n{{Commons|Acorns}}\n* [http://www.nativetech.org/recipes/recipe.php?recipeid=115 Nupa Acorn Soup] (Miwokan recipe)\n* [http://www.siouxme.com/acorn.html Cooking With Acorns: A Major North American Indian Food]\n* {{cite web |first=Terry |last=Krautwurst |date=September\u2013October 1988 |title=A Fall Field Guide Nuts |url=http://www.motherearthnews.com/Nature-Community/1988-09-01/A-Fall-Field-Guide-to-Nuts.aspx |work=[[Mother Earth News]] |accessdate=20 October 2009}}\n* Julia F. Parker and Beverly R. Ortiz, ''It Will Live Forever: Traditional Yosemite Indian Acorn Preparation'', Heyday Books, 2nd revised edition (1 September 1996), trade paperback, 160 pages, {{ISBN|0-930588-45-2}}, {{ISBN|978-0-930588-45-8}}\n* ''[http://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/documents/psw_gtr044/psw_gtr044.pdf Proceedings of the symposium on the ecology, management, and utilization of California oaks, 26\u201328 June]'' USDA Forest Service General Technical Report PSW-044, Berkeley, California, 1980, edited by Timothy R. Plumb, 368 pages\n\n{{Nuts}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Quercus]]\n[[Category:Edible nuts and seeds]]\n[[Category:Ornaments]]\n[[Category:Plants used in Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Post-Columbian Native American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Heraldic charges]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link skipped; link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acorn"}
{"title_page": "British nationality law and Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{Short description|Status of Hong Kong people in United Kingdom law}}\n{{For|information on the most prominent type of British nationality in Hong Kong|British National (Overseas)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{British subjects}}\n'''British nationality law ''' as it pertains to '''Hong Kong''' has been unusual ever since Hong Kong became a [[British colony]] in 1842. From its beginning as a sparsely populated trading port to today's cosmopolitan international financial centre and [[world city]] of over seven million people, the territory has attracted [[refugees]], immigrants and [[expatriates]] alike searching for a new life.\n\nCitizenship matters were complicated by the fact that [[British nationality law]] treated those born in [[:Hong Kong]] as British subjects (although they did not enjoy full rights and citizenship), while the [[People's Republic of China]] did not recognise Hong Kongers with Chinese ancestry as British. The main legal rationale for the Chinese position was that recognising these people as British could be seen as tacit acceptance of a series of treaties which China considers \"[[Unequal treaties|unequal]]\" \u2013 including the ones which ceded the [[Hong Kong Island]], the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] and the land between the Kowloon Peninsula and the [[Sham Chun River]] and neighbouring islands (i.e. the [[New Territories]]) to the UK. The main political reason was to prevent the vast majority of Hong Kong residents from having any recourse to British assistance (e.g. by claiming consular assistance or protection under an external treaty) after the [[handover of Hong Kong]].\n\n==Early colonial era==\n[[English common law]] has the rationale of natural-born citizenship, following the principle of ''[[jus soli]]'', in the theory that people born within the dominion of [[The Crown]], which included self-governing [[British Dominions|dominions]] and [[Crown colonies]], would have a \"natural allegiance\" to the Crown as a \"debt of gratitude\" to the Crown for protecting them through infancy.  As the dominion of the British Empire expanded, [[British subject]]s included not only persons within the United Kingdom but also those throughout the rest of the British Empire.\n\nBy this definition, anyone born in Hong Kong after it became a British colony in 1842 was a British subject. The Naturalisation of Aliens Act 1847 expanded what had been covered in the Naturalisation Act 1844, which applied only to people within the United Kingdom, to all its dominions and colonies. The Act made provisions for naturalisation as well as allowing for acquisition of British subject status by marriage between a foreign woman and a man with British subject status.\n\n===British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914===\n{{main|British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914}}\nThe British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914 (now renamed as \"Status of Aliens Act 1914\") came into force on 1 January 1915, codifying for the first time the law relating to British nationality. No major change was introduced but it set into law how people associated with Hong Kong \u2013 as part of \"His Majesty's dominions\" \u2013 would acquire British subject status.\n\n===British Nationality Act 1948===\n{{Main|British Nationality Act 1948}}\n\nThe [[Commonwealth of Nations]]' heads of government decided in 1948 to embark on a major change in the law of nationality throughout the Commonwealth. It was decided at the conference that the United Kingdom and the self-governing dominions would each adopt separate national citizenship, but retain the common imperial status of British subject. The British Nationality Act 1948 provided for a new status of [[Citizen of the United Kingdom and Colonies]] (CUKC), consisting of British subjects who had a close relationship (either through birth or descent) with the United Kingdom and its remaining colonies. The Act also provided that British subjects could be known by the alternative title [[Commonwealth citizen]].\n\nThe Act came into force on 1 January 1949 and stipulated that anyone born in \"United Kingdom or a colony\" on or after that date was a CUKC. Those who were British subjects on 31 December 1948 were entitled to acquire CUKC status by declaration. The deadline for this was originally 31 December 1949, but the deadline was extended to 31 December 1962 by the British Nationality Act 1958.\n\nBritish Nationality Acts were passed in 1958, 1964 and 1965, which mainly fine-tuned special provisions about CUKC status acquisition.\n\n===Commonwealth Immigrants Acts===\nUntil 1962, all Commonwealth citizens could enter and stay in the United Kingdom without any restriction. Anticipating immigration waves from former and current colonies in Africa and Asia with the decolonisation of the 1960s, the United Kingdom passed the [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1962]] and [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1968]] to tighten immigration control for CUKCs into the United Kingdom.\n\nAs such, CUKCs connected with Hong Kong were subject to immigration control after 1962.\n\nFinally, under the [[Immigration Act 1971]], the concept of patriality or [[right of abode]] was created. CUKCs and other Commonwealth citizens had the right of abode in the UK only if they, their husband (if female), their parents or their grandparents were connected with the United Kingdom. This placed the UK in the rare position of denying some of its nationals entry into their country of nationality. However, the concept of patriality was only a temporary solution to halt a sudden wave of migration. The British government later reformed the law, resulting in the British Nationality Act 1981.\n\nThese acts shaped an increasingly restrictive immigration policy into the UK for Hong Kong residents even before the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] of 1984.\n\n=== British Nationality Act 1981 and British Dependent Territories Citizenship ===\n[[Image:Old-hongkong-bp.jpg|thumb|A [[British passport]] for a BDTC with connection with Hong Kong]]\nThe [[British Nationality Act 1981]] created new categories of British nationality and renamed British colonial territories. After implementation, all British Crown colonies became [[British Dependent Territories]]. The Act abolished the status of CUKC, and replaced it with three new categories of nationality on 1 January 1983:\n* [[British Citizen]] (for residents of the UK and the [[Crown dependency|Crown dependencies]])\n* [[British Dependent Territories Citizen]] (BDTC) (for the Crown colonies), and\n* [[British Overseas Citizen]] (BOC) (a class of non-inheritable nationality for those who are unable to become a British Citizen, a BDTC or a national of another country)\n\nThe law stated that those who have CUKC status by connection with Hong Kong and those born in Hong Kong on or after 1983 to a parent settled in Hong Kong are BDTCs. The law also stated that British Citizens or BDTCs by descent could not automatically pass on British nationality to a child born outside the United Kingdom or the dependent territories concerned unless a parent acquired citizenship otherwise than by descent.\n\n==After the Sino-British Joint Declaration==\n[[Image:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|right|100px]] [[Image:Flag of Hong Kong 1959.svg|right|100px]] [[Image:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|right|100px]]\nNegotiation concerning the future of Hong Kong started in the late 1970s between Britain and China. With the signing of the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] on 19 December 1984, the future of Hong Kong was set, with China to assume sovereignty of the entire territory of Hong Kong on 1 July 1997.\n\nAt that time, there were some 3.5 million residents of Hong Kong with BDTC status by virtue of their connection with Hong Kong.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Another 2 million were believed to have been eligible to apply to become BDTCs. After the handover, they would have lost this status and became solely [[Chinese nationality law|Chinese nationals]]. At the time, Hong Kong was the largest of the remaining British dependent territories with over 5 million inhabitants.\n\n===Creation of the British National (Overseas) status===\n{{Demographics of Hong Kong}}\n{{Main|British National (Overseas)}}\n\nThe [[Hong Kong Act 1985]] created an additional category of [[British nationality law|British nationality]] known as ''[[British National (Overseas)]]'' or ''BN(O)''. This new category was available only to Hong Kong BDTCs, and any Hong Kong BDTC who wished to do so would be able to acquire the status of BN(O). The status was non-transferable and available only by application, and the deadline to apply was 30 June 1997.\n\n====British Overseas Citizen status for those who are 'otherwise stateless'====\nAny Hong Kong BDTCs who failed to register as a BN(O) by 1 July 1997 and would thereby be rendered stateless (generally because they were a non-ethnic Chinese and therefore could not automatically acquire Chinese nationality), automatically became a [[British Overseas Citizen]] under the Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf |title=Article 6(1), ''Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order, 1986'' |access-date=18 August 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf |archive-date=26 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1990: British citizenship for 50,000 Hong Kong families===\n{{Main|British Nationality Selection Scheme}}\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989]], many people in Hong Kong began to fear for their future post-1997. Emigration was rampant and a brain-drain was beginning to affect the economy of Hong Kong. To stem the drain, people urged the British government to grant full British citizenship to all Hong Kong BDTCs \u2013 but this request was never accepted. However, the British did agree to creating the [[British Nationality Selection Scheme]], which granted to a select 50,000 people and their families the ability to obtain full British citizenship without having to fulfill the ordinary requirements, under the British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1990.<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1990/34/contents|title=British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990}}</ref> Under the Act, the Home Secretary was required to register any person recommended by the [[Governor of Hong Kong]] (as well as the applicant's spouse and minor children) as a British Citizen. Any person who was registered under the act automatically ceased to be a BDTC upon registration as a British Citizen. No person could be registered under the act after 30 June 1997.\n\n===Hong Kong (War Wives and Widows) Act 1996: British citizenship for Hong Kong war wives and widows===\nWomen who had received assurance from the Secretary of State that they would be eligible for settlement in the United Kingdom on the basis of their husband's war service in the defence of Hong Kong may be registered as British Citizens if they were resident in Hong Kong and had not remarried. There is no requirement for the woman to hold (or have held) any form of British nationality. Women registered as British Citizens under this act acquire British citizenship \"otherwise than by descent\" and thus also their children would be [[British Citizen]]s.<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1996/41/contents|title=Hong Kong (War Wives and Widows) Act 1996}}</ref>\n\n===British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997: British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) without Chinese ancestry===\nAnother special group of solely Hong Kong British nationals were the non-Chinese ethnic minorities of Hong Kong. They are primarily immigrants or children of immigrants from Nepal, India and [[Pakistan]]. After the [[transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|handover]] to China, they would not be accepted as inherently being citizens of the People's Republic. They would be left effectively [[stateless person|stateless]] \u2013 they would have British nationality and [[permanent residency]] and right of abode in Hong Kong, but no right of abode in the UK, nor a right to claim [[Chinese nationality law|Chinese nationality]].\n\nThe ethnic minorities petitioned to be granted full British citizenship,<ref>[http://www.journalism.sfsu.edu/www/pubs/prism/nov95/03.html A Pasage to Nowhere] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050910112715/http://www.journalism.sfsu.edu/www/pubs/prism/nov95/03.html |date=10 September 2005 }} (Prism Nov 1995) ''accessed 1 Aug 2010''</ref> and were backed by several politicians [[Jack Straw (politician)|Jack Straw]], then the Shadow Home Secretary said <ref>[http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=48962 ]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> in a letter to the then Home Secretary [[Michael Howard]] dated 30 January 1997 that \"common sense and common humanity demand that we give these people full British citizenship. The limbo in which they will find themselves in July arises directly from the agreements which Britain made with China\". He further stated that a claim that BN(O) status amounts to British nationality \"is pure sophistry\".</ref> and media.<ref>''[[The Economist]]'' also said that \"the failure to offer citizenship to most of Hong Kong's residents was shameful\", and \"it was the height of cynicism to hand 6 million people over to a regime of proven brutality without allowing them any means to move elsewhere.\" The article also stated that the real reason that the new Labour government still refused to give full British citizenship to other BDTCs was because if the UK waited until Hong Kong had been disposed of it \"would be seen as highly cynical\", as [[Elizabeth Symons, Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean|The Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean]], a [[Foreign Office]] minister, conceded. (\"Britain's colonial obligations\", 3 July 1997, ''[[The Economist]]'')</ref> The subsequently enacted British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1997/20/contents|title=British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997}}</ref> gives them an entitlement to acquire full British citizenship by making an application to register for that status after 1 July 1997.\n\n===Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002: British Overseas Territories Citizen status is not applicable to Hong Kong===\nIn light of the passing of the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002]], which made provision to substitute the wording of \"British Dependent Territories\" with \"[[British Overseas Territories]]\" in the British Nationality Act 1981 among other new provisions, further clarification was made even though this act did not even apply to Hong Kong. Section 14 of the subsequent Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 stated specifically that a person may not be registered as a [[British Overseas Territories Citizen]] (BOTC) by virtue of a connection with Hong Kong.\n\n===Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009: British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) who do not have another nationality or citizenship===\n{{main|Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009}}\nA small group of Hong Kong ethnic minorities had not been eligible for acquiring British citizenship under the British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997 because they were not ordinarily resident in Hong Kong before 4 February 1997 or they were under 18 / 21 years of age, had dual nationality through their parents on or after 4 February 1997, but had lost it upon turning 18/21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/british-nationality-hong-kong-act-1997-nationality-policy-guidance|title=Registration as a British citizen: British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> These BN(O)s lost their second nationality due to changes in the nationality laws of certain countries and had, therefore, become de facto stateless. They could register to become [[British citizens]] under section 4B of the [[British Nationality Act 1981]] as amended by [[Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009]] to \"remedy the limbo status of probably the last remaining group of solely British nationals who have no other nationality or citizenship, who have not recently and deliberately given up another nationality or citizenship\".<ref>[[Lord Avebury]] in the [[House of Lords]]</ref> To be eligible for registration, they must demonstrate that they had not lost, through action or inaction, any other nationality on and after 19 March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/other-british-nationals-nationality-policy-guidance|title=Registration as a British citizen: other British nationals|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> Registration under s4B confers British citizenship by descent.\n\n==Chinese view on nationality of Hong Kong residents==\nThe Chinese government stated in its memorandum of the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] on December 19, 1984 that under the [[Chinese nationality law]], \"all Hong Kong Chinese compatriots, whether they are holders of the 'British Dependent Territories Citizens' Passport' or not, are Chinese nationals\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmab.gov.hk/en/issues/jd6.htm| title = The Joint Declaration - Memoranda (Exchanged Between the Two Sides)|publisher= Constitutional and Mainland Affairs Bureau, The Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region | accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In 1990, when the [[Gulf War]] started, the Chinese embassy provided  a proof of Chinese citizenship to a Hong Kong Chinese businessman in Kuwait holding a BDTC passport and helped him evacuate.<ref>{{cite book|title=\u4e2d\u570b\u5167\u5730\u8207\u9999\u6e2f\u5730\u5340\u6cd5\u5f8b\u7684\u885d\u7a81\u8207\u5354\u8abf|trans-title = Conflict and Coordination of Laws of Mainland China and Hong Kong |publisher=Chung Hwa Book Company (Hong Kong) |editor=Dong Likun|year=2016|pages=181-182|language=zh}}</ref> [[Chinese nationality law]] has applied in Hong Kong since the handover on 1 July 1997. Hong Kong BDTC status ceased to exist and cannot be regained. An interpretation for implementing Chinese nationality law for Hong Kong was presented at the Nineteenth Session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress on 15 May 1996, a year prior to the Hong Kong handover and came into effect on 1 July 1997. The explanations concerning the implementation of the nationality of Hong Kong citizens is that Hong Kong citizens of Chinese descent are Chinese nationals whether or not they have acquired other foreign citizenship(s). Where such Chinese nationals resident in Hong Kong undergo a change of citizenship (e.g. in accordance with Article 9 of the Nationality Law, which provides that a person who becomes ''settled'' in a foreign country ''and'' acquires foreign citizenship loses his or her Chinese citizenship - Hong Kong is not recognised as foreign territory, before or after 1 July 1997), this must be declared to immigration authorities to be recognised under Chinese nationality law. British nationality acquired in Hong Kong (including BN(O) and under the British Nationality Selection Scheme are specifically not recognised as a change of nationality (as they did not occur after the person became ''settled'' in a foreign country). Therefore, a Hong Kong resident who had acquired non-Chinese citizenship would still be recognised as a Chinese citizen after 1 July 1997 (effectively becoming a [[dual nationality|dual national]]), but if that person declares the change of nationality to immigration authorities, they would effectively cease to be a Chinese national.\n\nThis is reflected in the position the [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]] has on Hong Kong permanent residents of Chinese nationality who were Hong Kong permanent residents immediately before 1 July 1997 and hold non-Chinese nationality or citizenship. Those who were permanent residents before the Handover continue to enjoy right of abode in Hong Kong whether they have remained overseas for long time or hold foreign nationality. They however, will not enjoy foreign consular protection in Hong Kong as long as they do not declare a change of nationality to the Immigration Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/residents/immigration/roa/eligible-position-chinese-hold-foreign-passports.html|title=The Position of Residents (including Former Residents) of Chinese Nationality who were Permanent Residents Immediately Before 1 July 1997 and Hold Foreign Passports &#124; Immigration Department|website=www.immd.gov.hk}}</ref>\n\n==Recent groups eligible for a form of British Nationality==\n\n===British citizenship for non-ethnic Chinese which were wrongfully denied===\nIn February 2006, in response to representations made by Lord Avebury and Tameem Ebrahim,<ref>[http://www.britishcitizen.info/CitizenshipDenied_HO_Submission.pdf representations made by Lord Avebury and Tameem Ebrahim, 6 December 2004 (Accessed 1 Aug 2010)]</ref> British authorities announced that six hundred British citizenship applications of ethnic minority children of Indian descent from Hong Kong were wrongly refused.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldlwa/060228wa1.pdf|title=British citizenship applications of ethnic minority children of Indian descent from Hong Kong wrongly refused}}</ref> The applications dated from the period July 1997 onwards. Where the applicant in such cases confirms that he or she still wishes to receive British citizenship the decision will be reconsidered on request.\n\n===British Overseas Citizen status/British citizenship for certain ethnic Indians (new Indian law)===\nRecent changes to India's ''Citizenship Act, 1955'' (see [[Indian nationality law]]) provide that Indian citizenship by descent can no longer be acquired automatically at the time of birth. This amendment will also allow some children of Indian origin born in Hong Kong after 3 December 2004 who have a BN(O) or BOC parent to automatically acquire BOC status at birth under the provisions for reducing statelessness in [https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf articles 6(2) and 6(3) of the ''Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order, 1986'']. If they have acquired no other nationality after birth, they will be entitled to [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds04/text/41220w04.htm#column_WA123 register for full British citizenship].\n\n===British Overseas Citizen status/British citizenship for certain ethnic Nepalese (reinterpretation of Nepalese law)===\nRecent clarification of [[Nepal citizenship law]] has meant a number of persons born in Hong Kong who failed to renounce their British nationality before the age of 21 and were previously thought to be citizens of Nepal are in fact solely British. The British Government has recently accepted that certain Nepalese passport holders born in Hong Kong before 30 June 1976 are BOCs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/foreign-commonwealth-office|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> and can register for British citizenship if they wish to do so.\n\n===British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) who are otherwise stateless===\nThe passage of the Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009 provides a path for British Nationals (Overseas) who had no other citizenship before 19 March 2009 to apply for British citizenship under s.&nbsp;4B of the British Nationality Act 1981. To qualify, they must demonstrate that they had not lost or renounced any other nationalities, through action or inaction, on or after 19 March 2009.\n\n==Future of the British National (Overseas) status: Lord Goldsmith's citizenship review in 2008==\n[[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|Lord Goldsmith]] discussed the BN(O) issue in his citizenship review in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405223352/http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf|archivedate=2008-04-05|title=Wayback Machine|date=5 April 2008|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> He regarded the BN(O) status as \"anomalous\" in the history of British nationality law, but saw no alternative to preserving this status.<ref>\"Nonetheless to remove this status without putting something significant in its place would be seen as the British reneging on their promise to the people of Hong Kong. The only option which would be characterized as fair would be to offer existing BN(O) holders the right to gain full British citizenship. It is likely that many would not take this up as the prospects economic and fiscal of moving to the UK are not favourable to those well-established in Hong Kong. However, I am advised that this would be a breach of the commitments made between China and the UK in the 1984 Joint Declaration on the future of Hong Kong, an international treaty between the two countries; and that to secure Chinese agreement to vary the terms of that treaty would not be possible. On that basis, I see no alternative but to preserve this one anomalous category of citizenship\": Chapter 4, paragraph 12.</ref>\n\nHowever, Goldsmith stated in February 2020:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3051995/britain-could-give-hong-kong-bno-passport-holders-right-abode|title=Britain \u2018could give Hong Kong BN(O) passport holders\u2019 right of abode|date=24 February 2020|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> \u201cI want to make it clear: I never intended my report on citizenship to be a statement on any opinion by me that there would be a breach of the arrangements with China if the UK were to offer greater rights,\u201d he said. \u201cI do not see why the UK government would be in breach of any obligation undertaken in the joint declaration were it to resolve to extend full right of abode to BN(O) passport holders while continuing to honour their side of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.\u201d\n\n==See also==\n*[[British passport]]\n*[[British National (Overseas) passport]]\n*[[History of British nationality law]]\n*[[Hong Kong Special Administrative Region passport]]\n*[[Exit & Entry Permit]] \u2013 issued by the Republic of China (Taiwan) to Hong Kong and Macao residents for entry to Taiwan\n*[[Right of abode in Hong Kong]]\n\n===Government documents===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405223352/http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf Lord Goldsmith QC Citizenship Review ''Citizenship: Our Common Bond'']\n*[http://www.fco.gov.uk/servlet/Front?pagename=OpenMarket/Xcelerate/ShowPage&c=Page&cid=1138870241398 British citizenship information for persons from Hong Kong of Indian origin]\n*[http://www.fco.gov.uk/servlet/Front?pagename=OpenMarket/Xcelerate/ShowPage&c=Page&cid=1138870243763 British citizenship information for persons from Hong Kong of Nepalese origin]\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldlwa/060228wa1.pdf Home Office letter to Lord Avebury, confirming that more than 600 applications for British citizenship from Hong Kong were wrongly refused]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-23a.213.6&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g213.7 which persons born in Hong Kong before 1949 acquired British nationality]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-18a.173.0&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g173.1 which persons born in Hong Kong between 1949 and 1982 acquired British nationality]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-18a.173.3&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g173.4 which persons born in Hong Kong between 1983 and 1997 acquired British nationality]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930153728/http://www.gnn.gov.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=2&ReleaseID=174346 SUPPORTING BRITISH NATIONALS ABROAD: A GUIDE TO CONSULAR ASSISTANCE]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100625235545/http://travel.state.gov/visa/frvi/reciprocity/reciprocity_3699.html Reciprocity Schedule (United Kingdom), United States]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100626003656/http://travel.state.gov/visa/frvi/reciprocity/reciprocity_3579.html Reciprocity Schedule (Hong Kong), United States]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zEcwW0yuuwA BN(O) passport TV advertisement in 1994]\n\n===Legislations===\n*British Nationality Acts: [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1981revd.htm 1981], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1965.htm 1965], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1964.htm 1964], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1958.htm 1958], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1948.htm 1948], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1772.htm 1772], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1730.htm 1730]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081003045618/http://www.britishcitizen.info/HKBNO1986.pdf Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf Provisions for reducing statelessness in Article 6 of the Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986]\n\n===Newspapers/Commentaries===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070103185619/http://www.hku.hk/hkcsp/ccex/ehkcss01/issue2_ar_ma_01.htm The Transition of Hong Kong People's Nationality after World War II by Michiko Ai]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929093302/http://www.dab.org.hk/en/main.jsp?content=article-content.jsp&categoryId=1205&articleId=168 Nationality of the Chief Executive of the SAR], [[Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070510092328/http://www1.appledaily.atnext.com/template/apple/art_main.cfm?iss_id=20070407&sec_id=4104&subsec_id=11867&art_id=6979745 \u6578\u5b57\u8a71\u7576\u5e74 450\u842c\u4eba\u6301\u7279\u5340\u8b77\u7167], ''[[Apple Daily]]''\n*[http://paper.wenweipo.com/2007/04/20/PL0704200010.htm BNO\u9010\u6f38\u8d70\u9032\u9999\u6e2f\u6b77\u53f2], ''[[Wen Wei Po]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080419225620/http://www.mingpaosf.com/htm/News/20070601/HK-gfk1.htm BNO\u8b77\u7167\u2260\u82f1\u7c4d], ''[[Mingpao]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080528160200/http://www.ilpa.org.uk/submissions/Citizenship%20Review.doc SUBMISSION TO LORD GOLDSMITH FOR THE CITIZENSHIP REVIEW: THE DIFFERENT CATEGORIES OF BRITISH NATIONALITY, Immigration Law Practitioners' Association]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*\u5f35\u52c7\u3001\u9673\u7389\u7530\uff1a\u300a\u9999\u6e2f\u5c45\u6c11\u7684\u570b\u7c4d\u554f\u984c\u300b\uff08\u51fa\u7248\u793e\uff1a\u4e09\u806f\u66f8\u5e97\uff08\u9999\u6e2f\uff09\uff09 (Chinese)\n*\u300a\u4fee\u6539\u82f1\u570b\u570b\u7c4d\u6cd5\u7684\u6df1\u523b\u6559\u8a13\u300b, [[Leung Chun Ying]], ''[[Mingpao]]'', 16 March 2007\n*\u300a\u4eba\u5fc3\u5c1a\u672a\u56de\u6b78\u570b\u4eba\u4ecd\u9700\u52aa\u529b\u300b, [[Leung Chun Ying]], ''[[Mingpao]]'', 1 June 2007\n* Ng Chi-sum, Jane C.Y. Lee and Qu Ayang, ''Nationality and Right of Abode of Hong Kong Residents \u2013 Continuity and Change before and after 1997'', 1997, Centre of Asian Studies, Hong Kong University (book in Chinese)\n*''Britain's colonial obligations'', ''[[The Economist]]'', 3 July 1997\n*''The colonies\u2014Leftovers'', ''[[The Economist]]'', 3 July 1997\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/uk-british-nationality-hong-kong-citizens-tom-tugendhat UK should give British nationality to Hong Kong citizens, Tugendhat says]\n{{British nationality law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:British Nationality Law And Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:British nationality law]]\n[[Category:Immigration to the United Kingdom|Nationality law]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:International travel documents]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong|Nationality law]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong travel documents]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Chinese community in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom concerning Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong and the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Status of Hong Kong people in United Kingdom law}}\n{{For|information on the most prominent type of British nationality in Hong Kong|British National (Overseas)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{British subjects}}\n'''British nationality law ''' as it pertains to '''Hong Kong''' has been unusual ever since Hong Kong became a [[British colony]] in 1842. From its beginning as a sparsely populated trading port to today's cosmopolitan international financial centre and [[world city]] of over seven million people, the territory has attracted [[refugees]], immigrants and [[expatriates]] alike searching for a new life.\n\nCitizenship matters were complicated by the fact that [[British nationality law]] treated those born in [[:Hong Kong]] as British subjects (although they did not enjoy full rights and citizenship), while the [[People's Republic of China]] did not recognise Hong Kongers with Chinese ancestry as British. The main legal rationale for the Chinese position was that recognising these people as British could be seen as tacit acceptance of a series of treaties which China considers \"[[Unequal treaties|unequal]]\" \u2013 including the ones which ceded the [[Hong Kong Island]], the [[Kowloon Peninsula]] and the land between the Kowloon Peninsula and the [[Sham Chun River]] and neighbouring islands (i.e. the [[New Territories]]) to the UK. The main political reason was to prevent the vast majority of Hong Kong residents from having any recourse to British assistance (e.g. by claiming consular assistance or protection under an external treaty) after the [[handover of Hong Kong]].\n\n==Early colonial era==\n[[English common law]] has the rationale of natural-born citizenship, following the principle of ''[[jus soli]]'', in the theory that people born within the dominion of [[The Crown]], which included self-governing [[British Dominions|dominions]] and [[Crown colonies]], would have a \"natural allegiance\" to the Crown as a \"debt of gratitude\" to the Crown for protecting them through infancy.  As the dominion of the British Empire expanded, [[British subject]]s included not only persons within the United Kingdom but also those throughout the rest of the British Empire.\n\nBy this definition, anyone born in Hong Kong after it became a British colony in 1842 was a British subject. The Naturalisation of Aliens Act 1847 expanded what had been covered in the Naturalisation Act 1844, which applied only to people within the United Kingdom, to all its dominions and colonies. The Act made provisions for naturalisation as well as allowing for acquisition of British subject status by marriage between a foreign woman and a man with British subject status.\n\n===British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914===\n{{main|British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914}}\nThe British Nationality and Status of Aliens Act 1914 (now renamed as \"Status of Aliens Act 1914\") came into force on 1 January 1915, codifying for the first time the law relating to British nationality. No major change was introduced but it set into law how people associated with Hong Kong \u2013 as part of \"His Majesty's dominions\" \u2013 would acquire British subject status.\n\n===British Nationality Act 1948===\n{{Main|British Nationality Act 1948}}\n\nThe [[Commonwealth of Nations]]' heads of government decided in 1948 to embark on a major change in the law of nationality throughout the Commonwealth. It was decided at the conference that the United Kingdom and the self-governing dominions would each adopt separate national citizenship, but retain the common imperial status of British subject. The British Nationality Act 1948 provided for a new status of [[Citizen of the United Kingdom and Colonies]] (CUKC), consisting of British subjects who had a close relationship (either through birth or descent) with the United Kingdom and its remaining colonies. The Act also provided that British subjects could be known by the alternative title [[Commonwealth citizen]].\n\nThe Act came into force on 1 January 1949 and stipulated that anyone born in \"United Kingdom or a colony\" on or after that date was a CUKC. Those who were British subjects on 31 December 1948 were entitled to acquire CUKC status by declaration. The deadline for this was originally 31 December 1949, but the deadline was extended to 31 December 1962 by the British Nationality Act 1958.\n\nBritish Nationality Acts were passed in 1958, 1964 and 1965, which mainly fine-tuned special provisions about CUKC status acquisition.\n\n===Commonwealth Immigrants Acts===\nUntil 1962, all Commonwealth citizens could enter and stay in the United Kingdom without any restriction. Anticipating immigration waves from former and current colonies in Africa and Asia with the decolonisation of the 1960s, the United Kingdom passed the [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1962]] and [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1968]] to tighten immigration control for CUKCs into the United Kingdom.\n\nAs such, CUKCs connected with Hong Kong were subject to immigration control after 1962.\n\nFinally, under the [[Immigration Act 1971]], the concept of patriality or [[right of abode]] was created. CUKCs and other Commonwealth citizens had the right of abode in the UK only if they, their husband (if female), their parents or their grandparents were connected with the United Kingdom. This placed the UK in the rare position of denying some of its nationals entry into their country of nationality. However, the concept of patriality was only a temporary solution to halt a sudden wave of migration. The British government later reformed the law, resulting in the British Nationality Act 1981.\n\nThese acts shaped an increasingly restrictive immigration policy into the UK for Hong Kong residents even before the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] of 1984.\n\n=== British Nationality Act 1981 and British Dependent Territories Citizenship ===\n[[Image:Old-hongkong-bp.jpg|thumb|A [[British passport]] for a BDTC with connection with Hong Kong]]\nThe [[British Nationality Act 1981]] created new categories of British nationality and renamed British colonial territories. After implementation, all British Crown colonies became [[British Dependent Territories]]. The Act abolished the status of CUKC, and replaced it with three new categories of nationality on 1 January 1983:\n* [[British Citizen]] (for residents of the UK and the [[Crown dependency|Crown dependencies]])\n* [[British Dependent Territories Citizen]] (BDTC) (for the Crown colonies), and\n* [[British Overseas Citizen]] (BOC) (a class of non-inheritable nationality for those who are unable to become a British Citizen, a BDTC or a national of another country)\n\nThe law stated that those who have CUKC status by connection with Hong Kong and those born in Hong Kong on or after 1983 to a parent settled in Hong Kong are BDTCs. The law also stated that British Citizens or BDTCs by descent could not automatically pass on British nationality to a child born outside the United Kingdom or the dependent territories concerned unless a parent acquired citizenship otherwise than by descent.\n\n==After the Sino-British Joint Declaration==\n[[Image:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|right|100px]] [[Image:Flag of Hong Kong 1959.svg|right|100px]] [[Image:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|right|100px]]\nNegotiation concerning the future of Hong Kong started in the late 1970s between Britain and China. With the signing of the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] on 19 December 1984, the future of Hong Kong was set, with China to assume sovereignty of the entire territory of Hong Kong on 1 July 1997.\n\nAt that time, there were some 3.5 million residents of Hong Kong with BDTC status by virtue of their connection with Hong Kong.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Another 2 million were believed to have been eligible to apply to become BDTCs. After the handover, they would have lost this status and became solely [[Chinese nationality law|Chinese nationals]]. At the time, Hong Kong was the largest of the remaining British dependent territories with over 5 million inhabitants.\n\n===Creation of the British National (Overseas) status===\n{{Demographics of Hong Kong}}\n{{Main|British National (Overseas)}}\n\nThe [[Hong Kong Act 1985]] created an additional category of [[British nationality law|British nationality]] known as ''[[British National (Overseas)]]'' or ''BN(O)''. This new category was available only to Hong Kong BDTCs, and any Hong Kong BDTC who wished to do so would be able to acquire the status of BN(O). The status was non-transferable and available only by application, and the deadline to apply was 30 June 1997.\n\n====British Overseas Citizen status for those who are 'otherwise stateless'====\nAny Hong Kong BDTCs who failed to register as a BN(O) by 1 July 1997 and would thereby be rendered stateless (generally because they were a non-ethnic Chinese and therefore could not automatically acquire Chinese nationality), automatically became a [[British Overseas Citizen]] under the Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf |title=Article 6(1), ''Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order, 1986'' |access-date=18 August 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf |archive-date=26 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1990: British citizenship for 50,000 Hong Kong families===\n{{Main|British Nationality Selection Scheme}}\nAfter the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989]], many people in Hong Kong began to fear for their future post-1997. Emigration was rampant and a brain-drain was beginning to affect the economy of Hong Kong. To stem the drain, people urged the British government to grant full British citizenship to all Hong Kong BDTCs \u2013 but this request was never accepted. However, the British did agree to creating the [[British Nationality Selection Scheme]], which granted to a select 50,000 people and their families the ability to obtain full British citizenship without having to fulfill the ordinary requirements, under the British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1990.<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1990/34/contents|title=British Nationality Act (Hong Kong) 1990}}</ref> Under the Act, the Home Secretary was required to register any person recommended by the [[Governor of Hong Kong]] (as well as the applicant's spouse and minor children) as a British Citizen. Any person who was registered under the act automatically ceased to be a BDTC upon registration as a British Citizen. No person could be registered under the act after 30 June 1997.\n\n===Hong Kong (War Wives and Widows) Act 1996: British citizenship for Hong Kong war wives and widows===\nWomen who had received assurance from the Secretary of State that they would be eligible for settlement in the United Kingdom on the basis of their husband's war service in the defence of Hong Kong may be registered as British Citizens if they were resident in Hong Kong and had not remarried. There is no requirement for the woman to hold (or have held) any form of British nationality. Women registered as British Citizens under this act acquire British citizenship \"otherwise than by descent\" and thus also their children would be [[British Citizen]]s.<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1996/41/contents|title=Hong Kong (War Wives and Widows) Act 1996}}</ref>\n\n===British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997: British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) without Chinese ancestry===\nAnother special group of solely Hong Kong British nationals were the non-Chinese ethnic minorities of Hong Kong. They are primarily immigrants or children of immigrants from Nepal, India and [[Pakistan]]. After the [[transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|handover]] to China, they would not be accepted as inherently being citizens of the People's Republic. They would be left effectively [[stateless person|stateless]] \u2013 they would have British nationality and [[permanent residency]] and right of abode in Hong Kong, but no right of abode in the UK, nor a right to claim [[Chinese nationality law|Chinese nationality]].\n\nThe ethnic minorities petitioned to be granted full British citizenship,<ref>[http://www.journalism.sfsu.edu/www/pubs/prism/nov95/03.html A Pasage to Nowhere] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050910112715/http://www.journalism.sfsu.edu/www/pubs/prism/nov95/03.html |date=10 September 2005 }} (Prism Nov 1995) ''accessed 1 Aug 2010''</ref> and were backed by several politicians [[Jack Straw (politician)|Jack Straw]], then the Shadow Home Secretary said <ref>[http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=48962 ]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> in a letter to the then Home Secretary [[Michael Howard]] dated 30 January 1997 that \"common sense and common humanity demand that we give these people full British citizenship. The limbo in which they will find themselves in July arises directly from the agreements which Britain made with China\". He further stated that a claim that BN(O) status amounts to British nationality \"is pure sophistry\".</ref> and media.<ref>''[[The Economist]]'' also said that \"the failure to offer citizenship to most of Hong Kong's residents was shameful\", and \"it was the height of cynicism to hand 6 million people over to a regime of proven brutality without allowing them any means to move elsewhere.\" The article also stated that the real reason that the new Labour government still refused to give full British citizenship to other BDTCs was because if the UK waited until Hong Kong had been disposed of it \"would be seen as highly cynical\", as [[Elizabeth Symons, Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean|The Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean]], a [[Foreign Office]] minister, conceded. (\"Britain's colonial obligations\", 3 July 1997, ''[[The Economist]]'')</ref> The subsequently enacted British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997<ref>{{UK-LEG|path=ukpga/1997/20/contents|title=British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997}}</ref> gives them an entitlement to acquire full British citizenship by making an application to register for that status after 1 July 1997.\n\n===Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002: British Overseas Territories Citizen status is not applicable to Hong Kong===\nIn light of the passing of the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002]], which made provision to substitute the wording of \"British Dependent Territories\" with \"[[British Overseas Territories]]\" in the British Nationality Act 1981 among other new provisions, further clarification was made even though this act did not even apply to Hong Kong. Section 14 of the subsequent Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 stated specifically that a person may not be registered as a [[British Overseas Territories Citizen]] (BOTC) by virtue of a connection with Hong Kong.\n\n===Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009: British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) who do not have another nationality or citizenship===\n{{main|Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009}}\nA small group of Hong Kong ethnic minorities had not been eligible for acquiring British citizenship under the British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997 because they were not ordinarily resident in Hong Kong before 4 February 1997 or they were under 18 / 21 years of age, had dual nationality through their parents on or after 4 February 1997, but had lost it upon turning 18/21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/british-nationality-hong-kong-act-1997-nationality-policy-guidance|title=Registration as a British citizen: British Nationality (Hong Kong) Act 1997|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> These BN(O)s lost their second nationality due to changes in the nationality laws of certain countries and had, therefore, become de facto stateless. They could register to become [[British citizens]] under section 4B of the [[British Nationality Act 1981]] as amended by [[Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009]] to \"remedy the limbo status of probably the last remaining group of solely British nationals who have no other nationality or citizenship, who have not recently and deliberately given up another nationality or citizenship\".<ref>[[Lord Avebury]] in the [[House of Lords]]</ref> To be eligible for registration, they must demonstrate that they had not lost, through action or inaction, any other nationality on and after 19 March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/other-british-nationals-nationality-policy-guidance|title=Registration as a British citizen: other British nationals|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> Registration under s4B confers British citizenship by descent.\n\n==Chinese view on nationality of Hong Kong residents==\nThe Chinese government stated in its memorandum of the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] on December 19, 1984 that under the [[Chinese nationality law]], \"all Hong Kong Chinese compatriots, whether they are holders of the 'British Dependent Territories Citizens' Passport' or not, are Chinese nationals\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmab.gov.hk/en/issues/jd6.htm| title = The Joint Declaration - Memoranda (Exchanged Between the Two Sides)|publisher= Constitutional and Mainland Affairs Bureau, The Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region | accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In 1990, when the [[Gulf War]] started, the Chinese embassy provided  a proof of Chinese citizenship to a Hong Kong Chinese businessman in Kuwait holding a BDTC passport and helped him evacuate.<ref>{{cite book|title=\u4e2d\u570b\u5167\u5730\u8207\u9999\u6e2f\u5730\u5340\u6cd5\u5f8b\u7684\u885d\u7a81\u8207\u5354\u8abf|trans-title = Conflict and Coordination of Laws of Mainland China and Hong Kong |publisher=Chung Hwa Book Company (Hong Kong) |editor=Dong Likun|year=2016|pages=181-182|language=zh}}</ref> [[Chinese nationality law]] has applied in Hong Kong since the handover on 1 July 1997. Hong Kong BDTC status ceased to exist and cannot be regained. An interpretation for implementing Chinese nationality law for Hong Kong was presented at the Nineteenth Session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress on 15 May 1996, a year prior to the Hong Kong handover and came into effect on 1 July 1997. The explanations concerning the implementation of the nationality of Hong Kong citizens is that Hong Kong citizens of Chinese descent are Chinese nationals whether or not they have acquired other foreign citizenship(s). Where such Chinese nationals resident in Hong Kong undergo a change of citizenship (e.g. in accordance with Article 9 of the Nationality Law, which provides that a person who becomes ''settled'' in a foreign country ''and'' acquires foreign citizenship loses his or her Chinese citizenship - Hong Kong is not recognised as foreign territory, before or after 1 July 1997), this must be declared to immigration authorities to be recognised under Chinese nationality law. British nationality acquired in Hong Kong (including BN(O) and under the British Nationality Selection Scheme are specifically not recognised as a change of nationality (as they did not occur after the person became ''settled'' in a foreign country). Therefore, a Hong Kong resident who had acquired non-Chinese citizenship would still be recognised as a Chinese citizen after 1 July 1997 (effectively becoming a [[dual nationality|dual national]]), but if that person declares the change of nationality to immigration authorities, they would effectively cease to be a Chinese national.\n\nThis is reflected in the position the [[Hong Kong Immigration Department]] has on Hong Kong permanent residents of Chinese nationality who were Hong Kong permanent residents immediately before 1 July 1997 and hold non-Chinese nationality or citizenship. Those who were permanent residents before the Handover continue to enjoy right of abode in Hong Kong whether they have remained overseas for long time or hold foreign nationality. They however, will not enjoy foreign consular protection in Hong Kong as long as they do not declare a change of nationality to the Immigration Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.immd.gov.hk/eng/residents/immigration/roa/eligible-position-chinese-hold-foreign-passports.html|title=The Position of Residents (including Former Residents) of Chinese Nationality who were Permanent Residents Immediately Before 1 July 1997 and Hold Foreign Passports &#124; Immigration Department|website=www.immd.gov.hk}}</ref>\n\n==Recent groups eligible for a form of British Nationality==\n\n===British citizenship for non-ethnic Chinese which were wrongfully denied===\nIn February 2006, in response to representations made by Lord Avebury and Tameem Ebrahim,<ref>[http://www.britishcitizen.info/CitizenshipDenied_HO_Submission.pdf representations made by Lord Avebury and Tameem Ebrahim, 6 December 2004 (Accessed 1 Aug 2010)]</ref> British authorities announced that six hundred British citizenship applications of ethnic minority children of Indian descent from Hong Kong were wrongly refused.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldlwa/060228wa1.pdf|title=British citizenship applications of ethnic minority children of Indian descent from Hong Kong wrongly refused}}</ref> The applications dated from the period July 1997 onwards. Where the applicant in such cases confirms that he or she still wishes to receive British citizenship the decision will be reconsidered on request.\n\n===British Overseas Citizen status/British citizenship for certain ethnic Indians (new Indian law)===\nRecent changes to India's ''Citizenship Act, 1955'' (see [[Indian nationality law]]) provide that Indian citizenship by descent can no longer be acquired automatically at the time of birth. This amendment will also allow some children of Indian origin born in Hong Kong after 3 December 2004 who have a BN(O) or BOC parent to automatically acquire BOC status at birth under the provisions for reducing statelessness in [https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf articles 6(2) and 6(3) of the ''Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order, 1986'']. If they have acquired no other nationality after birth, they will be entitled to [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds04/text/41220w04.htm#column_WA123 register for full British citizenship].\n\n===British Overseas Citizen status/British citizenship for certain ethnic Nepalese (reinterpretation of Nepalese law)===\nRecent clarification of [[Nepal citizenship law]] has meant a number of persons born in Hong Kong who failed to renounce their British nationality before the age of 21 and were previously thought to be citizens of Nepal are in fact solely British. The British Government has recently accepted that certain Nepalese passport holders born in Hong Kong before 30 June 1976 are BOCs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/foreign-commonwealth-office|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> and can register for British citizenship if they wish to do so.\n\n===British citizenship for British Nationals (Overseas) who are otherwise stateless===\nThe passage of the Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009 provides a path for British Nationals (Overseas) who had no other citizenship before 19 March 2009 to apply for British citizenship under s.&nbsp;4B of the British Nationality Act 1981. To qualify, they must demonstrate that they had not lost or renounced any other nationalities, through action or inaction, on or after 19 March 2009.\n\n==Future of the British National (Overseas) status: Lord Goldsmith's citizenship review in 2008==\n[[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|Lord Goldsmith]] discussed the BN(O) issue in his citizenship review in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405223352/http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf|archivedate=2008-04-05|title=Wayback Machine|date=5 April 2008|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> He regarded the BN(O) status as \"anomalous\" in the history of British nationality law, but saw no alternative to preserving this status.<ref>\"Nonetheless to remove this status without putting something significant in its place would be seen as the British reneging on their promise to the people of Hong Kong. The only option which would be characterized as fair would be to offer existing BN(O) holders the right to gain full British citizenship. It is likely that many would not take this up as the prospects economic and fiscal of moving to the UK are not favourable to those well-established in Hong Kong. However, I am advised that this would be a breach of the commitments made between China and the UK in the 1984 Joint Declaration on the future of Hong Kong, an international treaty between the two countries; and that to secure Chinese agreement to vary the terms of that treaty would not be possible. On that basis, I see no alternative but to preserve this one anomalous category of citizenship\": Chapter 4, paragraph 12.</ref>\n\nHowever, Goldsmith stated in February 2020:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3051995/britain-could-give-hong-kong-bno-passport-holders-right-abode|title=Britain \u2018could give Hong Kong BN(O) passport holders\u2019 right of abode|date=24 February 2020|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> \u201cI want to make it clear: I never intended my report on citizenship to be a statement on any opinion by me that there would be a breach of the arrangements with China if the UK were to offer greater rights,\u201d he said. \u201cI do not see why the UK government would be in breach of any obligation undertaken in the joint declaration were it to resolve to extend full right of abode to BN(O) passport holders while continuing to honour their side of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.\u201d\n\n==See also==\n*[[British passport]]\n*[[British National (Overseas) passport]]\n*[[History of British nationality law]]\n*[[Hong Kong Special Administrative Region passport]]\n*[[Exit & Entry Permit]] \u2013 issued by the Republic of China (Taiwan) to Hong Kong and Macao residents for entry to Taiwan\n*[[Right of abode in Hong Kong]]\n\n===Government documents===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080405223352/http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/citizenship-report-full.pdf Lord Goldsmith QC Citizenship Review ''Citizenship: Our Common Bond'']\n*[http://www.fco.gov.uk/servlet/Front?pagename=OpenMarket/Xcelerate/ShowPage&c=Page&cid=1138870241398 British citizenship information for persons from Hong Kong of Indian origin]\n*[http://www.fco.gov.uk/servlet/Front?pagename=OpenMarket/Xcelerate/ShowPage&c=Page&cid=1138870243763 British citizenship information for persons from Hong Kong of Nepalese origin]\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldlwa/060228wa1.pdf Home Office letter to Lord Avebury, confirming that more than 600 applications for British citizenship from Hong Kong were wrongly refused]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-23a.213.6&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g213.7 which persons born in Hong Kong before 1949 acquired British nationality]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-18a.173.0&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g173.1 which persons born in Hong Kong between 1949 and 1982 acquired British nationality]\n*British government statement confirming [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2007-01-18a.173.3&s=section%3Awrans+speaker%3A12876#g173.4 which persons born in Hong Kong between 1983 and 1997 acquired British nationality]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930153728/http://www.gnn.gov.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=2&ReleaseID=174346 SUPPORTING BRITISH NATIONALS ABROAD: A GUIDE TO CONSULAR ASSISTANCE]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100625235545/http://travel.state.gov/visa/frvi/reciprocity/reciprocity_3699.html Reciprocity Schedule (United Kingdom), United States]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100626003656/http://travel.state.gov/visa/frvi/reciprocity/reciprocity_3579.html Reciprocity Schedule (Hong Kong), United States]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zEcwW0yuuwA BN(O) passport TV advertisement in 1994]\n\n===Legislations===\n*British Nationality Acts: [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1981revd.htm 1981], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1965.htm 1965], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1964.htm 1964], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1958.htm 1958], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1948.htm 1948], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1772.htm 1772], [http://www.uniset.ca/naty/BNA1730.htm 1730]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081003045618/http://www.britishcitizen.info/HKBNO1986.pdf Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080226205835/http://www.britishcitizen.info/StatelessReductionProvisions.pdf Provisions for reducing statelessness in Article 6 of the Hong Kong (British Nationality) Order 1986]\n\n===Newspapers/Commentaries===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070103185619/http://www.hku.hk/hkcsp/ccex/ehkcss01/issue2_ar_ma_01.htm The Transition of Hong Kong People's Nationality after World War II by Michiko Ai]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929093302/http://www.dab.org.hk/en/main.jsp?content=article-content.jsp&categoryId=1205&articleId=168 Nationality of the Chief Executive of the SAR], [[Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070510092328/http://www1.appledaily.atnext.com/template/apple/art_main.cfm?iss_id=20070407&sec_id=4104&subsec_id=11867&art_id=6979745 \u6578\u5b57\u8a71\u7576\u5e74 450\u842c\u4eba\u6301\u7279\u5340\u8b77\u7167], ''[[Apple Daily]]''\n*[http://paper.wenweipo.com/2007/04/20/PL0704200010.htm BNO\u9010\u6f38\u8d70\u9032\u9999\u6e2f\u6b77\u53f2], ''[[Wen Wei Po]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080419225620/http://www.mingpaosf.com/htm/News/20070601/HK-gfk1.htm BNO\u8b77\u7167\u2260\u82f1\u7c4d], ''[[Mingpao]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080528160200/http://www.ilpa.org.uk/submissions/Citizenship%20Review.doc SUBMISSION TO LORD GOLDSMITH FOR THE CITIZENSHIP REVIEW: THE DIFFERENT CATEGORIES OF BRITISH NATIONALITY, Immigration Law Practitioners' Association]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n==Further reading==\n*\u5f35\u52c7\u3001\u9673\u7389\u7530\uff1a\u300a\u9999\u6e2f\u5c45\u6c11\u7684\u570b\u7c4d\u554f\u984c\u300b\uff08\u51fa\u7248\u793e\uff1a\u4e09\u806f\u66f8\u5e97\uff08\u9999\u6e2f\uff09\uff09 (Chinese)\n*\u300a\u4fee\u6539\u82f1\u570b\u570b\u7c4d\u6cd5\u7684\u6df1\u523b\u6559\u8a13\u300b, [[Leung Chun Ying]], ''[[Mingpao]]'', 16 March 2007\n*\u300a\u4eba\u5fc3\u5c1a\u672a\u56de\u6b78\u570b\u4eba\u4ecd\u9700\u52aa\u529b\u300b, [[Leung Chun Ying]], ''[[Mingpao]]'', 1 June 2007\n* Ng Chi-sum, Jane C.Y. Lee and Qu Ayang, ''Nationality and Right of Abode of Hong Kong Residents \u2013 Continuity and Change before and after 1997'', 1997, Centre of Asian Studies, Hong Kong University (book in Chinese)\n*''Britain's colonial obligations'', ''[[The Economist]]'', 3 July 1997\n*''The colonies\u2014Leftovers'', ''[[The Economist]]'', 3 July 1997\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/uk-british-nationality-hong-kong-citizens-tom-tugendhat UK should give British nationality to Hong Kong citizens, Tugendhat says]\n{{British nationality law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:British Nationality Law And Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:British nationality law]]\n[[Category:Immigration to the United Kingdom|Nationality law]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:History of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:International travel documents]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong|Nationality law]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong travel documents]]\n[[Category:China\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Chinese community in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom concerning Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong and the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n", "name_user": "Kaihsu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_nationality_law_and_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "After Hours (The Weeknd album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|2020 studio album by The Weeknd}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = After Hours\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[The Weeknd]]\n| cover        = The Weeknd - After Hours.png\n| alt          = \n| caption      = Standard cover art for the album, deluxe features the same cover with a red overlay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-shares-deluxe-version-of-after-hours-listen/|title=Chromatics, Lil Uzi Vert, Oneohtrix, and More Remix the Weeknd: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n| released     = March 20, 2020\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132020\n| studio       = \n* [[Jungle City Studios|Jungle City]] (New York, New York)\n* [[Maratone Studios|MXM]] (Los Angeles, California)\n* [[Noble Street Studios|Noble Street]] (Toronto, Ontario)\n* XO ([[Hidden Hills, California]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shop.theweeknd.com/collections/all|title=ALL {{!}} T H E W E E K N D S H O P|website=The Weeknd Shop|accessdate=February 20, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203033816/https://shop.theweeknd.com/collections/all/products/collectors-7-vinyl-001-digital-single|archivedate=December 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| length       = 56:14\n| label        = \n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| genre        = \n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n* [[dream pop]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n| producer     = \n* [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n* [[Kevin Parker (musician)|Kevin Parker]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* [[Metro Boomin]]\n* Notinbed\n* [[Oneohtrix Point Never|OPN]]\n* [[Oscar Holter]]\n* Prince 85\n* [[Ricky Reed]]\n* [[The Weeknd]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Weeknd in Japan]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc    = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative covers\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Weeknd - After Hours (Target edition).jpeg\n | caption = [[Target Corporation|Target]] and [[HMV]] exclusive CD cover\n }}{{Extra album cover\n | header  = no\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Weeknd - After Hours (Remixes).jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = ''After Hours (Remixes)'' cover\n }}{{Singles\n| name = After Hours\n| type = studio\n| single1 = [[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\n| single1date = November 27, 2019\n| single2 = [[Blinding Lights]]\n| single2date = November 29, 2019\n| single3 = [[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\n| single3date = March 24, 2020<!-- According to The Weeknd's own website, \"After Hours\" is not one of the album's single -->\n }}\n}}\n\n'''''After Hours''''' is the fourth studio album by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]]. The album was released by on March 20, 2020 by [[XO (record label)|XO]] and [[Republic Records]]. \n\nThe album was produced primarily by The Weeknd, along with a variety of high-profile producers such as [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]], [[Illangelo]], and [[Metro Boomin]], all of whom The Weeknd had worked with previously. The standard edition has no features, although the remixes edition contains [[guest appearance]]s from [[Chromatics (band)|Chromatics]] and [[Lil Uzi Vert]]. Music journalists have noted the album as an artistic reinvention for The Weeknd, with the introduction of [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[dream pop]] influences, while thematically, ''After Hours'' explores promiscuity, overindulgence, and self-loathing. \n\nThe artwork and aesthetic for the album's promotional material has been described as psychedelic and being inspired by various films, such as: ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'' (1995), ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)|Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]]'' (1998), ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'' and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (both 2019). The album was supported by three singles: \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\", \"[[Blinding Lights]]\", and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\", with \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\" peaking at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Its [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] was released as a promotional single. \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\" both received [[RIAA certification|platinum]] certifications in the US. In March 2020, ''After Hours'' broke the record for the most global pre-adds in [[Apple Music]] history, with over 1.02 million users.\n\n''After Hours'' received widespread acclaim, with some critics praising the album as The Weeknd's best piece of work. The album debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with 444,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, 275,000 of which were in pure sales. It is The Weeknd's fourth number-one album, and marks the biggest first week sales of 2020 for an album. The album also reached number one in 16 other countries, including the Canada and the United Kingdom. ''After Hours'' will be promoted with [[the After Hours Tour]], which is set to span [[North America]] and [[Europe]]. \n\n==Background and release==\nThe Weeknd first teased that he was working on a new album in November 2018, via a performance in which he told the crowd that \"''Chapter VI'' was coming soon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-teases-chapter-vi-album-shares-new-artwork-2413493|title=The Weeknd teases 'Chapter VI' album, shares new artwork|website=NME|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On January 12, 2019, Tesfaye then proceeded to further tease the project and its sound by tweeting \"no more daytime music\" to fans, making media outlets believe that he was set to continue the darker music found in ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weekend-says-new-album-will-be-less-pop-friendly-no-more-daytime-music-news.69193.html|title=The Weeknd Says New Album Will Be Less Pop-Friendly: \"No More Daytime Music\"|website=HotNewHipHop|last=Ch|first=Devin|date=January 13, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Following a trio of collaborative singles throughout 2019, on August 6, he further reassured fans that he was working on his fourth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weekend-teases-new-album-chapter-6-2536077|title=Is The Weeknd's new album finally on its way?|website=NME|last=Skinner|first=Tom|date=August 7, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Then after a five-month period of silence,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-returns-to-instagram-and-fans-are-convinced-chapter-vi-is-coming-news.96171.html|title=The Weeknd Returns To Instagram & Fans Are Convinced \"Chapter VI\" Is Coming|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1095452/the-weeknd-returns-to-instagram-with-a-loading-message|title=The Weeknd Returns to Instagram With a \"Loading\" Message|publisher=[[E! Online]]|last=Schnurr|first=Samantha|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> on November 24, the single \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" was revealed through a [[Mercedes-Benz]] television commercial,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/24/the-weeknd-new-single-blinding-lights/|title=The Weeknd to Release New Single 'Blinding Lights' on Black Friday|website=Rap-Up|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> with reports of \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" surfacing a day later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/25/the-weeknd-teases-new-music/|title=The Weeknd Teases New Music|website=Rap-Up|date=November 25, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd_hints_at_new_music_arriving_tomorrow|title=The Weeknd Hints at New Music Arriving This Week|website=Exclaim!|last=Hudson|first=Alex|date=November 25, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The latter song then premiered on the seventh episode of The Weeknd's ''Memento Mori'' [[Beats 1]] radio show on November 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/11/the-weeknd-memento-mori-beats-1-show-episode-7|title=Stream The Weeknd's 'Memento Mori' Episode 7 on Beats 1 Radio|website=Complex|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Which in the hours leading into the release of the radio show episode, The Weeknd announced on social media his return to music with the captions \"the fall starts tomorrow night\" and \"Tonight we start a new brain melting psychotic chapter! Let's go!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2019/11/the-weeknd-to-release-2-new-singles-blinding-lights-heartless-this-week/|title=The Weeknd to Release 2 New Singles 'Blinding Lights' & \"Heartless\" This Week|website=HipHop-N-More|author=Akaash|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On February 13, 2020, The Weeknd revealed the title of the project \"After Hours\" through a 48-second teaser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3156604/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-teaser/|title=The Weeknd Announces New Album After Hours with an Ominous Teaser|publisher=MTV News|last=Roth|first=Madeline|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-announces-new-album-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd Announces New Album After Hours|website=Pitchfork|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> A couple days after the announcement of the album's name, its release date of March 20, 2020, was shared through social media to accompany the [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]]'s release as a promotional single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-details-new-album-shares-new-song-after-hours-listen/|title=The Weeknd Details New Album, Shares New Song \"After Hours\"|website=Pitchfork|last=Hussey|first=Allison|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/the-weeknd-new-album-title-reveal/|title=The Weeknd Reveals The Title Of His New Album with a Surreal Teaser Video|website=Uppoxx|last=Williams|first=Aaron|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> In the last week leading up to the album's release, ''After Hours''' tracklist was revealed on March 17, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesource.com/2020/03/18/the-weeknd-after-hours-tracklist/|title=The Weeknd Reveals the Tracklist for 'After Hours' Album|website=The Source|last=Grant|first=Shawn|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, 2020, The Weeknd announced that the album is dedicated to long time fan and host of the popular XO Podcast, Lance, who died the night before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/19/the-weeknd-dedicates-after-hours-dead-fan/|title=The Weeknd Dedicates New Album 'After Hours' to Fan Who Died|website=Rap Up|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Dedicate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-dedicates-after-hours-to-late-fan|title=The Weeknd Dedicates 'After Hours' to Fan Who Passed Away|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Price|first=Joe|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The album debuted alongside the eighth episode of ''Memento Mori'' on March 20, 2020, with The Weeknd also hosting a Spotify listening session upon its release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-debuting-after-hours-on-memento-mori-next-week-news.106263.html|title=The Weeknd Debuting 'After Hours' On \"Memento Mori\" Next Week|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-spotify-listening-session|title=The Weeknd Is Hosting an 'After Hours' Listening Session on Spotify|website=Hypebeast|last=Ingvaldsen|first=Torsten|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A deluxe edition of the album containing five remixes was released without any prior notice on March 23, 2020.<ref name=\"Hypebeast1\">{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-deluxe-album-stream|title=The Weeknd Surprises Fans With Deluxe Version of 'After Hours'|website=Hypebeast|last=Li|first=Nicolaus|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On March 30, 2020, on the two-year anniversary of ''My Dear Melancholy'', an updated version of the deluxe edition containing three new bonus tracks was released.<ref name=\"Pitchfork1\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-shares-three-new-songs-listen/|title=The Weeknd Shares Three New Songs: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> A remix EP titled ''After Hours (Remixes)'' featuring the deluxe edition's remixes and an additional remix, was released on April 3, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://runthetrap.com/2020/04/01/the-weeknd-teases-after-hours-remix-ep/|title=The Weeknd Teases Upcoming 'After Hours' Remix EP|website=Run The Trap|last=Lopez|first=Riley|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artwork and aesthetic==\nThe artwork and aesthetic for the album's promotional material has been described as psychedelic and being inspired by various films, such as: ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)|Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]]'', ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'', ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'', and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', with the last film having a cameo appearance by The Weeknd himself.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3153297/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video/|title=The Weeknd Channels His Inner Joker in Mind-Frying 'Blinding Lights' Video|publisher=MTV News|last=Alston|first=Trey|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye's physical appearance in the era has been described by journalists as being red-pigmented,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/heres-everything-we-know-about-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours|title=Here's Everything We Know About The Weeknd's New Album 'After Hours'|website=Genius|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> with him consistently maintaining a red suit and specific hairstyle throughout all of the album's promotional material, such as its artwork, music videos, teasers, and live performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-new-album-after-hours-952501/|title=The Weeknd and His Mustache Announce New Album|website=Rolling Stone|last=Holmes|first=Charles|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The album's overall art direction was primarily handled by the Tammi brothers,<ref name=\"LN\"/> with its design being handled by Aleksi Tammi,<ref name=\"LN\"/> and its photography and visual direction being handled by Anton Tammi, who directed the music videos for the album's singles, and the project's same-titled short film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2020/01/22/who-is-anton-tammi-director-the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video/|title=Who is Anton Tammi? Director behind The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' music video|website=HITC Culture|last=Weston|first=Christopher|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The album's creative direction was handled by La Mar C. Taylor.<ref name=\"MBW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/confirmed-the-weeknds-after-hours-surpassed-a-million-pre-adds-on-apple-music-ahead-of-release/|title=Confirmed: The Weeknd's After Hours surpassed a million pre-adds on Apple Music ahead of release|website=Music Business Worldwide|last=Ingham|first=Tim|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nabil Elderkin]] handled the photography and video direction for the promotional material of the deluxe version of the project,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyfm.com.my/the-weeknd-drops-three-extra-songs-to-after-hours-album/|title=The Weeknd Drops Three Extra Songs To 'After Hours' Album|website=Fly FM|author=Elyda|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> in this material, Tesfaye continues the era's \"Sin City\" theme, with him residing within a casino and donning a black suit in the two teasers for the bonus tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-three-new-songs-after-hours-deluxe-edition|title=The Weeknd Drops 3 New Bonus 'After Hours' Songs|website=Complex|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Notably, the black suit used in the teasers for the deluxe edition of the album and cover art for the bonus tracks and remix EP was the first time The Weeknd worn a non-red suit in the promotional material for the project since his first live performance of \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' (dated December 6, 2019), in which he donned a blue suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-weeknd-peform-blinding-lights-onandnbspcolbert/|title=Watch the Weeknd Perform \"Blinding Lights\" on Colbert|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=December 7, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n\n===Tour===\n{{Main|The After Hours Tour}}\nOn February 20, 2020, [[The After Hours Tour]] was announced by The Weeknd through social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/02/20/the-weeknd-european-after-hours-tour|title=The Weeknd announces After Hours tour|website=The Fader|last=Renshaw|first=David|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> It is set to span North America and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/article/the-weeknd-announces-the-after-hours-world-tour-143648|title=The Weeknd Announces 'The After Hours' World Tour|website=Pollstar|last=Gottfried|first=Gideon|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The tour will last throughout the latter half of 2020, with it beginning on June 11 and ending on November 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whats-on/arts-and-entertainment/weeknd-after-hours-tour-2020-dates-set-list-pre-sale-details-and-how-get-tickets-glasgow-concert-1885105|title=Tickets, presale details, dates and venues for The Weeknd's After Hours Glasgow concert|website=Edinburgh Evening News|last=Nelson|first=Alex|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Sabrina Claudio]], [[Don Toliver]] and Black Atlass are set to open the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/the-weeknd-after-hours-tour-dates-sabrina-claudio-don-toliver-88glam|title=The Weeknd Announces New 'After Hours' Tour With Special Guests|website=Hypebeast|last=Johson|first=Patrick|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Performances===\nOn December 5, 2019, The Weeknd performed \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" for the first time on ''The Late Show with Stephen Colbert''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-heartless-colbert-923143/|title=Watch the Weeknd Perform Recent Single 'Heartless' on 'Colbert'|website=Rolling Stone|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=December 6, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" receiving its debut performance the following day on the same show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-new-song-919726/|title=The Weeknd Releases Full Version of New Song 'Blinding Lights'|website=Rolling Stone|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Both performances received positive reactions from critics and audiences, and were compared to those done by [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/the-weeknd-heartless-late-show-stephen-colbert-watch-video-1203427642/|title=Watch The Weeknd Perform 'Heartless' on 'The Late Show With Stephen Colbert'|website=Variety|last=Harris|first=LaTesha|date=December 6, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On January 22, 2020, \"Blinding Lights\" was performed at ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548553/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video|title=The Weeknd Gets Reckless in Sin City for Twisted 'Blinding Lights' Video|website=Billboard|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye's appearance during the performance on the show was inspired by the events that occurred within the aforementioned single's music video, which was released shortly before his live performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548806/the-weeknd-jimmy-kimmel-blinding-lights-video|title=The Weeknd Brings the 'Blinding Lights' to 'Kimmel' For Invigorating Performance: Watch|website=Billboard|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The Weeknd was announced as a performer for the March 7, 2020 episode of the [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|45th season]] of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/david-byrne-the-weeknd-saturday-night-live-musical-guest/|title=David Byrne and The Weeknd to perform on Saturday Night Live|website=Consequence of Sound|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> During his appearance, he performed a comedic track alongside [[Kenan Thompson]] and [[Chris Redd]], made specifically for the show, titled \"On the Couch\", and the songs: \"Blinding Lights\" and the previously unreleased \"[[Scared to Live]]\", the latter of which featured electronic musician [[Oneohtrix Point Never]] and interpolates \"[[Your Song]]\" by [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-weeknd-snl-video/|title=The Weeknd debuts new song on SNL, appears in \"On the Couch\" sketch: Watch|website=Consequence of Sound|last=Young|first=Alex|date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\nOn November 27, 2019, the album's lead single, \"Heartless\", was released digitally on music stores and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknds-excited-to-start-new-brain-melting-psychotic-chapter-news.96639.html|title=The Weeknd's Excited To Start \"New Brain Melting Psychotic Chapter\"|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The song was noticeably produced by American record producer [[Metro Boomin]]. At the time of its release, it was The Weeknd's first solo single since 2018's \"[[Call Out My Name]]\" from the EP ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' (2018). The single peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and became The Weeknd's fourth song to top the chart, with it also becoming Metro Boomin's second chart topper that he produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-heartless-no-1/|title=The Weeknd's 'Heartless' Hits No.1 On Billboard Hot 100|website=uDiscover|last=Stavropoulos|first=Laura|date=December 9, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its music video was released on December 3, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-weeknds-new-heartless-video/amp/|title=Watch the Weeknd's New \"Heartless\" Video|website=Pitchfork|last=Minsker|first=Evan|last2=Yoo|first2=Noah|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Blinding Lights\" was released digitally on music stores and streaming services on November 29, 2019, as the album's second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8544830/the-weeknd-new-music-mercedes-benz-commercial|title=Hear New Music From The Weeknd in Mercedes-Benz Commercial: Watch|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and reached number one in various other countries, becoming his first chart topper in the United Kingdom and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9346375/weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-hot-100|title=The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Doja Cat's 'Say So' Enters Top 10|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8550429/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-no-1-uk|title=First U.K. No. 1 Single for the Weeknd, Second Album Triumph For Blossoms|website=Billboard|last=Sexton|first=Paul|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/01/25/blinding-lights-becomes-the-weeknds-first-1-single-in-australia/|title=\"Blinding Lights\" Becomes The Weeknd's First #1 Single in Australia|website=Headline Planet|last=Cantor|first=Brian|date=January 25, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its music video is set in the aftermath of \"Heartless\"' visual and was released on January 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video|title=Watch The Weeknd's \"Blinding Lights\" Video|website=Complex|last=Ortiz|first=Edwin|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\" was released to [[rhythmic contemporary]] radio on March 24, 2020, as the album's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=March 21, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321082208/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Its music video follows the storyline of the previously released visuals and was released on March 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077699/the-weeknds-in-your-eyes-video-is-an-amazing-slasher-movie-parody/video/|title=The Weeknd's \"In Your Eyes\" Video Is An Amazing Slasher-Movie Parody: Watch|website=Stereogum|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional singles and other songs===\nOn February 18, 2020, Tesfaye announced the release of the album's [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] with the reveal of the album's cover art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8551359/the-weeknd-after-hours-release-date-title-track-release|title=The Weeknd Sets 'After Hours' Release Date, Shares Dark Title Track: Listen|website=Billboard|last=Brandle|first=Lars|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The promotional single reached the top 20 of various countries worldwide, including the United States, where it peaked at number 20 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9326707/roddy-ricch-the-box-number-one-eighth-week|title=BTS Sets New Career Best on Hot 100 as 'On' Blasts in at No. 4; Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Rules For Eighth Week|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 2, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, a music video for the album's closing track \"[[Until I Bleed Out]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/the-weeknd-until-i-bleed-out-music-video|title=The Weeknd Drops \"Until I Bleed Out\" Video|website=Complex|last=Cowen|first=Trace William|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The visuals for the song continue the themes found present throughout the promotional material for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd_continues_his_video_saga_with_until_i_bleed_out|title=The Weeknd Continues His Video Saga with \"Until I Bleed Out\"|website=Exclaim!|last=Thiessen|first=Brock|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Teaser and short film===\nOn February 13, 2020, The Weeknd released a 48-second teaser that announced the album's title. Journalists noted its resemblance to the digital work done in the 2019 film ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', which Tesfaye had a cameo in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-album-teaser-after-hours-watch-video-1203503446/|title=The Weeknd Drops Teaser for New Album, 'After Hours' (Watch)|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its visual were also compared to those found in the music videos for the album's first two singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popdust.com/the-weeknd-new-album-2645142098.html|title=The Weeknd Dramatically Announces His New Album|website=Popdust|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> \n\nA self titled short film for the album was first teased on March 3, 2020, with its release occurring on March 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-teases-after-hours-short-film-dropping-today-news.105402.html|title=The Weeknd Teases 'After Hours' Short Film Dropping Today|website=HotNewHipHop|last=S.|first=Lynn|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HotNewHipHop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-releases-after-hours-short-film-new-video.46027.html|title=The Weeknd Releases 'After Hours' Short Film|website=HotNewHipHop|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> It was directed by Anton Tammi and continued the storyline and aesthetics found in the visuals for \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\".<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film-watch-video-1203524075/|title=Watch The Weeknd's Disturbing Short Film for 'After Hours'|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The film is set shortly after The Weeknd's performance of \"Blinding Lights\" on ''Jimmy Kimmel Live!'' (dated January 22, 2020) and features various snippets of the tracks from the album as Tesfaye navigates a subway.<ref name=\"variety\"/> It concludes with The Weeknd seemingly murdering a couple in a secluded elevator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9328014/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film|title=The Weeknd &#34;After Hours&#34; Short Film: Watch|website=Billboard|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The visual was noted by journalists as being inspired by the films ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'' and ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''.<ref name=\"HotNewHipHop\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.7/10<ref name=\"ADM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11323/The-Weeknd-After-Hours.aspx|title=After Hours by The Weeknd reviews|publisher=AnyDecentMusic?|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 83/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/after-hours/the-weeknd|title=''After Hours'' by The Weeknd, Reviews and Tracks|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/after-hours-mw0003358815|title=After Hours \u2013 The Weeknd|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Kellman|first=Andy|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A\u2013<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-the-weeknd-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd \u2013 After Hours|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=McDuffie|first=Candace|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Evening Standard]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/the-weeknd-after-hours-review-a4392746.html|title=The Weeknd \u2013 After Hours review: Shadowy escapism for the great lock-in|work=[[Evening Standard]]|last=Smyth|first=David|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 8/10<ref name=\"Carey\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd-after_hours|title=The Weeknd After Hours|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Carey|first=Jacob|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Cragg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/20/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-review-abel-tesfaye|title=The Weeknd: After Hours review \u2013 agile blend of usual sex and self-hate|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Cragg|first=Michael|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/the-weeknd-album-review-after-hours-stream-tracklist-max-martin-features-lyrics-a9413706.html|title=The Weeknd review, After Hours: Music you listen to when the party's over|website=[[The Independent]]|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Britton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/the-weeknd-after-hours-review-his-most-all-encompassing-record-to-date-is-also-an-existential-quandary-2632591|title=The Weeknd \u2013 'After Hours' review: his most all-encompassing record to date is also an existential quandary|work=[[NME]]|last=Britton|first=Luke|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 7.9/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-weeknd-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd: After Hours Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Herrera|first=Isabella|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev9score = 8/10<ref name=\"PopMaatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/weeknd-after-hours-review-2645576658.html|title=The Weeknd: After Hours|website=[[PopMatters]]|last=Kim|first=Hans|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-971129/|title=The Weeknd is Alone Again, Naturally, on 'After Hours'|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Dolan|first=Jon|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''After Hours'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 83, based on 19 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 7.7 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"ADM\"/>\n\nWriting for ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', Candace McDuffie praised the album, stating that \"As he evolves, he continues to reinvent himself, and he knows exactly how to leave fans hooked on havoc. And After Hours is proof that he's not done with us yet; in fact, he's just getting started.\"<ref name=\"COS\"/> ''[[Exclaim!]]''{{'}}s reviewer Jacob Carey stated in his review that \"''After Hours'' does feel like the Weeknd's very own version of Vegas \u2013 a place where overindulgence, self-loathing and promiscuity are not only welcomed, but encouraged.\"<ref name=\"Carey\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s critic Michael Cragg gave ''After Hours'' a positive review, praising the \"sense of narrative cohesion\" on the album, saying that \"songs bleed into each other, with sonic references dotted throughout to neaten up threads that previously he [The Weeknd] would have left to unravel. By balancing the two sides of his musical personality \u2013 not to mention add some levity to that boring, bad-taste id \u2013 ''After Hours'' feels like the first Weeknd album in a while to offer up a clear, singular vision rather than something frustratingly abstract.\"<ref name=\"Cragg\" /> Writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', Roisin O'Connor stated that \"''After Hours'' abandons the danceability of its predecessor in favour of moody introspection. This is the music you listen to when the party's over.\" O'Connor further compared the album to The Weeknd's previous releases, saying that he on ''After Hours'' \"still delves into a sadboy persona but there's a tinge of remorse that runs through, in comparison to the cold and often cruel tone of earlier cuts.\"<ref name=\"Independent\" /> Luke Morgan Britton of ''[[NME]]'' called ''After Hours'' \"The Weeknd's strongest record in some time\" and that \"It's a record free of features and full of probing self-reflection.\"<ref name=\"Britton\" /> \n\nJon Dolan of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album a positive review, stating that \"''After Hours'' certainly has its share of pity-partying. But there's also a vulnerability that goes beyond the usual too-beautiful-for-the-world sulking.\" Dolan also said that the album \"hits the best balance yet of the gloomy melodrama of the Weeknd's early EPs or his 2018 release ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' and the pop slickness of his 2016 LP ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> Writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Jem Aswad praised the album, stating that \"The Weeknd is launching the next era with his most fully realized album yet, 'After Hours.' Sonically, the hallmarks are ultra-cinematic keyboards, pulsating sub-bass, hard beats (which are seldom danceable), '80s synthesizer flourishes and caverns of echo, all of which contrast with his high, angelic voice.\" Aswad ended his review by saying that \"''After Hours'' is one of the most successful musicians of the past decade testing the balance between innovation and commerciality as much as anyone today.\"<ref name=\"Aswad\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-review-1203539981/|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours': Album Review|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> David Smyth of ''[[Evening Standard]]'' particularly praised the song \"Blinding Lights\", while stating that The Weeknd's \"in a bit of a fug\" on the rest of the album.<ref name=\"ES\" />\n\n==Commercial performance==\nDespite the album not being released yet during the tracking period ending on February 27, 2020, ''After Hours'' managed to reach a position of number 10 on the US [[Rolling Stone Top 200|''Rolling Stone'' Top 200]] through the 36,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s provided by the already available singles at the time.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Top 200 (February 21, 2020 - February 27, 2020)\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/albums/2020-02-27/|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, 2020, ''After Hours'' broke the record for the most global pre-adds for an album in Apple Music history, with over 1.02&nbsp;million users pre-adding the album to their libraries.<ref name=\"MBW\"/> \n\n''After Hours'' debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 444,000 album-equivalent units, including 275,000 pure album sales. It is The Weeknd's fourth number-one album, and marks the biggest first week sales of 2020 for an album.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9345850/the-weeknd-after-hours-billboard-200-debut-2020-biggest-week|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart With Biggest Week of 2020|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, after the album's first week of availability, all 14 songs charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], with ten of them in the top 40, led by \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" at number one, and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\" debuting the highest, at number 16.<ref name=\"Every Song\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/9346588/every-song-weeknd-after-hours-hot-100|title=Every Song From The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Is on the Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Zellener|first=Xander|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The album remained at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 in its second week with 138,000 album-equivalent units, of which 47,000 were pure album sales. It is The Weeknd's third consecutive album to spend multiple weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9351457/the-weeknd-after-hours-no-1-billboard-200-chart|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> In its third week, the album remained at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 with 90,000 album-equivalent units (including 23,000 pure album sales). Becoming the first album to lead for three consecutive weeks since [[Post Malone]]'s ''[[Hollywood's Bleeding]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9356700/the-weeknd-after-hours-third-week-no-1-billboard-200|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Scores Third Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> In its fourth week, ''After Hours'' earned 75,000 album-equivalent units (including 20,000 pure album sales), remaining at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart. Its the first album to notch four consecutive weeks since [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s ''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9361577/the-weeknd-after-hours-billboard-200-albums-chart-month-no-1|title=The Weeknd Makes It a Month at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with over 26,000 units sold, making it The Weeknd's second number one on the chart, five years after ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-weeknd-scores-second-uk-number-1-album-with-after-hours__29226/|title=The Weeknd scores second UK Number 1 album with After Hours|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=Ainsley|first=Helen|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It also topped the chart in The Weeknd's native Canada, with 54,000 album-equivalent units.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2020/03/29/weeknd-has-weeks-no1-album|title=The Weeknd Has This Week's No.1 Album|website=FYIMusicNews|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from liner notes.<ref name=\"LN\">{{cite AV media notes|title=After Hours|type=CD liner notes|others=[[The Weeknd]]|publisher=[[XO (record label)|XO]] and [[Republic Records]]|year=2020|id=81839-4}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Track listing for ''After Hours''\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 56:14\n\n| title1 = Alone Again\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]|[[Jason Quenneville]]|[