ch 22, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n| released     = March 20, 2020\n| recorded     = 2018\u20132020\n| studio       = \n* [[Jungle City Studios|Jungle City]] (New York, New York)\n* [[Maratone Studios|MXM]] (Los Angeles, California)\n* [[Noble Street Studios|Noble Street]] (Toronto, Ontario)\n* XO ([[Hidden Hills, California]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shop.theweeknd.com/collections/all|title=ALL {{!}} T H E W E E K N D S H O P|website=The Weeknd Shop|accessdate=February 20, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203033816/https://shop.theweeknd.com/collections/all/products/collectors-7-vinyl-001-digital-single|archivedate=December 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| length       = 56:14\n| label        = \n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| genre        = \n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n* [[dream pop]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/>\n| producer     = \n* [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]]\n* [[Illangelo]]\n* [[Kevin Parker (musician)|Kevin Parker]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* [[Metro Boomin]]\n* Notinbed\n* [[Oneohtrix Point Never|OPN]]\n* [[Oscar Holter]]\n* Prince 85\n* [[Ricky Reed]]\n* [[The Weeknd]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Weeknd in Japan]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| year         = 2020\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc    = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative covers\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Weeknd - After Hours (Target edition).jpeg\n | caption = [[Target Corporation|Target]] and [[HMV]] exclusive CD cover\n }}{{Extra album cover\n | header  = no\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = The Weeknd - After Hours (Remixes).jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = ''After Hours (Remixes)'' cover\n }}{{Singles\n| name = After Hours\n| type = studio\n| single1 = [[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\n| single1date = November 27, 2019\n| single2 = [[Blinding Lights]]\n| single2date = November 29, 2019\n| single3 = [[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\n| single3date = March 24, 2020<!-- According to The Weeknd's own website, \"After Hours\" is not one of the album's single -->\n }}\n}}\n\n'''''After Hours''''' is the fourth studio album by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]]. The album was released by on March 20, 2020 by [[XO (record label)|XO]] and [[Republic Records]]. \n\nThe album was produced primarily by The Weeknd, along with a variety of high-profile producers such as [[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]], [[Illangelo]], and [[Metro Boomin]], all of whom The Weeknd had worked with previously. The standard edition has no features, although the deluxe edition contains [[guest appearance]]s from [[Chromatics (band)|Chromatics]] and [[Lil Uzi Vert]]. Music journalists have noted the album as an artistic reinvention for The Weeknd, with the introduction of [[New wave music|new wave]] and [[dream pop]] influences, while thematically, ''After Hours'' explores promiscuity, overindulgence, and self-loathing. \n\nThe artwork and aesthetic for the album's promotional material has been described as psychedelic and being inspired by various films, such as: ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'' (1995), ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)|Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]]'' (1998), ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'' and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (both 2019). The album was supported by three singles: \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\", \"[[Blinding Lights]]\", and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\", with \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\" peaking at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Its [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] was released as a promotional single. \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\" both received [[RIAA certification|platinum]] certifications in the US. In March 2020, ''After Hours'' broke the record for the most global pre-adds in [[Apple Music]] history, with over 1.02 million users.\n\n''After Hours'' received widespread acclaim, with some critics praising the album as The Weeknd's best piece of work. The album debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with 444,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, 275,000 of which were in pure sales. It is The Weeknd's fourth number-one album, and marks the biggest first week sales of 2020 for an album. The album also reached number one in 16 other countries, including the Canada and the United Kingdom. ''After Hours'' will be promoted with [[the After Hours Tour]], which is set to span [[North America]] and [[Europe]]. \n\n==Background and release==\nThe Weeknd first teased that he was working on a new album in November 2018, via a performance in which he told the crowd that \"''Chapter VI'' was coming soon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weeknd-teases-chapter-vi-album-shares-new-artwork-2413493|title=The Weeknd teases 'Chapter VI' album, shares new artwork|website=NME|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=November 27, 2018|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On January 12, 2019, Tesfaye then proceeded to further tease the project and its sound by tweeting \"no more daytime music\" to fans, making media outlets believe that he was set to continue the darker music found in ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weekend-says-new-album-will-be-less-pop-friendly-no-more-daytime-music-news.69193.html|title=The Weeknd Says New Album Will Be Less Pop-Friendly: \"No More Daytime Music\"|website=HotNewHipHop|last=Ch|first=Devin|date=January 13, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Following a trio of collaborative singles throughout 2019, on August 6, he further reassured fans that he was working on his fourth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-weekend-teases-new-album-chapter-6-2536077|title=Is The Weeknd's new album finally on its way?|website=NME|last=Skinner|first=Tom|date=August 7, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Then after a five-month period of silence,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-returns-to-instagram-and-fans-are-convinced-chapter-vi-is-coming-news.96171.html|title=The Weeknd Returns To Instagram & Fans Are Convinced \"Chapter VI\" Is Coming|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1095452/the-weeknd-returns-to-instagram-with-a-loading-message|title=The Weeknd Returns to Instagram With a \"Loading\" Message|publisher=[[E! Online]]|last=Schnurr|first=Samantha|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> on November 24, the single \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" was revealed through a [[Mercedes-Benz]] television commercial,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/24/the-weeknd-new-single-blinding-lights/|title=The Weeknd to Release New Single 'Blinding Lights' on Black Friday|website=Rap-Up|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> with reports of \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" surfacing a day later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/11/25/the-weeknd-teases-new-music/|title=The Weeknd Teases New Music|website=Rap-Up|date=November 25, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd_hints_at_new_music_arriving_tomorrow|title=The Weeknd Hints at New Music Arriving This Week|website=Exclaim!|last=Hudson|first=Alex|date=November 25, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The latter song then premiered on the seventh episode of The Weeknd's ''Memento Mori'' [[Beats 1]] radio show on November 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/11/the-weeknd-memento-mori-beats-1-show-episode-7|title=Stream The Weeknd's 'Memento Mori' Episode 7 on Beats 1 Radio|website=Complex|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Which in the hours leading into the release of the radio show episode, The Weeknd announced on social media his return to music with the captions \"the fall starts tomorrow night\" and \"Tonight we start a new brain melting psychotic chapter! Let's go!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2019/11/the-weeknd-to-release-2-new-singles-blinding-lights-heartless-this-week/|title=The Weeknd to Release 2 New Singles 'Blinding Lights' & \"Heartless\" This Week|website=HipHop-N-More|author=Akaash|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On February 13, 2020, The Weeknd revealed the title of the project \"After Hours\" through a 48-second teaser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3156604/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-teaser/|title=The Weeknd Announces New Album After Hours with an Ominous Teaser|publisher=MTV News|last=Roth|first=Madeline|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-announces-new-album-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd Announces New Album After Hours|website=Pitchfork|last=Yoo|first=Noah|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> A couple days after the announcement of the album's name, its release date of March 20, 2020, was shared through social media to accompany the [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]]'s release as a promotional single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-details-new-album-shares-new-song-after-hours-listen/|title=The Weeknd Details New Album, Shares New Song \"After Hours\"|website=Pitchfork|last=Hussey|first=Allison|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/the-weeknd-new-album-title-reveal/|title=The Weeknd Reveals The Title Of His New Album with a Surreal Teaser Video|website=Uppoxx|last=Williams|first=Aaron|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> In the last week leading up to the album's release, ''After Hours''' tracklist was revealed on March 17, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesource.com/2020/03/18/the-weeknd-after-hours-tracklist/|title=The Weeknd Reveals the Tracklist for 'After Hours' Album|website=The Source|last=Grant|first=Shawn|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, 2020, The Weeknd announced that the album is dedicated to long time fan and host of the popular XO Podcast, Lance, who died the night before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/19/the-weeknd-dedicates-after-hours-dead-fan/|title=The Weeknd Dedicates New Album 'After Hours' to Fan Who Died|website=Rap Up|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Dedicate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-dedicates-after-hours-to-late-fan|title=The Weeknd Dedicates 'After Hours' to Fan Who Passed Away|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Price|first=Joe|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The album debuted alongside the eighth episode of ''Memento Mori'' on March 20, 2020, with The Weeknd also hosting a Spotify listening session upon its release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-debuting-after-hours-on-memento-mori-next-week-news.106263.html|title=The Weeknd Debuting 'After Hours' On \"Memento Mori\" Next Week|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-spotify-listening-session|title=The Weeknd Is Hosting an 'After Hours' Listening Session on Spotify|website=Hypebeast|last=Ingvaldsen|first=Torsten|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A deluxe edition of the album containing five remixes was released without any prior notice on March 23, 2020.<ref name=\"Hypebeast1\">{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/3/the-weeknd-after-hours-deluxe-album-stream|title=The Weeknd Surprises Fans With Deluxe Version of 'After Hours'|website=Hypebeast|last=Li|first=Nicolaus|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On March 30, 2020, on the two-year anniversary of ''My Dear Melancholy'', an updated version of the deluxe edition containing three new bonus tracks was released.<ref name=\"Pitchfork1\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-shares-three-new-songs-listen/|title=The Weeknd Shares Three New Songs: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> A remix EP titled ''After Hours (Remixes)'' featuring the deluxe edition's remixes and an additional remix, was released on April 3, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://runthetrap.com/2020/04/01/the-weeknd-teases-after-hours-remix-ep/|title=The Weeknd Teases Upcoming 'After Hours' Remix EP|website=Run The Trap|last=Lopez|first=Riley|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artwork and aesthetic==\nThe artwork and aesthetic for the album's promotional material has been described as psychedelic and being inspired by various films, such as: ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)|Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]]'', ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'', ''[[Casino (1995 film)|Casino]]'', and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', with the last film having a cameo appearance by The Weeknd himself.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3153297/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video/|title=The Weeknd Channels His Inner Joker in Mind-Frying 'Blinding Lights' Video|publisher=MTV News|last=Alston|first=Trey|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye's physical appearance in the era has been described by journalists as being red-pigmented,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/heres-everything-we-know-about-the-weeknds-new-album-after-hours|title=Here's Everything We Know About The Weeknd's New Album 'After Hours'|website=Genius|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> with him consistently maintaining a red suit and specific hairstyle throughout all of the album's promotional material, such as its artwork, music videos, teasers, and live performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-new-album-after-hours-952501/|title=The Weeknd and His Mustache Announce New Album|website=Rolling Stone|last=Holmes|first=Charles|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The album's overall art direction was primarily handled by the Tammi brothers,<ref name=\"LN\"/> with its design being handled by Aleksi Tammi,<ref name=\"LN\"/> and its photography and visual direction being handled by Anton Tammi, who directed the music videos for the album's singles, and the project's same-titled short film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2020/01/22/who-is-anton-tammi-director-the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video/|title=Who is Anton Tammi? Director behind The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' music video|website=HITC Culture|last=Weston|first=Christopher|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The album's creative direction was handled by La Mar C. Taylor.<ref name=\"MBW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/confirmed-the-weeknds-after-hours-surpassed-a-million-pre-adds-on-apple-music-ahead-of-release/|title=Confirmed: The Weeknd's After Hours surpassed a million pre-adds on Apple Music ahead of release|website=Music Business Worldwide|last=Ingham|first=Tim|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nabil Elderkin]] handled the photography and video direction for the promotional material of the deluxe version of the project,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyfm.com.my/the-weeknd-drops-three-extra-songs-to-after-hours-album/|title=The Weeknd Drops Three Extra Songs To 'After Hours' Album|website=Fly FM|author=Elyda|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> in this material, Tesfaye continues the era's \"Sin City\" theme, with him residing within a casino and donning a black suit in the two teasers for the bonus tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-three-new-songs-after-hours-deluxe-edition|title=The Weeknd Drops 3 New Bonus 'After Hours' Songs|website=Complex|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Notably, the black suit used in the teasers for the deluxe edition of the album and cover art for the bonus tracks and remix EP was the first time The Weeknd worn a non-red suit in the promotional material for the project since his first live performance of \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' (dated December 6, 2019), in which he donned a blue suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-weeknd-peform-blinding-lights-onandnbspcolbert/|title=Watch the Weeknd Perform \"Blinding Lights\" on Colbert|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=December 7, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n\n===Tour===\n{{Main|The After Hours Tour}}\nOn February 20, 2020, [[The After Hours Tour]] was announced by The Weeknd through social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/02/20/the-weeknd-european-after-hours-tour|title=The Weeknd announces After Hours tour|website=The Fader|last=Renshaw|first=David|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> It is set to span North America and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/article/the-weeknd-announces-the-after-hours-world-tour-143648|title=The Weeknd Announces 'The After Hours' World Tour|website=Pollstar|last=Gottfried|first=Gideon|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The tour will last throughout the latter half of 2020, with it beginning on June 11 and ending on November 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whats-on/arts-and-entertainment/weeknd-after-hours-tour-2020-dates-set-list-pre-sale-details-and-how-get-tickets-glasgow-concert-1885105|title=Tickets, presale details, dates and venues for The Weeknd's After Hours Glasgow concert|website=Edinburgh Evening News|last=Nelson|first=Alex|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Sabrina Claudio]], [[Don Toliver]] and Black Atlass are set to open the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2020/2/the-weeknd-after-hours-tour-dates-sabrina-claudio-don-toliver-88glam|title=The Weeknd Announces New 'After Hours' Tour With Special Guests|website=Hypebeast|last=Johson|first=Patrick|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Performances===\nOn December 5, 2019, The Weeknd performed \"[[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\" for the first time on ''The Late Show with Stephen Colbert''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-heartless-colbert-923143/|title=Watch the Weeknd Perform Recent Single 'Heartless' on 'Colbert'|website=Rolling Stone|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=December 6, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" receiving its debut performance the following day on the same show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-new-song-919726/|title=The Weeknd Releases Full Version of New Song 'Blinding Lights'|website=Rolling Stone|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Both performances received positive reactions from critics and audiences, and were compared to those done by [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/the-weeknd-heartless-late-show-stephen-colbert-watch-video-1203427642/|title=Watch The Weeknd Perform 'Heartless' on 'The Late Show With Stephen Colbert'|website=Variety|last=Harris|first=LaTesha|date=December 6, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> On January 22, 2020, \"Blinding Lights\" was performed at ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548553/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video|title=The Weeknd Gets Reckless in Sin City for Twisted 'Blinding Lights' Video|website=Billboard|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Tesfaye's appearance during the performance on the show was inspired by the events that occurred within the aforementioned single's music video, which was released shortly before his live performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8548806/the-weeknd-jimmy-kimmel-blinding-lights-video|title=The Weeknd Brings the 'Blinding Lights' to 'Kimmel' For Invigorating Performance: Watch|website=Billboard|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=January 23, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The Weeknd was announced as a performer for the March 7, 2020 episode of the [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|45th season]] of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/02/david-byrne-the-weeknd-saturday-night-live-musical-guest/|title=David Byrne and The Weeknd to perform on Saturday Night Live|website=Consequence of Sound|last=Schatz|first=Lake|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> During his appearance, he performed a comedic track alongside [[Kenan Thompson]] and [[Chris Redd]], made specifically for the show, titled \"On the Couch\", and the songs: \"Blinding Lights\" and the previously unreleased \"[[Scared to Live]]\", the latter of which featured electronic musician [[Oneohtrix Point Never]] and interpolates \"[[Your Song]]\" by [[Elton John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/the-weeknd-snl-video/|title=The Weeknd debuts new song on SNL, appears in \"On the Couch\" sketch: Watch|website=Consequence of Sound|last=Young|first=Alex|date=March 8, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\nOn November 27, 2019, the album's lead single, \"Heartless\", was released digitally on music stores and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknds-excited-to-start-new-brain-melting-psychotic-chapter-news.96639.html|title=The Weeknd's Excited To Start \"New Brain Melting Psychotic Chapter\"|website=HotNewHipHop|last=A.|first=Aron|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The song was noticeably produced by American record producer [[Metro Boomin]]. At the time of its release, it was The Weeknd's first solo single since 2018's \"[[Call Out My Name]]\" from the EP ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' (2018). The single peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and became The Weeknd's fourth song to top the chart, with it also becoming Metro Boomin's second chart topper that he produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/the-weeknd-heartless-no-1/|title=The Weeknd's 'Heartless' Hits No.1 On Billboard Hot 100|website=uDiscover|last=Stavropoulos|first=Laura|date=December 9, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its music video was released on December 3, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-the-weeknds-new-heartless-video/amp/|title=Watch the Weeknd's New \"Heartless\" Video|website=Pitchfork|last=Minsker|first=Evan|last2=Yoo|first2=Noah|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Blinding Lights\" was released digitally on music stores and streaming services on November 29, 2019, as the album's second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8544830/the-weeknd-new-music-mercedes-benz-commercial|title=Hear New Music From The Weeknd in Mercedes-Benz Commercial: Watch|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=November 26, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and reached number one in various other countries, becoming his first chart topper in the United Kingdom and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9346375/weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-hot-100|title=The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Doja Cat's 'Say So' Enters Top 10|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8550429/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-no-1-uk|title=First U.K. No. 1 Single for the Weeknd, Second Album Triumph For Blossoms|website=Billboard|last=Sexton|first=Paul|date=February 7, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/01/25/blinding-lights-becomes-the-weeknds-first-1-single-in-australia/|title=\"Blinding Lights\" Becomes The Weeknd's First #1 Single in Australia|website=Headline Planet|last=Cantor|first=Brian|date=January 25, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its music video is set in the aftermath of \"Heartless\"' visual and was released on January 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/01/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-video|title=Watch The Weeknd's \"Blinding Lights\" Video|website=Complex|last=Ortiz|first=Edwin|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\" was released to [[rhythmic contemporary]] radio on March 24, 2020, as the album's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=March 21, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321082208/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Its music video follows the storyline of the previously released visuals and was released on March 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077699/the-weeknds-in-your-eyes-video-is-an-amazing-slasher-movie-parody/video/|title=The Weeknd's \"In Your Eyes\" Video Is An Amazing Slasher-Movie Parody: Watch|website=Stereogum|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional singles and other songs===\nOn February 18, 2020, Tesfaye announced the release of the album's [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|title track]] with the reveal of the album's cover art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8551359/the-weeknd-after-hours-release-date-title-track-release|title=The Weeknd Sets 'After Hours' Release Date, Shares Dark Title Track: Listen|website=Billboard|last=Brandle|first=Lars|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> The promotional single reached the top 20 of various countries worldwide, including the United States, where it peaked at number 20 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9326707/roddy-ricch-the-box-number-one-eighth-week|title=BTS Sets New Career Best on Hot 100 as 'On' Blasts in at No. 4; Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Rules For Eighth Week|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 2, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, a music video for the album's closing track \"[[Until I Bleed Out]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/the-weeknd-until-i-bleed-out-music-video|title=The Weeknd Drops \"Until I Bleed Out\" Video|website=Complex|last=Cowen|first=Trace William|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The visuals for the song continue the themes found present throughout the promotional material for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd_continues_his_video_saga_with_until_i_bleed_out|title=The Weeknd Continues His Video Saga with \"Until I Bleed Out\"|website=Exclaim!|last=Thiessen|first=Brock|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Teaser and short film===\nOn February 13, 2020, The Weeknd released a 48-second teaser that announced the album's title. Journalists noted its resemblance to the digital work done in the 2019 film ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', which Tesfaye had a cameo in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/weeknd-album-teaser-after-hours-watch-video-1203503446/|title=The Weeknd Drops Teaser for New Album, 'After Hours' (Watch)|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> Its visual were also compared to those found in the music videos for the album's first two singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popdust.com/the-weeknd-new-album-2645142098.html|title=The Weeknd Dramatically Announces His New Album|website=Popdust|last=Cummings-Grady|first=Mackenzie|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref> \n\nA self titled short film for the album was first teased on March 3, 2020, with its release occurring on March 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-teases-after-hours-short-film-dropping-today-news.105402.html|title=The Weeknd Teases 'After Hours' Short Film Dropping Today|website=HotNewHipHop|last=S.|first=Lynn|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"HotNewHipHop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-releases-after-hours-short-film-new-video.46027.html|title=The Weeknd Releases 'After Hours' Short Film|website=HotNewHipHop|last=Zidel|first=Alex|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> It was directed by Anton Tammi and continued the storyline and aesthetics found in the visuals for \"Heartless\" and \"Blinding Lights\".<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film-watch-video-1203524075/|title=Watch The Weeknd's Disturbing Short Film for 'After Hours'|website=Variety|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The film is set shortly after The Weeknd's performance of \"Blinding Lights\" on ''Jimmy Kimmel Live!'' (dated January 22, 2020) and features various snippets of the tracks from the album as Tesfaye navigates a subway.<ref name=\"variety\"/> It concludes with The Weeknd seemingly murdering a couple in a secluded elevator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9328014/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film|title=The Weeknd &#34;After Hours&#34; Short Film: Watch|website=Billboard|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The visual was noted by journalists as being inspired by the films ''[[Joker (2019 film)|Joker]]'' and ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''.<ref name=\"HotNewHipHop\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.7/10<ref name=\"ADM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11323/The-Weeknd-After-Hours.aspx|title=After Hours by The Weeknd reviews|publisher=AnyDecentMusic?|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 83/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/after-hours/the-weeknd|title=''After Hours'' by The Weeknd, Reviews and Tracks|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/after-hours-mw0003358815|title=After Hours \u2013 The Weeknd|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Kellman|first=Andy|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A\u2013<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-the-weeknd-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd \u2013 After Hours|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=McDuffie|first=Candace|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Evening Standard]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ES\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/the-weeknd-after-hours-review-a4392746.html|title=The Weeknd \u2013 After Hours review: Shadowy escapism for the great lock-in|work=[[Evening Standard]]|last=Smyth|first=David|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 8/10<ref name=\"Carey\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/the_weeknd-after_hours|title=The Weeknd After Hours|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Carey|first=Jacob|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Cragg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/20/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-review-abel-tesfaye|title=The Weeknd: After Hours review \u2013 agile blend of usual sex and self-hate|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Cragg|first=Michael|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/the-weeknd-album-review-after-hours-stream-tracklist-max-martin-features-lyrics-a9413706.html|title=The Weeknd review, After Hours: Music you listen to when the party's over|website=[[The Independent]]|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Britton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/the-weeknd-after-hours-review-his-most-all-encompassing-record-to-date-is-also-an-existential-quandary-2632591|title=The Weeknd \u2013 'After Hours' review: his most all-encompassing record to date is also an existential quandary|work=[[NME]]|last=Britton|first=Luke|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 7.9/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/the-weeknd-after-hours/|title=The Weeknd: After Hours Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Herrera|first=Isabella|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev9score = 8/10<ref name=\"PopMaatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/weeknd-after-hours-review-2645576658.html|title=The Weeknd: After Hours|website=[[PopMatters]]|last=Kim|first=Hans|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-971129/|title=The Weeknd is Alone Again, Naturally, on 'After Hours'|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Dolan|first=Jon|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''After Hours'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 83, based on 19 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 7.7 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"ADM\"/>\n\nWriting for ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', Candace McDuffie praised the album, stating that \"As he evolves, he continues to reinvent himself, and he knows exactly how to leave fans hooked on havoc. And After Hours is proof that he's not done with us yet; in fact, he's just getting started.\"<ref name=\"COS\"/> ''[[Exclaim!]]''{{'}}s reviewer Jacob Carey stated in his review that \"''After Hours'' does feel like the Weeknd's very own version of Vegas \u2013 a place where overindulgence, self-loathing and promiscuity are not only welcomed, but encouraged.\"<ref name=\"Carey\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s critic Michael Cragg gave ''After Hours'' a positive review, praising the \"sense of narrative cohesion\" on the album, saying that \"songs bleed into each other, with sonic references dotted throughout to neaten up threads that previously he [The Weeknd] would have left to unravel. By balancing the two sides of his musical personality \u2013 not to mention add some levity to that boring, bad-taste id \u2013 ''After Hours'' feels like the first Weeknd album in a while to offer up a clear, singular vision rather than something frustratingly abstract.\"<ref name=\"Cragg\" /> Writing for ''[[The Independent]]'', Roisin O'Connor stated that \"''After Hours'' abandons the danceability of its predecessor in favour of moody introspection. This is the music you listen to when the party's over.\" O'Connor further compared the album to The Weeknd's previous releases, saying that he on ''After Hours'' \"still delves into a sadboy persona but there's a tinge of remorse that runs through, in comparison to the cold and often cruel tone of earlier cuts.\"<ref name=\"Independent\" /> Luke Morgan Britton of ''[[NME]]'' called ''After Hours'' \"The Weeknd's strongest record in some time\" and that \"It's a record free of features and full of probing self-reflection.\"<ref name=\"Britton\" /> \n\nJon Dolan of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album a positive review, stating that \"''After Hours'' certainly has its share of pity-partying. But there's also a vulnerability that goes beyond the usual too-beautiful-for-the-world sulking.\" Dolan also said that the album \"hits the best balance yet of the gloomy melodrama of the Weeknd's early EPs or his 2018 release ''[[My Dear Melancholy]]'' and the pop slickness of his 2016 LP ''[[Starboy (album)|Starboy]]''.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> Writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Jem Aswad praised the album, stating that \"The Weeknd is launching the next era with his most fully realized album yet, 'After Hours.' Sonically, the hallmarks are ultra-cinematic keyboards, pulsating sub-bass, hard beats (which are seldom danceable), '80s synthesizer flourishes and caverns of echo, all of which contrast with his high, angelic voice.\" Aswad ended his review by saying that \"''After Hours'' is one of the most successful musicians of the past decade testing the balance between innovation and commerciality as much as anyone today.\"<ref name=\"Aswad\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/reviews/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-review-1203539981/|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours': Album Review|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Aswad|first=Jem|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> David Smyth of ''[[Evening Standard]]'' particularly praised the song \"Blinding Lights\", while stating that The Weeknd's \"in a bit of a fug\" on the rest of the album.<ref name=\"ES\" />\n\n==Commercial performance==\nDespite the album not being released yet during the tracking period ending on February 27, 2020, ''After Hours'' managed to reach a position of number 10 on the US [[Rolling Stone Top 200|''Rolling Stone'' Top 200]] through the 36,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s provided by the already available singles at the time.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Top 200 (February 21, 2020 - February 27, 2020)\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/albums/2020-02-27/|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, 2020, ''After Hours'' broke the record for the most global pre-adds for an album in Apple Music history, with over 1.02&nbsp;million users pre-adding the album to their libraries.<ref name=\"MBW\"/> \n\n''After Hours'' debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 444,000 album-equivalent units, including 275,000 pure album sales. It is The Weeknd's fourth number-one album, and marks the biggest first week sales of 2020 for an album.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9345850/the-weeknd-after-hours-billboard-200-debut-2020-biggest-week|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart With Biggest Week of 2020|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, after the album's first week of availability, all 14 songs charted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], with ten of them in the top 40, led by \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" at number one, and \"[[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\" debuting the highest, at number 16.<ref name=\"Every Song\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/9346588/every-song-weeknd-after-hours-hot-100|title=Every Song From The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Is on the Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Zellener|first=Xander|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The album remained at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 in its second week with 138,000 album-equivalent units, of which 47,000 were pure album sales. It is The Weeknd's third consecutive album to spend multiple weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9351457/the-weeknd-after-hours-no-1-billboard-200-chart|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> In its third week, the album remained at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 with 90,000 album-equivalent units (including 23,000 pure album sales). Becoming the first album to lead for three consecutive weeks since [[Post Malone]]'s ''[[Hollywood's Bleeding]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9356700/the-weeknd-after-hours-third-week-no-1-billboard-200|title=The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Scores Third Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> In its fourth week, ''After Hours'' earned 75,000 album-equivalent units (including 20,000 pure album sales), remaining at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart. Its the first album to notch four consecutive weeks since [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s ''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9361577/the-weeknd-after-hours-billboard-200-albums-chart-month-no-1|title=The Weeknd Makes It a Month at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe album debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with over 26,000 units sold, making it The Weeknd's second number one on the chart, five years after ''[[Beauty Behind the Madness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-weeknd-scores-second-uk-number-1-album-with-after-hours__29226/|title=The Weeknd scores second UK Number 1 album with After Hours|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=Ainsley|first=Helen|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It also topped the chart in The Weeknd's native Canada, with 54,000 album-equivalent units.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2020/03/29/weeknd-has-weeks-no1-album|title=The Weeknd Has This Week's No.1 Album|website=FYIMusicNews|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from liner notes.<ref name=\"LN\">{{cite AV media notes|title=After Hours|type=CD liner notes|others=[[The Weeknd]]|publisher=[[XO (record label)|XO]] and [[Republic Records]]|year=2020|id=81839-4}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Track listing for ''After Hours''\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 56:14\n\n| title1 = Alone Again\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]|[[Jason Quenneville]]|[[Illangelo|Carlo Montagnese]]|[[Frank Dukes|Adam Feeney]]}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|[[Illangelo]]|[[The Weeknd]]|[[Jason Quenneville|DaHeala]]|[[Frank Dukes]]{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length1 = 4:10\n\n| title2 = Too Late\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville|Montagnese|[[Ricky Reed|Eric Burton Frederic]]}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Illangelo|[[Ricky Reed]]|The Weeknd|DaHeala|Nate Mercereau{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:59\n\n| title3 = Hardest to Love\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|[[Max Martin|Karl Martin Sandberg]]|[[Oscar Holter]]}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|[[Max Martin]]|Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| length3 = 3:31\n\n| title4 = [[Scared to Live]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|[[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balshe]]|Sandberg|Holter|[[Oneohtrix Point Never|Daniel Lopatin]]|[[Elton John]]|[[Bernie Taupin|Bernard Taupin]]}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Martin|Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| length4 = 3:11\n\n| title5 = Snowchild\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville|Balshe|Montagnese}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Illangelo|The Weeknd|DaHeala}}\n| length5 = 4:07\n\n| title6 = Escape from LA\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Montagnese|[[Metro Boomin|Leland Tyler Wayne]]|Mike McTaggart}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|[[Metro Boomin]]|The Weeknd|Illangelo}}\n| length6 = 5:55\n\n| title7 = [[Heartless (The Weeknd song)|Heartless]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Wayne|Montagnese|[[Dre Moon|Andre Proctor]]}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Metro Boomin|The Weeknd|Illangelo|[[Dre Moon]]{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length7 = 3:18\n\n| title8 = [[Faith (The Weeknd song)|Faith]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Montagnese|Wayne}}\n| extra8 = {{hlist|Metro Boomin|The Weeknd|Illangelo}}\n| length8 = 4:43\n\n| title9 = [[Blinding Lights]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Quenneville|Sandberg|Holter}}\n| extra9 = {{hlist|Martin|Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| length9 = 3:20\n\n| title10 = [[In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)|In Your Eyes]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Sandberg|Holter}}\n| extra10 = {{hlist|Martin|Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| length10 = 3:57\n\n| title11 = Save Your Tears\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Quenneville|Sandberg|Holter}}\n| extra11 = {{hlist|Martin|Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| length11 = 3:35\n\n| title12 = Repeat After Me\n| note12 = interlude\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|[[Kevin Parker (musician)|Kevin Parker]]|Lopatin}}\n| extra12 = {{hlist|Parker|[[Oneohtrix Point Never|OPN]]}}\n| length12 = 3:15\n\n| title13 = [[After Hours (The Weeknd song)|After Hours]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville|Balshe|Montagnese|[[Mario Winans]]}}\n| extra13 = {{hlist|Illangelo|The Weeknd|DaHeala|Winans{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length13 = 6:01\n\n| title14 = [[Until I Bleed Out]]\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Wayne|Lopatin|Mejdi Rhars|Notinbed}}\n| extra14 = {{hlist|Metro Boomin|OPN|Prince 85|The Weeknd|Notinbed}}\n| length14 = 3:12\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Deluxe bonus tracks<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/after-hours-deluxe/1503714215|title=After Hours (Deluxe) by The Weeknd|website=Apple Music|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 65:25\n\n| title15 = Nothing Compares\n| writer15 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Quenneville|Frederic}}\n| extra15 = {{hlist|DaHeala|Ricky Reed|The Weeknd}}\n| length15 = 3:42\n\n| title16 = Missed You\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville}}\n| extra16 = {{hlist|DaHeala|The Weeknd}}\n| length16 = 2:24\n\n| title17 = Final Lullaby\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville}}\n| extra17 = {{hlist|DaHeala|The Weeknd}}\n| length17 = 3:05\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Remixes'' EP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/after-hours-remixes-ep/1505665120|title=After Hours (Remixes) by The Weeknd|website=Apple Music|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| extra_column = Remixer\n| total_length = 21:41\n\n| title1 = Heartless\n| note1 = <!-- Just named 'remix' on track listing -->remix; featuring [[Lil Uzi Vert]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Wayne|Montagnese|Proctor|[[Lil Uzi Vert|Symere Woods]]}}\n| extra1 = <!-- There isn't actually a 'remixer' for this track. It's just the original instrumental with a new verse by Lil Uzi Vert -->\n| length1 = 3:20\n\n| title2 = Blinding Lights\n| note2 = [[Chromatics (band)|Chromatics]] remix; featuring Chromatics\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville|Sandberg|Holter|Nathaniel Stanton Miller|[[Johnny Jewel|John David Padgett]]}}\n| extra2 = [[Johnny Jewel]]\n| length2 = 4:21\n\n| title3 = Save Your Tears\n| note3 = [[Oneohtrix Point Never|OPN]] remix\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Quenneville|Sandberg|Holter|Lopatin}}\n| extra3 = OPN\n| length3 = 3:40\n\n| title4 = Heartless\n| note4 = [[vaporwave]] remix; featuring Lil Uzi Vert\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Wayne|Montagnese|Proctor|Symere Woods|Quenneville}}\n| extra4 = DaHeala\n| length4 = 2:45\n\n| title5 = After Hours\n| note5 = [[The Blaze (band)|The Blaze]] remix\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Quenneville|Balshe|Montagnese|Winans|[[The Blaze (band)|Guillaume Alric]]|[[The Blaze (band)|Jonathan Alric]]}}\n| extra5 = [[The Blaze (band)|The Blaze]]\n| length5 = 3:58\n\n| title6 = Scared to Live\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Tesfaye|Balshe|Sandberg|Holter|Lopatin|John|Taupin}}\n| note6 = ''[[Saturday Night Live|SNL]]'' live\n| extra6 = \n| length6 = 3:37\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* {{sup|{{note|a|[a]}}}} signifies a co-producer\n* {{sup|{{note|b|[b]}}}} signifies an additional producer\n* The deluxe edition of the album was initially released on March 23, featuring tracks 2\u20136 of the ''Remixes'' EP as bonus tracks. On March 30, the release was updated to include three new bonus tracks before the remixes. On April 3, the remixes were released as a separate [[extended play|EP]], with track 1 added, while the deluxe edition of the album was amended to end at \"Final Lullaby\".<ref name=\"EP\">{{cite tweet|number=1244747961138987008|title=just a heads up, deluxe will end with final lullaby. putting remixes on a separate ep. it'll be updated friday. xo|user=theweeknd|author=The Weeknd|authorlink=The Weeknd|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Sample credits'''\n* \"Scared to Live\" contains interpolations from \"[[Your Song]]\", written by [[Elton John]] and [[Bernie Taupin|Bernard Taupin]].\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from liner notes.<ref name=\"LN\"/>\n\n'''Musicians'''\n* [[Metro Boomin]] \u2013 keyboards {{small|(track 7)}}, programming {{small|(track 7)}}\n* [[The Weeknd]] \u2013 vocals, keyboards, programming {{small|(tracks 1, 2, 3, 7, 9, 13)}}, bass, guitar, drums {{small|(track 9)}}\n* [[Max Martin]] \u2013 bass, drums, guitar, keyboards, programming {{small|(tracks 3, 9)}}\n* [[Oscar Holter]] \u2013 bass, dr