tps://shop.theweeknd.com/collections/music/products/after-hours-signed-deluxe-jewel-case-digital-album?c=%2Fcollections%2Fmusic&t=Music|title=AFTER HOURS SIGNED DELUXE JEWEL CASE + DIGITAL ALBUM|website=T H E W E E K N D S H O P|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 2020 albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|0dXLhjAxUl8|Album Title (Teaser)}}\n* {{YouTube|oq9AgxHvGjw|After Hours (Short film)}}\n\n{{The Weeknd}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Illangelo]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Metro Boomin]]\n[[Category:Republic Records albums]]\n[[Category:The Weeknd albums]]\n", "name_user": "MrloniBoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/After_Hours_(The_Weeknd_album)"}
{"title_page": "Justice delayed is justice denied", "text_new": "{{short description|Legal maxim}}\n'''\"Justice delayed is justice denied\"''' is a [[legal maxim]] meaning that if [[Legal remedy|legal redress]] or [[Equitable relief|equitable relief]] is available for a party that has suffered some injury, but is not forthcoming in a timely fashion, it is effectively the same as having no redress at all. This principle is the basis for the right to a [[speedy trial]] and similar rights which are meant to expedite the legal system, because it is unfair for the injured party to have to sustain the injury with little hope for resolution. The phrase has become a rallying cry for [[law reform|legal reformers]] who view [[court]]s, [[Judge|judge]]s, [[arbitrator]]s, [[administrative law judge]]s, [[commission]]s{{efn-ua|Defined broadly to include [[government agency]], [[regulatory agency]] or [[statutory authority]] that operates under the authority of a board of commissioners, including [[Independent agencies of the United States government]].}} or [[government]]s as acting too slowly in resolving legal issues either because the existing system is too complex or overburdened, or because the issue or party in question lacks political favour. When a court takes a matter \"under advisement\" {{ndash}} awaiting the issuance of a [[judicial opinion]], [[Court order|order]] or [[judgement]] and forestalls final [[Adjudication|adjudication]] or resolution of a [[Motion (legal)|motion]] {{ndash}} the issue of timeliness of the decision comes into play.\n\n== Origin ==\nThere are conflicting accounts of who first noted the phrase. According to ''Respectfully Quoted: A Dictionary of Quotations'', it is attributable to [[William Ewart Gladstone]], but such attribution was not verifiable.<ref>Suzy Platt (ed.). [http://www.bartleby.com/73/954.html Entry 954. William Ewart Gladstone (1809\u201398)]. ''Respectfully Quoted: A Dictionary of Quotations Requested from the Congressional Research Service''. [[Library of Congress]], 1989. (Attributed to William E. Gladstone. \u2014 Laurence J. Peter, ''Peter\u2019s Quotations'', p. 276 (1977). Unverified.)</ref> Alternatively, it may be attributed to [[William Penn]] in the form \"to delay Justice is Injustice\".<ref>Penn, William (1693), ''[https://archive.org/stream/somefruitssolit00penngoog#page/n92/mode/1up Some Fruits of Solitude]'', Headley, 1905, p. 86.</ref>\n\nMentions of justice delayed and denied are found in the [[Pirkei Avot]] 5:7, a section of the [[Mishnah]] (1st century BCE \u2013 2nd century CE): \"Our Rabbis taught: ...The sword comes into the world, because of justice delayed and justice denied...\". [[Nachmanides]] understands the advice given by [[Jethro (Bible)|Jethro]] in [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 18:22, to judge the people at all times, as suggesting that Israel needed more judges because potential litigants would otherwise suffer injustice due to their inability to find a judge to hear their case.<ref>[http://tmt.urj.net/archives/4jewishethics/052605.htm 10 Minutes of Torah. Ethical Teachings Selections from Pirkei Avot]. Retrieved 26 March 2013 {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Magna Carta]]'' of 1215, clause 40 of which reads, \"To no one will we sell, to no one will we refuse or delay, right or justice.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/evolutionofparliament/originsofparliament/birthofparliament/overview/magnacarta/magnacartaclauses/ |title=Birth of Parliament |publisher=[[British Parliament]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], used the phrase in the form \"justice too long delayed is justice denied\" in his \"[[Letter from Birmingham Jail]]\", smuggled out of jail in 1963, ascribing it to \"one of our distinguished jurists\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Articles_Gen/Letter_Birmingham.html|title=\"Letter from a Birmingham Jail [King, Jr.]\"|last=|first=|date=|website=African Studies Center - University of Pennsylvania|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190323113329/https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Articles_Gen/Letter_Birmingham.html|archive-date=2019-03-23|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nThe broader [[public policy]] implications are a source of concern. As Chief Justice of the United States [[Warren E. Burger]] noted in an address to the [[American Bar Association]] in 1970:\n<blockquote>\"A sense of confidence in the courts is essential to maintain the fabric of ordered liberty for a free people and three things could destroy that confidence and do incalculable damage to society: that people come to believe that inefficiency and delay will drain even a just judgment of its value; that people who have long been exploited in the smaller transactions of daily life come to believe that courts cannot vindicate their legal rights from fraud and over-reaching; that people come to believe the law \u2013 in the larger sense \u2013 cannot fulfill its primary function to protect them and their families in their homes, at their work, and on the public streets.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Burger |first1=Warren E. |date=August 24, 1970 |title=What's Wrong With the Courts: The Chief Justice Speaks Out (address to ABA meeting, Aug. 10, 1970) |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |volume=69 |number=8 |pages=68, 71}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLack of a speedy and effective resolution (amidst a bewildering multiplicity of statutes and forums with overlapping [[jurisdiction]]) can cause unwarranted delay. It has been observed that it creates a sense of frustration and unfairness, and a feeling of a lack of [[efficacy]], which adversely affects [[employee morale]] and [[labor relations]] in the [[Federal government of the United States|federal sector]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Justice_delayed_is_justice_denied_a_case/p8QsGPvZl_0C?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22Justice+delayed+is+justice+denied%22&pg=PA1&printsec=frontcover |date=November 9, 2005 |title=Justice Delayed is Justice Denied: A Case for a Federal Employees\u2019 Appeals Court |publisher=[[U.S. House of Representatives]] |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Delays in the law are hateful\" a Latin legal maxim.<ref name=\"Gurney\">{{cite book |first1=William Gurney |last1=Benham |authorlink1=William Gurney Benham|title=Putnam's Complete Book of Quotations, Proverbs and Household Words |year=1927}} quoted in {{cite book |first1=David. Editor |last1=Shrager |first2=Elizabeth, Editor |last2=Frost |title=The Quotable Lawyer |year=1986 |publisher=[[Facts on File]] New England Publishing Associates |isbn=0-8160-1184-2 |id=ISBN0-8160-2058-2 |location=New York, London |page=83}}</ref> On the other hand, \"No delay [in law] is long concerning the death of a man,\" is another Latin lawyer's aphorism.<ref name=\"Gurney\"/> \u201cIt is not to imagined that the King will be guilty of vexatious delays.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |author=Sir [[Dudley Ryder]], English jurist; lord chief justice. |title=Rex v. Berkley and another |year=1754 |work=Sayer\u2019s Rep. 124.}}</ref>\n\n== Practical application ==\nA Canadian [[Barrister]] wrote that \"Delay in rendering reasons for judgment is the #1 disease afflicting judges.\"<ref name=\"Duhaim\"/> [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]], John Owen Wilson,<ref>[https://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMHQAM_John_Owen_Wilson_Prince_George_BC_Canada John Owen Wilson] via [[Waymarking.com]]</ref> wrote about delay in the delivery of judgments that:\n<blockquote>\"The public has a right to expect of a judge decisiveness....\n\"Litigants expect, and rightfully expect, that the judge will soon relieve then from the agony of uncertainty that prevails until judgment is delivered.\n\"That is not to say that it is better to be quick than right.... The aim is to be both quick and right.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=A Book For Judges |first1=John Owen |last1=Wilson |year=2008}} quoted in Duhaim, 2013</ref></blockquote>\n\nEfficiency in the making of judicial decisions {{mdash}} and the avoidance of undue hesitancy while maintaining the accuracy and integrity of the decision making process {{mdash}} implicates [[law]] and [[legal ethics|ethics]]. When faced with inordinate delay, a litigant and lawyer are placed between 'a rock and a hard place.'<ref name=\"Duhaim\">{{cite web |url=http://www.duhaime.org/LegalResources/CivilLitigation/LawArticle-1270/Delay-in-Reasons-for-Judgment-Justice-Delayed-is-Justice-Denied.aspx |title=Delay in Reasons for Judgment: Justice Delayed is Justice Denied |first1=Lloyd |last1=Duhaime |date=June 9, 2013 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> There is little if any remedy, and there is a risk that even an inquiry will provoke an adverse result.<ref name=\"Duhaim\"/>\n\nThe [[Latin]] [[legal maxim]] ''Actus curi\u00e6 neminem gravabit'', meaning that the act of the Court shall prejudice no one, becomes applicable when a situation is protected because the Court is under an obligation to undo the wrong done to a party by the Court's own act. Thus, the court's delay should not prejudice the rights of a party,<ref name=\"Black\">{{cite book |title=Actus Curi\u00e6 neminem gravabit |work=[[Black's Law Dictionary]]|first1=Henry Campbell |last1=Black |authorlink1=Henry Campbell Black |edition=4th Revised |year=1968 |location=St. Paul, Minnesota |publisher=[[West Publishing]] |page=55 |quote=Jenk.Cent. 118 \"Where a delay in an action is the act of the court, neither party shall suffer for it.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/washington/supreme-court/1951/31184-1.html |title=''Carl v. Dept. of Labor & Industry'', 38 Wn.2d 890, 234 P.2d 487 |year=1951 |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Washington]], [[En Banc]]}}</ref> it being a well settled principle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cja.gov.in/Latest%20Judgement/11974%20OF%202016.pdf |title=''Neeraj Kumar Sainy and Orst(s) v. State of U.P. and Ors'' CIVIL APPEAL NO. 11974 OF 2016 (arising out of S.L.P. (Civil) No. 27906 of 2016) |publisher=[[Supreme Court of India]] |access-date=April 17, 2020 |format=[[PDF]]}}</ref> Subsequent events ought not to frustrate a well established cause of action.{{efn-ua|\"Where the nature of the relief, as originally sought, has become obsolete or unserviceable or a new form of relief will be more efficacious on account of developments subsequent to the suit or even during the appellate stage, it is but fair that the relief is moulded, varied or reshaped in the light of updated facts. ''[[Patterson v. Alabama|Patterson v. State of Alabama]]'' [1934] 294 U.S. 600, illustrates this position. It is important that the party claiming the relief or change of relief must have the same right from which either the first or the modified remedy may flow. Subsequent events in the course of the case cannot be constitutive of substantive rights enforceable in that very litigation ... but may influence the equitable jurisdiction to mould reliefs. Conversely, where rights have already vested in a party, they cannot be nullified or negated by subsequent events save where there is a change in the law and it is made applicable at any stage. [Citation omitted] ... Courts of justice may, when the compelling equities of a case oblige them, shape reliefs - cannot deny rights - to make them justly relevant in the updated circumstances. Where the relief is discretionary, Courts may exercise this jurisdiction to avoid injustice. Likewise, where the right to the remedy depends, under the statute itself, on the presence or absence of certain basic facts at the time the relief is to be ultimately granted, the Court, even in appeal, can take note of such supervening facts with fundamental impact....Where a cause of action is deficient but later events have made up the deficiency, the Court may, in order to avoid multiplicity of litigation, permit amendment and continue the proceeding, provided no prejudice is caused to the other side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legalcrystal.com/case/639383/board-control-cricket-india-vs-netaji-club |title=''Board of Control for Cricket, India and anr. Vs. Netaji Cricket Club'', Case Number Civil Appeal Nos. 237-239 of 2005 |publisher=Supreme Court of India |year=2005}}</ref>}}\n\n== In literature ==\nIn ''[[Bleakhouse]]'', [[Charles Dickens]] wrote about extraordinarily protracted proceedings in the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] English [[Court of Chancery]]. He used as illustrated \"a synonym of delay\" which yielded only disastrous consequences for the participants. The estate's court case goes on for 12 years, for reasons no one understands, and the entire estate is itself dissipated in the battle. As one writer notes:\n<blockquote>In the Victorian era, the Court of Chancery was a synonym of delay. In Bleak House Dickens invented a fictional legal case named ''[[Jarndyce and Jarndyce]]'' in order to caricature the legal system of England, and the iniquity of Chancery chiefly takes the form of procrastination: \"Jarndyce and Jarndyce drones on. This scarecrow of a suit has, in course of time, become so complicated, that no man alive knows what it means\" (BH1 16). As a consequence of this protraction, many characters involved in Jarndyce and Jarndyce are tortured by being held in painful anxiety\" one goes insand and another's mind is consumed with \u201ccorroding care, suspense, distrust, and doubt\u201d (BH 630).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dickens.jp/archive/bh/bh-tsutsui.pdf|title=Delay and Suspense in Bleak House |last1=Mizuki |first1=Tsutsui |format=PDF |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the preface to ''Bleak House'', Dickens cites two Chancery cases as especial inspirations, one of which was a \"[[friendly suit]]\":\n\n{{Quote|text=At the present moment (August, 1853) there is a suit before the court which was commenced nearly twenty years ago, in which from thirty to forty counsel have been known to appear at one time, in which costs have been incurred to the amount of seventy thousand pounds, which is A FRIENDLY SUIT, and which is (I am assured) no nearer to its termination now than when it was begun. There is another well-known suit in Chancery, not yet decided, which was commenced before the close of the last century and in which more than double the amount of seventy thousand pounds has been swallowed up in costs.}}\n\nBased on an 1853 [[Letters of Charles Dickens|letter of Dickens]],<ref>{{cite book |first1=Graham, Editor |last1=Storey |first2=Kathleen, Editor |last2=Tillotson |first3=Angus, Editor |last3=Easson |title=The Letters of Charles Dickens, VII |year=1993 |pages=128-129}}</ref> the first of these cases has been identified<ref name=\"dunstan\">{{cite journal |last1=Dunstan  |first1=William |title=The Real Jarndyce and Jarndyce |work=The Dickensian |volume=93.441 |date=Spring, 1997 |page=27}}</ref><ref name=\"katz\">{{cite journal |last1=Katz |first1=Leslie |title=''Bleak House'' in Australian Reasons for Judgment (July 21, 2017). |url= https://ssrn.com/abstract=1315862 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.1315862|via=SSRN}}</ref> as the dispute over the will of [[Charles_Day_(boot_blacking_manufacturer)|Charles Day]], a boot blacking manufacturer who died in 1836. Proceedings were commenced in 1837 and not concluded until at least 1854.\n\nThe second of these cases is generally identified<ref name=\"dunstan\"/> as the dispute over the will of the \"Acton Miser\" [[William Jennens]]{{efn-ua|[[William Jennens]] was known as \"William the Miser\" and the \"Acton Miser\". Jennens made his money loaning money to gamblers and was Britain's richest man at the time of his death in 1798, but aged 97 he had outlived the nominated executors and beneficiaries under his will. According to the [[BBC]] [[QI]] series, ''Jennens vs Jennens'' commenced in 1798 and was abandoned in 1915 (117 years later) when the legal fees had exhausted the Jennens estate of funds (worth ca. [[Pounds Sterling|\u00a3]]2 million), worth in excess of [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]230 million at 2015 rates,<ref>http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/education/Pages/inflation/calculator/flash/default.aspx {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>.<ref name=\"BBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01p8hrw/QI_Series_J_Justice/ BBC QI 8 Dec 2012, Series J, Episode 12 - Justice]</ref><ref name=\"Guidotti\">[http://www.freewebs.com/guidott/annthejennensfortune.htm The Guidott / Guidotti family, Acton Place, Summary of William Jennens] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920015353/http://www.freewebs.com/guidott/annthejennensfortune.htm |date=2014-09-20 }}</ref> The case of ''Jennens v Jennens'' formed part of the inspiration for the ''[[Jarndyce and Jarndyce]]'' case at the centre of the plot of ''[[Bleak House]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolkchurches.co.uk/acton.html|title=All Saints, Acton|publisher=www.suffolkchurches.co.uk|accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref>}} of [[Acton, Suffolk]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Guidotti\"/> Thus it had been ongoing for 55 years when ''Bleak House'' was published.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cloture]]\n* [[Filibuster]]\n* [[Moratorium (law)]]\n* [[Red tape]], inefficiency which can delay legal resolutions\n* [[Speedy trial]]\n* [[Stern v. Marshall]]\n* [[Statute of limitations]], which requires injured parties to bring timely claims\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Early_Case_Resolution_Justice_Delayed_Is/UwQdswEACAAJ?hl=en |title=Early Case Resolution, Justice Delayed Is Justice Denied|isbn=9781516844975 |id=ISBN 1516844971 |date=August 10, 2015 |type= Paperback}} analyzing the problems and opportunities from a [[Fortune 500]] company's perspective\n* {{cite book |authors=McMillan, J. E., Steelman, D. C., Goerdt, J. |year=2004 |title=Caseflow Management: The Heart of Court Management in the New Millennium. |location=United States: |publisher=[[National Center for State Courts]] |isbn=9780896562356 |id=ISBN0896562352 |type=Paperback}}\n\n[[Category:Adages]]\n[[Category:Administrative law]]\n[[Category:Civil procedure]]\n[[Category:Criminal procedure]]\n[[Category:English legal terminology]]\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Judgment (law)]]\n[[Category:Legal doctrines and principles| ]]\n[[Category:Legal interpretation]]\n[[Category:Quotations from law]]\n[[Category:Restorative justice]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Legal maxim}}\n'''\"Justice delayed is justice denied\"''' is a [[legal maxim]] meaning that if [[Legal remedy|legal redress]] or [[Equitable relief|equitable relief]] is available for a party that has suffered some injury, but is not forthcoming in a timely fashion, it is effectively the same as having no redress at all. This principle is the basis for the right to a [[speedy trial]] and similar rights which are meant to expedite the legal system, because it is unfair for the injured party to have to sustain the injury with little hope for resolution. The phrase has become a rallying cry for [[law reform|legal reformers]] who view [[court]]s, [[Judge|judge]]s, [[arbitrator]]s, [[administrative law judge]]s, [[commission]]s{{efn-ua|Defined broadly to include [[government agency]], [[regulatory agency]] or [[statutory authority]] that operates under the authority of a board of commissioners, including [[Independent agencies of the United States government]]}} or [[government]]s as acting too slowly in resolving legal issues either because the existing system is too complex or overburdened, or because the issue or party in question lacks political favour. When a court takes a matter \"under advisement\" {{ndash}} awaiting the issuance of a [[judicial opinion]], [[Court order|order]] or [[judgement]] and forestalls final [[Adjudication|adjudication]] or resolution of a [[Motion (legal)|motion]] {{ndash}} the issue of timeliness of the decision comes into play.\n\n== Origin ==\nThere are conflicting accounts of who first noted the phrase. According to ''Respectfully Quoted: A Dictionary of Quotations'', it is attributable to [[William Ewart Gladstone]], but such attribution was not verifiable.<ref>Suzy Platt (ed.). [http://www.bartleby.com/73/954.html Entry 954. William Ewart Gladstone (1809\u201398)]. ''Respectfully Quoted: A Dictionary of Quotations Requested from the Congressional Research Service''. [[Library of Congress]], 1989. (Attributed to William E. Gladstone. \u2014 Laurence J. Peter, ''Peter\u2019s Quotations'', p. 276 (1977). Unverified.)</ref> Alternatively, it may be attributed to [[William Penn]] in the form \"to delay Justice is Injustice\".<ref>Penn, William (1693), ''[https://archive.org/stream/somefruitssolit00penngoog#page/n92/mode/1up Some Fruits of Solitude]'', Headley, 1905, p. 86.</ref>\n\nMentions of justice delayed and denied are found in the [[Pirkei Avot]] 5:7, a section of the [[Mishnah]] (1st century BCE \u2013 2nd century CE): \"Our Rabbis taught: ...The sword comes into the world, because of justice delayed and justice denied...\". [[Nachmanides]] understands the advice given by [[Jethro (Bible)|Jethro]] in [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 18:22, to judge the people at all times, as suggesting that Israel needed more judges because potential litigants would otherwise suffer injustice due to their inability to find a judge to hear their case.<ref>[http://tmt.urj.net/archives/4jewishethics/052605.htm 10 Minutes of Torah. Ethical Teachings Selections from Pirkei Avot]. Retrieved 26 March 2013 {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Magna Carta]]'' of 1215, clause 40 of which reads, \"To no one will we sell, to no one will we refuse or delay, right or justice.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/evolutionofparliament/originsofparliament/birthofparliament/overview/magnacarta/magnacartaclauses/ |title=Birth of Parliament |publisher=[[British Parliament]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], used the phrase in the form \"justice too long delayed is justice denied\" in his \"[[Letter from Birmingham Jail]]\", smuggled out of jail in 1963, ascribing it to \"one of our distinguished jurists\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Articles_Gen/Letter_Birmingham.html|title=\"Letter from a Birmingham Jail [King, Jr.]\"|last=|first=|date=|website=African Studies Center - University of Pennsylvania|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190323113329/https://www.africa.upenn.edu/Articles_Gen/Letter_Birmingham.html|archive-date=2019-03-23|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nThe broader [[public policy]] implications are a source of concern. As Chief Justice of the United States [[Warren E. Burger]] noted in an address to the [[American Bar Association]] in 1970:\n<blockquote>\"A sense of confidence in the courts is essential to maintain the fabric of ordered liberty for a free people and three things could destroy that confidence and do incalculable damage to society: that people come to believe that inefficiency and delay will drain even a just judgment of its value; that people who have long been exploited in the smaller transactions of daily life come to believe that courts cannot vindicate their legal rights from fraud and over-reaching; that people come to believe the law \u2013 in the larger sense \u2013 cannot fulfill its primary function to protect them and their families in their homes, at their work, and on the public streets.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Burger |first1=Warren E. |date=August 24, 1970 |title=What's Wrong With the Courts: The Chief Justice Speaks Out (address to ABA meeting, Aug. 10, 1970) |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |volume=69 |number=8 |pages=68, 71}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLack of a speedy and effective resolution (amidst a bewildering multiplicity of statutes and forums with overlapping [[jurisdiction]]) can cause unwarranted delay. It has been observed that it creates a sense of frustration and unfairness, and a feeling of a lack of [[efficacy]], which adversely affects [[employee morale]] and [[labor relations]] in the [[Federal government of the United States|federal sector]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Justice_delayed_is_justice_denied_a_case/p8QsGPvZl_0C?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22Justice+delayed+is+justice+denied%22&pg=PA1&printsec=frontcover |date=November 9, 2005 |title=Justice Delayed is Justice Denied: A Case for a Federal Employees\u2019 Appeals Court |publisher=[[U.S. House of Representatives]] |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Delays in the law are hateful\" a Latin legal maxim.<ref name=\"Gurney\">{{cite book |first1=William Gurney |last1=Benham |authorlink1=William Gurney Benham|title=Putnam's Complete Book of Quotations, Proverbs and Household Words |year=1927}} quoted in {{cite book |first1=David. Editor |last1=Shrager |first2=Elizabeth, Editor |last2=Frost |title=The Quotable Lawyer |year=1986 |publisher=[[Facts on File]] New England Publishing Associates |isbn=0-8160-1184-2 |id=ISBN0-8160-2058-2 |location=New York, London |page=83}}</ref> On the other hand, \"No delay [in law] is long concerning the death of a man,\" is another Latin lawyer's aphorism.<ref name=\"Gurney\"/> \u201cIt is not to imagined that the King will be guilty of vexatious delays.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |author=Sir [[Dudley Ryder]], English jurist; lord chief justice. |title=Rex v. Berkley and another |year=1754 |work=Sayer\u2019s Rep. 124.}}</ref>\n\n== Practical application ==\nA Canadian [[Barrister]] wrote that \"Delay in rendering reasons for judgment is the #1 disease afflicting judges.\"<ref name=\"Duhaim\"/> [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Supreme Court of British Columbia]], John Owen Wilson,<ref>[https://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMHQAM_John_Owen_Wilson_Prince_George_BC_Canada John Owen Wilson] via [[Waymarking.com]]</ref> wrote about delay in the delivery of judgments that:\n<blockquote>\"The public has a right to expect of a judge decisiveness....\n\"Litigants expect, and rightfully expect, that the judge will soon relieve then from the agony of uncertainty that prevails until judgment is delivered.\n\"That is not to say that it is better to be quick than right.... The aim is to be both quick and right.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=A Book For Judges |first1=John Owen |last1=Wilson |year=2008}} quoted in Duhaim, 2013</ref></blockquote>\n\nEfficiency in the making of judicial decisions {{mdash}} and the avoidance of undue hesitancy while maintaining the accuracy and integrity of the decision making process {{mdash}} implicates [[law]] and [[legal ethics|ethics]]. When faced with inordinate delay, a litigant and lawyer are placed between 'a rock and a hard place.'<ref name=\"Duhaim\">{{cite web |url=http://www.duhaime.org/LegalResources/CivilLitigation/LawArticle-1270/Delay-in-Reasons-for-Judgment-Justice-Delayed-is-Justice-Denied.aspx |title=Delay in Reasons for Judgment: Justice Delayed is Justice Denied |first1=Lloyd |last1=Duhaime |date=June 9, 2013 |access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> There is little if any remedy, and there is a risk that even an inquiry will provoke an adverse result.<ref name=\"Duhaim\"/>\n\nThe [[Latin]] [[legal maxim]] ''Actus curi\u00e6 neminem gravabit'', meaning that the act of the Court shall prejudice no one, becomes applicable when a situation is protected because the Court is under an obligation to undo the wrong done to a party by the Court's own act. Thus, the court's delay should not prejudice the rights of a party,<ref name=\"Black\">{{cite book |title=Actus Curi\u00e6 neminem gravabit |work=[[Black's Law Dictionary]]|first1=Henry Campbell |last1=Black |authorlink1=Henry Campbell Black |edition=4th Revised |year=1968 |location=St. Paul, Minnesota |publisher=[[West Publishing]] |page=55 |quote=Jenk.Cent. 118 \"Where a delay in an action is the act of the court, neither party shall suffer for it.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/washington/supreme-court/1951/31184-1.html |title=''Carl v. Dept. of Labor & Industry'', 38 Wn.2d 890, 234 P.2d 487 |year=1951 |publisher=[[Supreme Court of Washington]], [[En Banc]]}}</ref> it being a well settled principle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cja.gov.in/Latest%20Judgement/11974%20OF%202016.pdf |title=''Neeraj Kumar Sainy and Orst(s) v. State of U.P. and Ors'' CIVIL APPEAL NO. 11974 OF 2016 (arising out of S.L.P. (Civil) No. 27906 of 2016) |publisher=[[Supreme Court of India]] |access-date=April 17, 2020 |format=[[PDF]]}}</ref> Subsequent events ought not to frustrate a well established cause of action.{{efn-ua|\"Where the nature of the relief, as originally sought, has become obsolete or unserviceable or a new form of relief will be more efficacious on account of developments subsequent to the suit or even during the appellate stage, it is but fair that the relief is moulded, varied or reshaped in the light of updated facts. ''[[Patterson v. Alabama|Patterson v. State of Alabama]]'' [1934] 294 U.S. 600, illustrates this position. It is important that the party claiming the relief or change of relief must have the same right from which either the first or the modified remedy may flow. Subsequent events in the course of the case cannot be constitutive of substantive rights enforceable in that very litigation ... but may influence the equitable jurisdiction to mould reliefs. Conversely, where rights have already vested in a party, they cannot be nullified or negated by subsequent events save where there is a change in the law and it is made applicable at any stage. [Citation omitted] ... Courts of justice may, when the compelling equities of a case oblige them, shape reliefs - cannot deny rights - to make them justly relevant in the updated circumstances. Where the relief is discretionary, Courts may exercise this jurisdiction to avoid injustice. Likewise, where the right to the remedy depends, under the statute itself, on the presence or absence of certain basic facts at the time the relief is to be ultimately granted, the Court, even in appeal, can take note of such supervening facts with fundamental impact....Where a cause of action is deficient but later events have made up the deficiency, the Court may, in order to avoid multiplicity of litigation, permit amendment and continue the proceeding, provided no prejudice is caused to the other side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legalcrystal.com/case/639383/board-control-cricket-india-vs-netaji-club |title=''Board of Control for Cricket, India and anr. Vs. Netaji Cricket Club'', Case Number Civil Appeal Nos. 237-239 of 2005 |publisher=Supreme Court of India |year=2005}}</ref>}}\n\n== In literature ==\nIn ''[[Bleakhouse]]'', [[Charles Dickens]] wrote about extraordinarily protracted proceedings in the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] English [[Court of Chancery]]. He used as illustrated \"a synonym of delay\" which yielded only disastrous consequences for the participants. The estate's court case goes on for 12 years, for reasons no one understands, and the entire estate is itself dissipated in the battle. As one writer notes:\n<blockquote>In the Victorian era, the Court of Chancery was a synonym of delay. In Bleak House Dickens invented a fictional legal case named ''[[Jarndyce and Jarndyce]]'' in order to caricature the legal system of England, and the iniquity of Chancery chiefly takes the form of procrastination: \"Jarndyce and Jarndyce drones on. This scarecrow of a suit has, in course of time, become so complicated, that no man alive knows what it means\" (BH1 16). As a consequence of this protraction, many characters involved in Jarndyce and Jarndyce are tortured by being held in painful anxiety\" one goes insand and another's mind is consumed with \u201ccorroding care, suspense, distrust, and doubt\u201d (BH 630).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dickens.jp/archive/bh/bh-tsutsui.pdf|title=Delay and Suspense in Bleak House |last1=Mizuki |first1=Tsutsui |format=PDF |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the preface to ''Bleak House'', Dickens cites two Chancery cases as especial inspirations, one of which was a \"[[friendly suit]]\":\n\n{{Quote|text=At the present moment (August, 1853) there is a suit before the court which was commenced nearly twenty years ago, in which from thirty to forty counsel have been known to appear at one time, in which costs have been incurred to the amount of seventy thousand pounds, which is A FRIENDLY SUIT, and which is (I am assured) no nearer to its termination now than when it was begun. There is another well-known suit in Chancery, not yet decided, which was commenced before the close of the last century and in which more than double the amount of seventy thousand pounds has been swallowed up in costs.}}\n\nBased on an 1853 [[Letters of Charles Dickens|letter of Dickens]],<ref>{{cite book |first1=Graham, Editor |last1=Storey |first2=Kathleen, Editor |last2=Tillotson |first3=Angus, Editor |last3=Easson |title=The Letters of Charles Dickens, VII |year=1993 |pages=128-129}}</ref> the first of these cases has been identified<ref name=\"dunstan\">{{cite journal |last1=Dunstan  |first1=William |title=The Real Jarndyce and Jarndyce |work=The Dickensian |volume=93.441 |date=Spring, 1997 |page=27}}</ref><ref name=\"katz\">{{cite journal |last1=Katz |first1=Leslie |title=''Bleak House'' in Australian Reasons for Judgment (July 21, 2017). |url= https://ssrn.com/abstract=1315862 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.1315862|via=SSRN}}</ref> as the dispute over the will of [[Charles_Day_(boot_blacking_manufacturer)|Charles Day]], a boot blacking manufacturer who died in 1836. Proceedings were commenced in 1837 and not concluded until at least 1854.\n\nThe second of these cases is generally identified<ref name=\"dunstan\"/> as the dispute over the will of the \"Acton Miser\" [[William Jennens]]{{efn-ua|[[William Jennens]] was known as \"William the Miser\" and the \"Acton Miser\". Jennens made his money loaning money to gamblers and was Britain's richest man at the time of his death in 1798, but aged 97 he had outlived the nominated executors and beneficiaries under his will. According to the [[BBC]] [[QI]] series, ''Jennens vs Jennens'' commenced in 1798 and was abandoned in 1915 (117 years later) when the legal fees had exhausted the Jennens estate of funds (worth ca. [[Pounds Sterling|\u00a3]]2 million), worth in excess of [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]230 million at 2015 rates,<ref>http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/education/Pages/inflation/calculator/flash/default.aspx {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>.<ref name=\"BBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01p8hrw/QI_Series_J_Justice/ BBC QI 8 Dec 2012, Series J, Episode 12 - Justice]</ref><ref name=\"Guidotti\">[http://www.freewebs.com/guidott/annthejennensfortune.htm The Guidott / Guidotti family, Acton Place, Summary of William Jennens] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920015353/http://www.freewebs.com/guidott/annthejennensfortune.htm |date=2014-09-20 }}</ref> The case of ''Jennens v Jennens'' formed part of the inspiration for the ''[[Jarndyce and Jarndyce]]'' case at the centre of the plot of ''[[Bleak House]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suffolkchurches.co.uk/acton.html|title=All Saints, Acton|publisher=www.suffolkchurches.co.uk|accessdate=2008-10-15}}</ref>}} of [[Acton, Suffolk]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref name=\"Guidotti\"/> Thus it had been ongoing for 55 years when ''Bleak House'' was published.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cloture]]\n* [[Filibuster]]\n* [[Moratorium (law)]]\n* [[Red tape]], inefficiency which can delay legal resolutions\n* [[Speedy trial]]\n* [[Stern v. Marshall]]\n* [[Statute of limitations]], which requires injured parties to bring timely claims\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Early_Case_Resolution_Justice_Delayed_Is/UwQdswEACAAJ?hl=en |title=Early Case Resolution, Justice Delayed Is Justice Denied|isbn=9781516844975 |id=ISBN 1516844971 |date=August 10, 2015 |type= Paperback}} analyzing the problems and opportunities from a [[Fortune 500]] company's perspective\n* {{cite book |authors=McMillan, J. E., Steelman, D. C., Goerdt, J. |year=2004 |title=Caseflow Management: The Heart of Court Management in the New Millennium. |location=United States: |publisher=[[National Center for State Courts]] |isbn=9780896562356 |id=ISBN0896562352 |type=Paperback}}\n\n[[Category:Adages]]\n[[Category:Administrative law]]\n[[Category:Civil procedure]]\n[[Category:Criminal procedure]]\n[[Category:English legal terminology]]\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Judgment (law)]]\n[[Category:Legal doctrines and principles| ]]\n[[Category:Legal interpretation]]\n[[Category:Quotations from law]]\n[[Category:Restorative justice]]\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": ".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justice_delayed_is_justice_denied"}
{"title_page": "Casey Affleck", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Casey Affleck\n| image        = Casey Affleck at the Manchester by the Sea premiere (30199719155) (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Affleck in 2016\n| birth_name   = Caleb Casey McGuire Affleck-Boldt\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1975|08|12}}\n| birth_place  = [[Falmouth, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| education    = [[George Washington University]]<br>[[Columbia University]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|director}}\n| years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Summer Phoenix]]|2006|2017|reason=div}}\n| children     = 2\n| awards       = [[List of awards and nominations received by Casey Affleck|Full List]]\n| relatives    = [[Ben Affleck]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Caleb Casey McGuire Affleck-Boldt''' (born August 12, 1975) is an American actor and director. He began his career as a child actor, appearing in the [[PBS]] television film ''[[Lemon Sky]]'' (1988) and the miniseries ''[[The Kennedys of Massachusetts]]'' (1990). He later appeared in three [[Gus Van Sant]] films&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[To Die For]]'' (1995), ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'' (1997), and ''[[Gerry (2002 film)|Gerry]]'' (2002)&nbsp;\u2013 and in [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s comedy heist trilogy ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' (2001), ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004), and ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]'' (2007). His first leading role was in [[Steve Buscemi]]'s independent comedy-drama ''[[Lonesome Jim]]'' (2006).\n\nAffleck's breakthrough was in 2007, when he was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance in the Western drama ''[[The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford]]'' and acted in the crime drama ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'', directed by his brother [[Ben Affleck]]. In 2010, he directed the mockumentary ''[[I'm Still Here (2010 film)|I'm Still Here]]''. He then had a string of successful films in the early 2010s, with ''[[Tower Heist]]'', ''[[ParaNorman]]'', and ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'', and received particular praise for his performance as an outlaw in the indie film ''[[Ain't Them Bodies Saints]]''.\n\nIn 2016, Affleck starred as the lead in the drama film ''[[Manchester by the Sea (film)|Manchester by the Sea]]''. For his performance as Lee Chandler, a man grieving the loss of his children, he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA]] and [[Academy Award for Best Actor]], and received a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] nomination. In 2017, Affleck received critical acclaim for his leading role in the supernatural drama film ''[[A Ghost Story]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nCaleb Casey McGuire Affleck-Boldt<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2sg3CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132 |title=Finding Your Roots, Season 2: The Official Companion to the PBS Series |last=Jr |first=Henry Louis Gates |date=January 28, 2016|publisher=UNC Press Books |isbn=978-1-4696-2619-2 |language=en}}</ref> was born on August 12, 1975 in [[Falmouth, Massachusetts]], to Christopher Anne \"Chris\" Boldt and Timothy Byers Affleck.<ref name=tvg>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/casey-affleck/143690/ |title=Casey Affleck |work=[[TV Guide]] |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912092738/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/casey-affleck/143690/ |archivedate=September 12, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', PBS, October 14, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://harvardmagazine.com/2010/03/tidbits-one-ringtailed \"A reunion report, and a ringtail cat\" | Harvard Magazine Mar\u2013Apr 2010]. Harvardmagazine.com (September 25, 2013). Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> The surname \"Affleck\" is of Scottish origin.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0403/16/lkl.00.html |title=CNN.com \u2013 Transcripts |publisher=CNN |date=March 16, 2004 |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> He also has Irish,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movies.ie/ben-affleck-interview-for-the-town/ |title=Ben Affleck Interview for THE TOWN \u2013 Interviews |publisher=Movies.ie |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eventguide.ie/articles.elive?session_id=11696590572785496&sku=070122142932 |title=Film Interview \u2013 Ben Affleck / 'Hollywoodland' |publisher=Event Guide |accessdate=September 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928004637/http://www.eventguide.ie/articles.elive?session_id=11696590572785496&sku=070122142932 |archivedate=September 28, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> German,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/largest-ethnic-groups-in-america-2013-8 |title=The Largest Ancestry Groups in the United States|publisher=Business Insider |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2015 |first1=Liz |first2=Gus |first3=Dina |last1=O'Connor |last2=Lubin |last3=Spector}}</ref> English, and Swiss ancestry.<ref name=tca2>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2001</ref>{{full citation needed |date=November 2017|reason=not possible to tell what this was supposed to verify}} Affleck's maternal great-great grandfather, {{lang|de|Heinrich Boldt|italic=no}}, -known for the discovery of the [[Curmsun Disc]], emigrated from [[Prussia]] in the late 1840s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/9647410/A_unique_object_from_Harald_Bluetooth_s_time._2015_ |title=A unique object from Harald Bluetooth's time |first=Sven |last=Rosborn |publisher=Academia |date=April 23, 2015 |accessdate=January 10, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201085538/http://www.academia.edu/9647410/A_unique_object_from_Harald_Bluetooth_s_time._2015_ |archivedate=February 1, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"tvn.pl\">{{cite news |url=https://dziendobry.tvn.pl/wideo,2064,n/skarb-zwiazany-z-rodzina-afflecka-w-rekach-polaka,234066.html |title=A treasure associated with Ben Affleck in the hands of a Polish family |publisher=TVN News |date=January 10, 2018 |accessdate=January 10, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235431/https://dziendobry.tvn.pl/wideo,2064,n/skarb-zwiazany-z-rodzina-afflecka-w-rekach-polaka,234066.html |archivedate=January 9, 2018 }}</ref> Casey's mother was a [[Radcliffe College]]\u2013 and [[Harvard University|Harvard]]\u2013educated elementary school teacher. His father worked sporadically as an auto mechanic,<ref name=\"viewaskew1\">[http://viewaskew.com/chasingamy/benview.html Cinezine \u2013 Frank Discussions With Ben Affleck]. Viewaskew.com. Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/yourtown/boston/northend/articles/2010/09/15/with_new_film_affleck_ties_boston_knot_tighter/?page=full |title=With new film, Affleck ties Boston knot tighter|work=Boston Globe |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |first=Wesley |last=Morris |date=September 15, 2010}}</ref> a carpenter,<ref name=\"oocities1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oocities.org/affleck1971/playboy.html |title=December '99-Playboy: Interview with Ben Affleck|publisher=oocities.org |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> a [[bookmaker|bookie]],<ref name=\"kinja1\">{{cite news |url=http://playboysfw.kinja.com/ben-affleck-on-argo-his-distaste-for-politics-and-the-1508624335 |title=Ben Affleck on Argo, His Distaste For Politics and the Batman Backlash |first=Michael |last=Fleming |date=January 27, 2014 |work=[[Playboy (magazine)|Playboy]] |accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20135136,00.html Reality Check \u2013 Rehab, Substance Abuse, Coping and Overcoming Illness, Ben Affleck]. ''People''. (August 20, 2001). Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> an electrician,<ref name=\"people1\">{{cite news |last=Schneider |first=Karen S. |date=February 21, 2000 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20130541,00.html |title=Good Time Hunting \u2013 Personal Success, Ben Affleck |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> a bartender,<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\">Atkinson, Kim. (May 15, 2006) [http://www.bostonmagazine.com/2006/05/the-other-affleck/ The Other Affleck]. 'Boston Magazine''. Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> and a janitor at Harvard University.<ref name=\"filmref-ben\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/85/Ben-Affleck.html |title=Ben Affleck Biography (1972\u2013) |accessdate=June 26, 2008 |publisher=Film reference}}</ref><ref>[http://tomshone.blogspot.ie/2011/01/how-good-will-hunting-got-its-ending.html THESE VIOLENT DELIGHTS: Malick gave Good Will Hunting its ending]. Tomshone.blogspot.ie (January 5, 2011). Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/5/Casey-Affleck.html |title=Casey Affleck Biography |accessdate=June 26, 2008|publisher=Film Reference}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/285832951.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+10%2C+2003&author=Emma+Stickgold%2C+Globe+Correspondent&pub=Boston+Globe&desc=ELIZABETH+SHAW%2C+MUSEUM+OF+MODERN+ART+OFFICIAL&pqatl=google |title=Mrs. Shaw was also the grandmother of Hollywood actors Ben and Casey Affleck.|publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date=February 10, 2003 |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |first=Emma |last=Stickgold}}</ref> In the mid-1960s, he had been a stage manager, director, writer and actor with the [[Theater Company of Boston]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.actorsequity.org/Newsmedia/news2012/jan17.DavidWheeler.asp |title=DAVID WHEELER, Father Of The Boston Theatre Scene |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527214431/http://www.actorsequity.org/Newsmedia/news2012/jan17.DavidWheeler.asp |archive-date=May 27, 2014 |work=[[Actors' Equity Association]] |date=January 27, 2012 |accessdate=June 5, 2014 |first=Donna |last=Sorbello}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.larrybryggman.com/ob1.htm |title=PERFORMANCES{{!}}Off-Broadway |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030937/http://www.larrybryggman.com/ob1.htm# |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |work=Larrybryggman.com |accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1964/8/19/the-cocktail-party-pthe-theatre-company/ ''The Cocktail Party'' review], thecrimson.com; retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> During Affleck's childhood, his father was \"a disaster of a drinker\".<ref name=\"wtfpod.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wtfpod.com/podcast/episode-767-casey-affleck/ |title=Episode 767 \u2013 Casey Affleck |newspaper=WTF with Marc Maron Podcast |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck first started acting by \"reenacting what was happening at home\" during role play exercises at [[Al-Anon/Alateen|Alateen]] meetings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/06/casey-affleck-acceptance-speech-santa-barbara-film-festival/ |title=Watch Casey Affleck's Heartfelt Speech at the Santa Barbara International Film Festival |date=February 6, 2017 |newspaper=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=February 19, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his parents' divorce when he was 9, Affleck and his older brother, [[Ben Affleck|Ben]], lived with their mother and visited their father weekly.<ref name=\"wtfpod.com\"/> He learned to speak Spanish during a year spent traveling around Mexico with his mother and brother when he was 10.<ref name=\"telegraphgarratt\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3673779/Casey-Afflecks-time-to-shine.html |title=Casey Affleck's time to shine |last=Garratt |first=Sheryl |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The two siblings spent \"all of our time together, pretty much. Obviously at school we were in different grades, but we had the same friends.\"<ref name=\"telegraphgarratt\" /> When Affleck was 14, his father moved to [[Indio, California]] to enter a rehabilitation facility, and later worked there as an addiction counselor.<ref name=\"people1\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=McGinty |first=Kate |date=January 5, 2013 |url=http://blogs.mydesert.com/2013/01/05/palm-springs-film-festival-ben-affleck-spit-on-me/ |title=Palm Springs film festival: Ben Affleck spit on me |newspaper=[[MyDesert]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527215548/http://blogs.mydesert.com/2013/01/05/palm-springs-film-festival-ben-affleck-spit-on-me/ |archive-date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=June 5, 2014 |publisher=[[Gannett]]}}</ref><ref name=\"rollingstone2\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ben-afflecks-hollywood-ending-20040401?page=2 Ben Affleck's Hollywood Ending | Movies News] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110004051/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/ben-afflecks-hollywood-ending-20040401?page=2 |date=January 10, 2016}}, RollingStone.com; retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.angelfire.com/biz6/athena2/interviews/gq0501.html Ben in GQ]. Angelfire.com; retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> Affleck reconnected with his father during visits to California as a teenager: \"I got to know him, really, because he was sober for the first time ... The man I knew before that was just completely different.\"<ref name=\"wtfpod.com\"/><ref name=\"npr.org\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=502418270 |title=Casey Affleck: At First, Acting Was 'Nothing More Than A Day Off From School'|publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up in a politically active, liberal household in [[Central Square, Cambridge]],<ref name=\"kinja1\"/><ref name=\"salon.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2000/11/08/reacts_ny |title=Ben Affleck: \"I hope Nader can still sleep\"|work=Salon |first=Amy |last=Reiter |date=November 8, 2000 |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> Affleck and his brother were surrounded by people who worked in the arts,<ref>\"Ben Affleck on stardom, settling down, and working with best buddy Matt Damon\" By Sheryl Berk for ''Biography Magazine'' (July 2002)</ref> were regularly taken to the theater by their mother,<ref>[https://collider.com/casey-affleck-aint-them-bodies-saints-interview/ Casey Affleck Talks AIN'T THEM BODIES SAINTS, His Brother, I'M STILL HERE, and More]. Collider.com (November 20, 2013). Retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> and were encouraged to make their own home movies.<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/12/02/casey-affleck-star-of-out-of-the-furnace-on-his-hollywood-struggles.html |title=Casey Affleck, Star of 'Out of the Furnace', on His Hollywood Struggles |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=December 2, 2013 |website=The Daily Beast |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The brothers sometimes appeared in local weather commercials and as movie extras because of their mother's friendship with a local casting director.<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\"/><ref name=\"npr.org\"/><ref name=\"washingtonpost2007\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/16/AR2007101602302.html Bond of Brothers], ''The Washington Post''; retrieved June 5, 2014.</ref> Casey acted in numerous high school theater productions while a student at [[Cambridge Rindge and Latin School]].<ref name=\"npr.org\" /><ref name=\"today\">{{cite web |url=http://www.today.com/id/23279884/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/casey-affleck-teachers-rd-oscar-nominee/ |title=Casey Affleck is teacher's 3rd Oscar nominee|publisher=TODAY.com |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref> He has said he \"wouldn't be an actor\" if not for his high school theater teacher Gerry Speca: \"He kind of turned me on to acting, why it can be fun, how it can be rewarding.\"<ref name=\"today\"/>\n\nAt the age of 18, Affleck moved to [[Los Angeles]] for a year to pursue an acting career, and lived with his brother and their childhood friend [[Matt Damon]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/24/magazine/casey-affleck-should-be-more-famous.html |title=Casey Affleck Should Be More Famous |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |date=November 21, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Despite having \"the best possible first experience\" while filming ''[[To Die For]]'',<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/awards-chatter-podcast-casey-affleck-935376 |title='Awards Chatter' Podcast \u2014 Casey Affleck ('Manchester by the Sea') |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=October 6, 2016 |first=Scott |last=Feinberg}}</ref> he spent much of the year working as a busboy at a restaurant in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]]. He decided to move to [[Washington, D.C.]], to study politics at [[George Washington University]].<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\"/> He soon transferred to [[Columbia University]] in [[New York City]], where he followed the [[Core Curriculum (Columbia College)|core curriculum]] for a total of two years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yaleherald.com/archive/xxx/2000.11.16/features/exclusive.html |title=One-on-one with Casey Affleck |date=November 16, 2000|work=[[The Yale Herald]] |first=Elisabeth |last=Marshall |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306033643/http://www.yaleherald.com/archive/xxx/2000.11.16/features/exclusive.html# |archive-date=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"index\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indexmagazine.com/interviews/casey_affleck.shtml |title=Casey Affleck, 1998|publisher=indexmagazine.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017|year=1998 |first=Rebecca |last=Godfrey|work=[[Index Magazine]]}}</ref> However, he did not graduate: \"I would do a semester of school, go do a movie ... Opportunities kept presenting themselves that were hard for me to turn down ... By then, I didn't really have roots at the school or a group of friends.\"<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early work (1988\u20132006)===\nAffleck acted professionally during his childhood due to his mother's friendship with a Cambridge-area casting director, Patty Collinge.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> In addition to local weather commercials and movie [[Extra (acting)|extra]] work,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=502418270 |title=Casey Affleck Interview: Star Of Manchester By The Sea Talks About Being An Extra, Acting, Family|publisher=NPR |date=November 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> he appeared as [[Kevin Bacon]]'s brother in the [[PBS]] television movie ''[[Lemon Sky]]'' (1988), directed by Collinge's husband Jan Egleson,<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> and as a young [[Robert Kennedy]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] miniseries ''[[The Kennedys of Massachusetts]]'' (1990).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2816736/casey-affleck-american-playhouse-lemon-sky |title=Before They Were Famous: Casey Affleck in '80s TV Show|publisher=MTV News |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> These early acting experiences \"meant nothing more than a day off from school\" to Affleck, and he only began to consider a career as an actor when in high school.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> When he later moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting career in earnest, his first movie role was as a [[antisocial personality disorder|sociopathic]] teenager in [[Gus Van Sant]]'s 1995 satirical comedy ''[[To Die For]]''. During filming in [[Toronto]], Affleck shared an apartment with co-star [[Joaquin Phoenix]] and they became close friends.<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\" /> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' praised Affleck's performance, saying he \"skillfully capture[s] the pang of adolescence among no-hopers.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/to-die-for-19950101 |title=To Die For |newspaper=Rolling Stone |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |first=Peter |last=Travers |date=October 6, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/casey-affleck-2-1117974394 |title=Casey Affleck \u2013 Breakthrough Actor|work=Variety |date=October 19, 2007 |accessdate=August 21, 2017 |first=Stephen |last=Schaefer}}</ref> However, Affleck then had a \"disappointing\" experience while making the 1996 drama ''[[Race the Sun]]'' and, \"as soon as the film finished, I went to school.\"<ref name=\"index\" />\n\nWhile studying at Columbia, Affleck had a supporting role in Van Sant's ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'' (1997), written by his brother and their childhood friend [[Matt Damon]].<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\" /><ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\" /> Despite arranging a first meeting between Van Sant and his brother to discuss the project, Affleck was reluctant to leave college temporarily to act in the film.<ref name=\"index\" /> He was eventually persuaded to play one of four friends living in [[South Boston]]&nbsp;\u2013 a role written specifically for him<ref name=\"nytimes\" />&nbsp;\u2013 and improvised many of his lines.<ref name=\"vansant\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/gus-van-sant-casey-affleck-to-die-for-good-will-hunting-1201892669/ |title=Gus Van Sant on Making 'To Die For' and 'Good Will Hunting' With Casey Affleck |last=Setoodeh |first=Ramin |date=October 18, 2016 |newspaper=Variety |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/24/good-will-hunting-facts_n_7126534.html |title=7 Things You May Not Know About 'Good Will Hunting' |last=Blickley |first=Leigh |date=April 24, 2015 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Jay Carr of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' praised the \"emotional subtleties and variety\" of the performances, and singled out \"Casey Affleck's junior member of the quartet, dying to be taken as seriously as the others.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cache.boston.com/globe/living/moviereviews/carr_reviews/Good_Will_Hunting.htm |title='Will' has its way |last=Carr |first=Jay|work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=December 25, 1997}}</ref> Following the critical and commercial success of the movie, Affleck's career opportunities did not significantly improve. At the same time, his life became exposed to the public and parts of his life became \"part of pop culture and public life.\"<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\" /> Also in 1997, he had a small role in [[Kevin Smith]]'s ''[[Chasing Amy]]'', starring his brother. He returned to university for a semester before quitting to focus on his acting career.<ref name=\"index\" />\n\nAffleck's career entered a \"dark\" period, with a series of supporting roles in critical and commercial failures.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/><ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\"/> He later remarked: \"It dawned on me late that I should be selective about what I do.\"<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/> In the independent comedy ''[[Desert Blue]]'' (1998), he starred opposite [[Kate Hudson]] as a small-town jock.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/desert-blue-1200455133 |title=Review: 'Desert Blue' |last=Lovell |first=Glenn |date=September 18, 1998 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Peter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' felt that, while \"interesting\", his character was \"entirely underdeveloped\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Desert-Blue-Wanders-Aimlessly-Film-has-good-2923603.php |title='Desert Blue' Wanders Aimlessly/Film has good cast but lacks focus |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=June 18, 1999 |first=Peter |last=Stack}}</ref> In 1999, he made an uncredited cameo in the teen comedy ''[[American Pie (film)|American Pie]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/04/from-the-wire-remembering-american-pie-130084 |title=From the Wire: Remembering 'American Pie' |last=Singer |first=Matt |date=April 4, 2012|publisher=IndieWire |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> and appeared as a punk rocker romantically involved with both [[Gaby Hoffmann]] and [[Christina Ricci]]'s characters in the New Year's Eve ensemble comedy ''[[200 Cigarettes]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9807E3DB163CF935A15751C0A96F958260 |title=Film Review; How Was New Year's Eve? Smokin'! |last=Maslin |first=Janet |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=February 26, 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.com/13383187/200-cigarettes-new-years-eve/ |title=Why ''200 Cigarettes'' Is Still the Best New Year's Eve Movie Ever |last=Garcia |first=Patricia |newspaper=Vogue |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=December 31, 2015}}</ref> In the comedy ''[[Drowning Mona]]'' (2000), starring [[Danny DeVito]], Affleck played a shy gardener suspected of murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/mar/03/entertainment/ca-4781 |title='Mona' a Tart Take on Human Nature |last=Thomas |first=Kevin |date=March 3, 2000 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US|issn=0458-3035 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Elvis Mitchell]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' acknowledged, in an otherwise negative review, that his role was \"well played\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950CE1D61E39F930A35750C0A9669C8B63 |title=FILM REVIEW; Caution: Falling Yugo Zone Ahead |last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2000, Affleck had a small role in the comedy ''[[Attention Shoppers (film)|Attention Shoppers]]'' and played [[Fortinbras]] in [[Ethan Hawke]]'s ''[[Hamlet (2000 film)|Hamlet]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-06-23/features/0006230852_1_polonius-ophelia-rosencrantz-and-guildenstern |title=A `Hamlet' For Our Times |newspaper=tribunedigital-thecourant |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> He appeared as the brother of [[Heather Graham]]'s character in the romantic comedy ''[[Committed (film)|Committed]]'' (2001), with Emanuel Levy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praising a \"terrific\" performance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/committed-1117778691/ |title=Review: 'Committed' |last=Levy |first=Emanuel |date=February 17, 2000 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2001, he had a small role in ''[[American Pie 2]]'' and appeared in the teen [[slasher film]] ''[[Soul Survivors]]''. Robert Koehler of ''Variety'' found him \"bland\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/soul-survivors-2-1200469932/ |title=Review: 'Soul Survivors' |last=Koehler |first=Robert |date=September 14, 2001 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> while Carla Meyer of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said that he did not make \"much of an impression, [but may] have been too depressed to really act.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/REVIEW-Abominable-teen-horror-film-Soul-2881833.php |title=REVIEW / Abominable teen horror film / 'Soul Survivor' is pure nonsense |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> One positive experience Affleck had during this period was working with Van Sant and cinematographer [[Harris Savides]] on ''[[Finding Forrester]]'' (2000) as Van Sant's assistant and technical consultant: \"Can you imagine a better film school that that? Gus is not only somebody who I love a lot but is also who has taught me, maybe more than anybody else in film.\"<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\" /><ref name=\"awardsdaily\">{{cite web |url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2013/12/07/casey-affleck-talks-about-out-of-the-furnace/ |title=Casey Affleck talks about Out of the Furnace |date=December 7, 2013 |website=Awards Daily |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAffleck found a degree of commercial success when he was cast in [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s heist comedy ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]'' (2001), starring [[George Clooney]], [[Brad Pitt]] and Damon. In roles Soderbergh originally intended for [[Luke Wilson]] and [[Owen Wilson]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/5-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-oceans-eleven-movies-w449145 |title=5 Things You Didn't Know About the 'Ocean's Eleven' Movies |newspaper=Rolling Stone |accessdate=January 1, 2017 |date=November 28, 2016 |first=Noel |last=Murray}}</ref> Affleck and [[Scott Caan]] played [[Mormon]] brothers and wisecracking mechanics who help to rob three Las Vegas casinos simultaneously.<ref name=\"setoodeh\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/casey-affleck-manchester-by-the-sea-1201891603/ |title=How Casey Affleck Found the Role of a Lifetime in 'Manchester by the Sea' |last=Setoodeh |first=Ramin |date=October 18, 2016 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> While it was a \"great, fun social experience,\" Affleck spent much of his time on set \"being, like, 100 feet away from the camera in the background.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> He would later reprise his role in ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' (2004) and ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]'' (2007).\n\nIn 2002, Affleck and Damon starred in Van Sant's experimental drama ''[[Gerry (2002 film)|Gerry]]'', playing two men who get lost while hiking in the desert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/archives/issues/winter2002/features/sands_time.php |title=Sands of Time |newspaper=Filmmaker Magazine |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/gerrymandering-an-interview-with-gus-van-sant |title=Interview: Gus Van Sant {{!}} Feature {{!}} Slant Magazine |newspaper=Slant Magazine |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck, Damon, and Van Sant conceived of the idea and wrote the screenplay together while living in neighboring New York apartments.<ref name=\"vansant\" /> The film, which had minimal dialogue, received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/the-new-cult-canon-igerryi-2491 |title=The New Cult Canon: Gerry |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/News_Story/Critic_Review/Guardian_Film_of_the_week/0,4267,1026936,00.html |title=Gerry {{!}} Reviews {{!}} guardian.co.uk Film |website=The Guardian |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck, who rarely watches his own movies,<ref name=\"setoodeh\" /> said of ''Gerry'' in 2016: \"That was an incredible experience. I saw one scene recently out of context at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] and I can't believe anyone ever sat through the whole thing. It probably works better as a whole but one scene lifted out&nbsp;\u2013 I thought, 'This is unbearable!'\"<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\" /> Also in 2002, Affleck starred with Damon and then-girlfriend [[Summer Phoenix]] in a [[West End theatre|West End]] stage production of [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s ''[[This Is Our Youth]]''.<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2002/may/08/theatre.artsfeatures2 |title=This Is Our Youth |last=Gardner |first=Lyn |date=May 8, 2002 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3577077/Drugs-snogs-a-stellar-cast-and-the-coolest-night-at-the-theatre.html |title=Drugs, snogs, a stellar cast \u2013 and the coolest night at the theatre |last=Spencer |first=By Charles |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Lonergan and Affleck became friends during rehearsals,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/Casey-Afflecks-performance-in-Manchester-by-the-Sea-has-critics-raving.html |title=Casey Affleck's performance in 'Manchester by the Sea' has critics raving |newspaper=Philadelphia Daily News |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> and Affleck later acted in [[workshop production]]s of Lonergan's plays in New York.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/the-frame/2016/09/03/51841/telluride-casey-affleck-reflects-on-working-with-j/ |title=Telluride: Casey Affleck reflects on working with Joaquin Phoenix, Christian Bale and others |last=Radio |first=Southern California Public |date=September 3, 2016 |newspaper=Southern California Public Radio |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/09/casey-affleck-interview-2016-telluride-film-festival-manchester-by-the-sea-1201722112/2/ |title=Casey Affleck Interview: 'Manchester By the Sea' Star On Early Roles |last=Kohn |first=Eric|publisher=indiewire.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAffleck's first leading role was in 2006's little-seen independent comedy-drama ''[[Lonesome Jim]]'', directed by [[Steve Buscemi]]. He played a depressed writer who returns from New York to live with his parents in Indiana, and begins a relationship with [[Liv Tyler]]'s character.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/oh-brother-where-art-thou-casey-affleck-interview-1-1431777 |title=Oh brother, where art thou? \u2013 Casey Affleck interview |website=The Scotsman |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Buscemi has said he knew Affleck would be able to carry the movie after watching his performance in ''Gerry''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ecranlarge.com/films/interview/900885-steve-buscemi-lonesome-jim |title=Interview \u2013 Steve Buscemi (Lonesome Jim) |date=November 14, 2005|publisher=EcranLarge.com |language=fr-FR |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/media-quiet-steve/Content?oid=2276350 |title=Media Quiet Steve |last=Haddon |first=Cole |website=San Antonio Current |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Stephen Hunter of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' remarked: \"Affleck's interesting .. He probably can't be a star in big movies because his drawback is a voice that sounds like a snivel drawn through a wet nasal passage into a whine ... And yet in certain kinds of films&nbsp;\u2013 this kind&nbsp;\u2013 he's 100 percent authentic.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/13/AR2006041302146.html |title=Bleak House on the Prairie |last=Hunter |first=Stephen |date=April 14, 2006 |newspaper=The Washington Post |language=en-US|issn=0190-8286 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Ty Burr of the ''[[Boston Globe]]'' said Affleck \"gets so far under the skin of this semi-charming jerk that the performance becomes both brave and aggravating.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2006/05/05/humor_in_jim_is_a_little_too_dry/ |title=Humor in 'Jim' is a little too dry \u2013 The Boston Globe |website=Boston Globe |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> However, Stephen Holden of ''The New York Times'' felt it \"would be a stronger movie if Mr. Affleck had the wherewithal to bare more of the passive-aggressive rage inside ... a more resourceful actor would have used this blank slate to scrawl a thousand telling details.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/24/movies/lonesome-jim-discovers-you-can-go-home-again-hat-in-hand.html |title='Lonesome Jim' Discovers You Can Go Home Again (Hat in Hand) |last=Holden |first=Stephen |date=March 24, 2006 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2006, he had a supporting role in the romantic comedy ''[[The Last Kiss (2006 film)|The Last Kiss]]'' as a friend of [[Zach Braff]]'s character.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2006/09/15/last_kiss_commits_to_low_fidelity/ |title='Last Kiss' commits to low fidelity \u2013 The Boston Globe |website=Boston Globe |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Breakthrough (2007\u20132012) ===\nAffleck had a breakthrough year in 2007, with the release of two films featuring critically acclaimed performances.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/movies/casey-affleck-interview-manchester-by-the-sea.html |title=Casey Affleck Is Making Another Splash, Reluctantly |last=Buckley |first=Cara |date=November 4, 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The first of these performances was in the Western drama ''[[The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford]]'', in which he played [[Robert Ford (outlaw)|Robert Ford]] to [[Brad Pitt]]'s [[Jesse James]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywood.com/general/brad-pitt-casey-affleck-jesse-james-interview-57174058/ |title='The Assassination of Jesse James' Interview: Brad Pitt and Casey Affleck Repeat the Lore |last=Staff |first=Hollywood.com |date=September 21, 2007|publisher=Hollywood.com |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck auditioned repeatedly for the role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mysinchew.com/node/8713 |title=The Other Affleck|publisher=mysinchew.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> While the director [[Andrew Dominik]] had seen Affleck in ''Gerry'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2007/interview-assassination-of-jesse-jamess-director-andrew-dominik/ |title=Interview: Assassination of Jesse James's Director Andrew Dominik|publisher=FirstShowing.net |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thefilmstage.com/features/living-in-the-shadow-of-jesse-james-an-appreciation-of-casey-afflecks-best-performance/ |title=Living in the Shadow of 'Jesse James': An Appreciation of Casey Affleck's Best Performance |date=December 2, 2013 |newspaper=The Film Stage |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> he cast him partly because of his \"beautiful-sounding voice. The voice is the thing that really gets you.\"<ref name=\"uproxx\">{{cite news |url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/exclusive-andrew-dominik-remembers-embattled-jesse-james-production-as-revival-screening-looms/ |title=Exclusive: 'Jesse James' director remembers embattled production as revival screening looms |date=November 7, 2013 |newspaper=UPROXX |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/12/terrence-malick-thought-it-was-too-slow-10-things-learned-from-the-revival-screening-of-the-assassination-of-jesse-james-by-the-coward-robert-ford-90884/ |title=Terrence Malick Thought It Was Too Slow: 10 Things Learned From The Revival Screening Of 'The Assassination Of Jesse James By The Coward Robert Ford' {{!}} IndieWire |last=Hoffman |first=Jordan |website=www.indiewire.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Manohla Dargis of ''The New York Times'' described Affleck's performance as a \"revelation\" which \"manages to make the character seem dumb and the actor wily and smart.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/21/movies/21assa.html |title=The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford \u2013 Movies \u2013 Review |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=September 21, 2007 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Similarly, Claudia Puig of ''USA Today'' declared him a \"real revelation [who] perfectly inhabits the role\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-09-20-jesse-james_N.htm |title='Jesse James' is just a great, gorgeous Western |work=USA Today |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |first=Claudia |last=Puig |date=September 20, 2007}}</ref> while Todd McCarthy of ''Variety'' said Affleck made \"an indelible impression as the insecure, physically unprepossessing weakling.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117934539.html?categoryid=2880&cs=1 |title=The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford|work=Variety |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |date=August 31, 2007}}</ref> Dana Stevens of ''Slate'' said \"the movie belongs to Affleck [who] goes for broke in a wonderfully brave and weird performance as the craven naif Bob. Somehow he makes us want to flee this creep at top speed, even as we pray no harm will come to him.\" For his performance, Affleck was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]].\n\n[[File:Casey Affleck.jpg|thumb|150px|Affleck on the set of ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'' in 2006]]\n\nWhile he was filming ''The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford'' in [[Calgary]], Affleck was visited by his brother, who offered him the leading role in his directorial project, the Boston crime thriller ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\" /> While his brother was a first-time director and in the midst of a career downturn, Affleck had confidence in the project: \"I felt like I knew him better than anyone else did.\"<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/benaffleckgonebabygone-111785--.html |title=Ben Affleck, behind the scenes |last=KOLTNOW |first=BARRY |newspaper=The Orange County Register |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> His performance, as an inexperienced private investigator tasked with finding a missing child, earned Affleck further plaudits for his acting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/gone_baby_gone/ |title=Gone Baby Gone |date=October 19, 2007 |publisher=rottentomatoes.com |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817101856/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/gone_baby_gone/ |archivedate=August 17, 2015 }}</ref> Manohla Dargis of ''The New York Times'' said: \"I'm not sure exactly when Casey Affleck became such a good actor ... Most actors want you to love them, but [he] doesn't seem to know that, or maybe he doesn't care.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/19/movies/19gone.html |title=Gone Baby Gone \u2013 Movies \u2013 Review |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=October 19, 2007 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Jim Ridley of ''The Village Voice'' described him as \"a major talent coming into his own\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/film/beantown-boys-make-good-6424146 |title=Beantown Boys Make Good |last=Ridley |first=Jim |date=October 9, 2007 |newspaper=The Village Voice |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> while Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' remarked that \"the revelation is Casey Affleck, who heretofore has been a rather wormy, uncharismatic screen presence.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Gone-Baby-Gone-gritty-and-gripping-with-shades-2534442.php |title='Gone Baby Gone' gritty and gripping, with shades of gray |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Ty Burr of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' commented: \"I'd never stopped to consider Casey Affleck as a movie star before, but under his big brother's tutelage, he blooms as a leading man of richly watchable savvy and intelligence.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2007/10/17/here_here/?page=full |title=Here, here! With crime thriller 'Gone Baby Gone,' Ben Affleck returns home and captures Boston in all its gritty glory |last=Burr |first=Ty|work=Boston Globe |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford'' and ''Gone Baby Gone'' were a financial failure and a modest box office success, respectively,<ref name=\"uproxx\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=gonebabygone.htm |title=Gone Baby Gone (2007) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|publisher=boxofficemojo.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck's acting career was widely believed to be at a turning point.<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\" /> However, he lost career momentum while directing ''[[I'm Still Here (2010 film)|I'm Still Here]]'' (2010), a divisive mockumentary about the musical career of his friend and then brother-in-law [[Joaquin Phoenix]].<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\" /> While Affleck later clarified that it was \"a planned, staged and scripted work of fiction,\"<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/8016510/Casey-Affleck-Joaquin-Phoenix-hoax-made-me-go-broke.html |title=Casey Affleck: Joaquin Phoenix hoax made me go broke |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> there was much media speculation during filming about whether Phoenix's public behaviour was performance art or a genuine breakdown.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/17/movies/17affleck.html |title=Documentary? Better Call It Performance Art|work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |first=Michael |last=Cieply |date=September 16, 2010}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''USA Today'' remarked that, \"whether truth or folly, it's not particularly well made. Even in the midst of Phoenix's most oddball and obsessive torment, it's boring ... What, exactly, is the point of a joke that nobody really gets?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2010-09-10-Imstillhere10_ST_N.htm |title='I'm Still Here': Joaquin Phoenix's meltdown, or a bizarre put-on?|work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |date=September 9, 2010 |first=Claudia |last=Puig}}</ref> Ty Burr of ''The Boston Globe'' described it as \"an interesting but half-baked exercise in persona deconstruction, celebrity politics, and meta-meta-entertainment ... Parts of it are close to genius; most of it is actively torturous to watch.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2010/09/10/phoenix_goes_up_in_flames/ |title=I'm Still Here |last=Burr |first=Ty |newspaper=Boston Globe |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Kenneth Turan of the ''Los Angeles Times'' said the film \"turns out to be much more interesting to speculate about than to actually watch.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/10/entertainment/la-et-stillhere-20100910 |title=Movie review: 'I'm Still Here' |last=Turan |first=Kenneth |date=September 10, 2010 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US|issn=0458-3035 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Reflecting on the experience in 2016, Affleck said: \"We never thought people would actually think it was real ... In hindsight, we should have had a press junket and done talk shows and said how it was a mockumentary.\"<ref name=\"indiewire\" />\n\nAffleck used his own money to fund ''I'm Still Here'' and, after running out of cash,<ref name=\"telegraph\" /> filming was paused for a month to allow him to play a Texan [[serial killer]] in [[Michael Winterbottom]]'s crime drama ''[[The Killer Inside Me (2010 film)|The Killer Inside Me]]'' (2010).<ref name=\"BloodyDisgusting\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/14372 |title=BD Horror News \u2013 'Killer Inside Me' Finds New Director and Cast |publisher=BloodyDisgusting |date=November 17, 2008 |accessdate=November 28, 2008}}</ref> Affleck later expressed regret over the movie's graphic violence.<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> Philip French of ''The Guardian'' found him \"disturbingly brilliant\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jun/06/killer-inside-me-film-review |title=The Killer Inside Me |last=French |first=Philip |date=June 5, 2010 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> while Peter Travers of ''Rolling Stone'' praised \"a mesmeric, implosively powerful performance.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-killer-inside-me-20100618 |title=The Killer Inside Me |newspaper=Rolling Stone |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Mark Olsen of the ''Los Angeles Times'' said Affleck \"showcases his uncanny ability to project a person holding two thoughts in his head at once, as he often gives away nothing in his face to convey the firestorm obviously raging in his soul.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2010/01/sundance-2010-the-killer-inside-me-.html |title=Sundance 2010: In defense of 'The Killer Inside Me' |date=January 29, 2010 |website=LA Times Blogs \u2013 24 Frames |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck then had a supporting role in the heist comedy ''[[Tower Heist]]'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies_2011/tower_heist/notes.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/64hFGXRbc?url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies_2011/tower_heist/notes.pdf |archive-date=January 14, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and voiced a character in the 2012 animation ''[[ParaNorman]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.ie/movie-review/ParaNorman/136120.htm |title=ParaNorman |last=Entertainment.ie |newspaper=entertainment.ie |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Wider recognition (2013\u2013present) ===\nAfter spending \"a big chunk of time\" directing ''I'm Still Here'' and dealing with the subsequent backlash,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.anothermag.com/art-photography/2983/casey-affleck-rooney-mara-on-ain-t-them-bodies-saints |title=Casey Affleck & Rooney Mara on Ain't Them Bodies Saints |last=AnOther |newspaper=AnOther |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck returned to regular acting work in 2013. \"It was ugly for a minute ... I sort of remembered why I liked acting and I missed it.\"<ref name=\"awardsdaily\" /> In [[David Lowery (director)|David Lowery]]'s ''[[Ain't Them Bodies Saints]]'' (2013), Affleck and [[Rooney Mara]] starred as outlaw lovers in 1970s-era Texas.<ref name=\"iamrogue\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iamrogue.com/news/interviews/item/9475-iar-interview-rooney-mara-and-casey-affleck-talk-aint-them-bodies-saints.html |title=IAR INTERVIEW: Rooney Mara and Casey Affleck Talk 'Ain't Them Bodies Saints' |publisher=iamROGUE.com |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck was drawn to the opportunity to play a character who \"was a much better person than anyone thought,\" after a string of roles as \"assassins or murderers or just creeps.\"<ref name=\"iamrogue\" /> Shannon M. Houston of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' described him as the movie's \"standout actor\": \"Down to his very jawline, Affleck captures the physicality and feeling of a sincerely romantic outlaw.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/08/aint-them-bodies-saints.html |title=Ain't Them Bodies Saints |newspaper=Paste |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Betsy Sharkey of the ''Los Angeles Times'' remarked: \"Affleck plays conflicted souls so very well ... Here you wish for a criminal's redemption.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/15/entertainment/la-et-mn-aint-them-bodies-saints-review |title=Review: 'Ain't Them Bodies Saints' is a romantic sinner |last=Sharkey |first=Betsy |date=August 15, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US|issn=0458-3035 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Michael Phillips of the ''Chicago Tribune'' said: \"He has great instincts when it comes to morally compromised anti-heroes, and without trolling for our sympathy, Affleck's Bob is more than just a collection of behaviors; it's a smartly considered performance.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-08-28/entertainment/sc-mov-0827-aint-them-bodies-saints-20130828_1_rooney-mara-ruth-david-lowery |title=Ain't Them Bodies Saints movie review by Chicago Tribune's Michael Phillips |newspaper=tribunedigital-chicagotribune |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Sebastian Doggart of ''The Guardian'' said he \"shows himself again to be a master of the criminal outsider\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jan/25/aint-them-bodies-saints-review |title=Sundance film festival 2013: Ain't Them Bodies Saints \u2013 first look review |last=Doggart |first=Sebastian |date=January 25, 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> while Chuck Wilson of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' found him \"flat-out heartbreaking.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/film/the-gorgeous-aint-them-bodies-saints-goes-deep-in-the-heart-of-texans-6439172 |title=The Gorgeous Ain't Them Bodies Saints Goes Deep in the Heart of Texans |last=Wilson |first=Chuck |date=August 14, 2013 |newspaper=The Village Voice |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe opportunity to act opposite [[Christian Bale]] in the drama ''[[Out of the Furnace]]'' \"reinvigorated\" Affleck and reminded him why he enjoyed acting.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/article/2013/11/26/casey-affleck-out-of-the-furnace/ |title=Q&A: Casey Affleck Talks New Movie 'Out of the Furnace' |newspaper=Boston Magazine |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Claudia Puig of ''[[USA Today]]'' found his performance as an [[Iraq War]] veteran dealing with [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] \"completely captivating ... The chemistry between Bale and Affleck is powerful, intensifying the credibility of their brotherly bond.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2013/12/03/out-of-the-furnace-review/3551107/ |title=Gritty, well-executed 'Furnace' mesmerizes|work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |date=December 3, 2013 |first=Claudia |last=Puig}}</ref> Michael Phillips of the ''Chicago Tribune'' said Affleck \"finds something fierce and noble in uneven material and in his character's rage. He's not like any other actor in American movies.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-12-05/entertainment/chi-out-of-the-furnace-1206-20131205_1_furnace-russell-writer-director-scott-cooper |title=Out of the Furnace movie review by Chicago Tribune's Michael Phillips |newspaper=tribunedigital-chicagotribune |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Ann Hornaday of ''The Washington Post'' described the performance as \"a searing portrayal of a young man who pushes himself to the punishing physical limit in search of both money and catharsis.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/out-of-the-furnace-movie-review-bale-affleck-dominate-downbeat-crime-drama/2013/12/04/d82b8f7c-5c27-11e3-95c2-13623eb2b0e1_story.html |title='Out of the Furnace' movie review: Bale, Affleck dominate downbeat crime drama |last=Hornaday |first=Ann |date=December 4, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |language=en-US|issn=0190-8286 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Manohla Dargis of ''The New York Times'' remarked that Affleck \"can come across as intensely vulnerable on screen, which nicely works for a broken man like Rodney.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/04/movies/out-of-the-furnace-with-christian-bale.html |title='Out of the Furnace,' With Christian Bale |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=December 3, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, Affleck and [[Jessica Chastain]] had supporting roles in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s science fiction film ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' as the grown-up children of [[Matthew McConaughey]]'s character,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/05/interstellar-review-christopher-nolan-matthew-mcconaughey |title=Interstellar review: Nolan's biggest spectacle \u2013 and biggest disappointment |last=Bradshaw |first=Peter |date=November 5, 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> with Todd McCarthy of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' describing his character as \"thinly developed\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/interstellar-film-review-744059 |title='Interstellar': Film Review |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Also in 2014, Affleck and producer [[John Powers Middleton]] launched the production company, The Affleck/Middleton Project.<ref>{{cite web |title=CASEY AFFLECK AND JOHN POWERS MIDDLETON ANNOUNCE NEW JOINT VENTURE, NAME JOHN RIDLEY PRESIDENT OF PRODUCTION |url=http://www.themovienetwork.com/press/casey-affleck-and-john-powers-middleton-announce-new-joint-venture-name-john-ridley-president-|work=The Movie Network|publisher=TheMovieNetwork.com |accessdate=June 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714222403/http://www.themovienetwork.com/press/casey-affleck-and-john-powers-middleton-announce-new-joint-venture-name-john-ridley-president- |archive-date=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAffleck starred in three films in 2016, the first two of which underperformed financially.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/02/28/box-office-bombs-away-as-gods-of-egypt-triple-9-and-eddie-the-eagle-perish-on-oscar-weekend/ |title=Box Office: Bombs Away As 'Gods Of Egypt,' 'Triple 9,' And 'Eddie The Eagle' Perish On Oscar Weekend |last=Mendelson |first=Scott|work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=June 23, 2017 |date=February 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/disney-expects-to-lose-75-million-on-the-finest-hours-1201725537/ |title=Disney Expects $75 Million Loss on 'The Finest Hours' |last=Rainey |first=James |date=March 8, 2016 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> In [[John Hillcoat]]'s crime thriller ''[[Triple 9]]'', Affleck played an uncorruptible detective. Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said he \"arrests our attention. I wonder if any other screen actor has ever seemed so focused and so distracted at the same time. He thinks more than he says, and so we listen, trying to get the part he's leaving out.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Triple-9-is-a-meticulous-well-made-crime-6851734.php |title='Triple 9' does justice to evil |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Justin Chang of ''Variety'' described him as \"one of the most persuasive leading men of his generation\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/triple-9-review-casey-affleck-1201707725/ |title=Film Review: 'Triple 9' |last=Chang |first=Justin |date=February 17, 2016 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> while Brogan Morris of ''Paste Magazine'' declared him \"maybe Hollywood's best offbeat leading man ... Few actors can suggest so much with such quiet precision, and even here Affleck is compulsively watchable despite his undercooked character.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/02/triple-9.html |title=Triple 9 |newspaper=Paste |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> In Disney's disaster drama ''[[The Finest Hours (2016 film)|The Finest Hours]]'', Affleck played a taciturn engineer on board a sinking ship. David Sims of ''The Atlantic'' said he \"gives the kind of measured, thought-out performance he's so eminently capable of, even if the film isn't complex enough to rise to his level ... He animates an introverted character with subtle mental busywork whenever he's on the screen.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/the-finest-hours-a-stoic-tale-of-a-daring-rescue/433911/ |title='The Finest Hours' Is as Dependable as Disaster Movies Come |last=Sims |first=David |newspaper=The Atlantic |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Sheri Linden of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' noted that he \"manages to turn his man of few words into the movie's most compelling figure.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/finest-hours-film-review-855165 |title='The Finest Hours': Film Review |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Casey Affleck on the Manchester by the Sea red carpet (30165304696) (cropped 2).jpg|thumb|180px|right|Affleck in October 2016]]\n\nIn his final role of 2016, Affleck starred as Lee Chandler, a grief-stricken [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] loner, in [[Kenneth Lonergan]]'s drama ''[[Manchester by the Sea (film)|Manchester by the Sea]]''. One of the film's producers, Matt Damon, initially intended to star in the film. When scheduling conflicts made this unfeasible, Damon agreed to step aside on the condition that he be replaced with Affleck.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/matt-damon-would-only-have-passed-manchester-by-the-sea-role-to-casey-affleck-35047717.html |title=Matt Damon would only have passed Manchester By The Sea role to Casey Affleck \u2013 Independent.ie |newspaper=The Irish Independent |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> Lonergan readily agreed,<ref>{{Citation |last=HeyUGuys |title=Kenneth Lonergan Exclusive Interview \u2013 Manchester by the Sea |date=January 4, 2017 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G1Ic9I0tolQ |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> remarking that Affleck was \"the natural person to go to.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manchester-by-sea-kenneth-lonergan-films-origin-working-casey-affleck-957548 |title='Manchester by the Sea': Kenneth Lonergan on the Film's Origin, Working With Casey Affleck |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> Affleck had close relationships with both men and had previously offered notes on early drafts of the script.<ref name=\"setoodeh\" /> The movie was a box office success,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/top-grossing-movies-2016-best-art-house-box-office-earners-960870/item/la-la-land-box-office-art-house-films-960883 |title=La La Land \u2013 Box Office 2016: 'La La Land,' 'Manchester by the Sea' Top Highest-Grossing Art House Films |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> and Affleck's performance received widespread critical praise. A.O. Scott of ''The New York Times'' described it as \"one of the most fiercely disciplined screen performances in recent memory. [He] conveys both Lee's inner avalanche of feeling and the numb decorum that holds it back.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/18/movies/manchester-by-the-sea-review-kenneth-lonergan-casey-affleck.html |title=Review: 'Manchester by the Sea' and the Tides of Grief |last=Scott |first=A. O. |date=November 17, 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKenneth Turan of the ''Los Angeles Times'' praised his \"quietly ferocious performance, his willingness to submerge himself into this character to an almost frightening extent.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-manchester-sea-review-20161114-story.html |title=Casey Affleck's searing performance cuts deep in Kenneth Lonergan's 'Manchester by the Sea' |last=Turan |first=Kenneth |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Ann Hornaday of ''The Washington Post'' said the film was \"anchored by a quietly volcanic central performance by Casey Affleck, in a breathtaking breakout role he's long deserved.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/casey-affleck-delivers-a-breakout-performance-in-manchester-by-the-sea/2016/11/22/488aa28e-ad9d-11e6-8b45-f8e493f06fcd_story.html |title=Casey Affleck delivers a breakout performance in 'Manchester by the Sea' |last=Hornaday |first=Ann |date=November 22, 2016 |newspaper=The Washington Post |language=en-US|issn=0190-8286 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> David Fear of ''Rolling Stone'' stated: \"He's given impressive turns before [but] the way Affleck gradually shows you the man's bone-deep grief and emotional damage makes you believe that one of this generation's finest actors has simply been waiting to be coaxed out.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/manchester-by-the-sea-the-story-behind-sundance-2016s-best-movie-20160201?page=2 |title=How 'Manchester by the Sea' Became a Sundance 2016 Hit |newspaper=Rolling Stone |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Affleck won the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Actor|National Board of Review]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]] for his performance.\n\nAfter dropping out of Lowery's ''[[Pete's Dragon (2016 film)|Pete's Dragon]]'' in order to star in ''Manchester by the Sea'',<ref name=\"setoodeh\" /> Affleck reteamed with the director to star opposite [[Rooney Mara]] in the experimental drama ''[[A Ghost Story]]'', which premiered at the Sundance Film Festival in early 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thefilmstage.com/news/casey-affleck-and-rooney-mara-secretly-shot-a-new-feature-with-david-lowery-this-summer/ |title=Casey Affleck and Rooney Mara Secretly Shot a New Feature With David Lowery This Summer |website=The Film Stage |first=Jordan |last=Raup |date=November 22, 2016 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> Affleck's character dies suddenly at the outset and he spends much of the film covered by a white sheet with two eye-holes, haunting his former home. David Rooney of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' said Affleck's performance managed to resonate despite limited time onscreen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/a-ghost-story-review-965994 |title='A Ghost Story': Film Review {{!}} Sundance 2017 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''Variety'' said Affleck \"has never been an easy actor to read. He's a low-charisma mumbler who tends to keep his characters' emotions bottled up, making him the rare performer who can convey as much with a sheet over his head as he does without.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/a-ghost-story-review-1201963220/ |title=Sundance Film Review: Casey Affleck and Rooney Mara in 'A Ghost Story' |last=Debruge |first=Peter |date=January 22, 2017 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Jordan Hoffman of ''The Guardian'' described him as \"cinema's finest mumbler ... I can't even tell if he's speaking or just emitting high-pitched vibrations anymore.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/23/a-ghost-story-review-casey-affleck-david-lowery-rooney-mara |title=A Ghost Story review: Casey Affleck channels Swayze in haunting love story |last=Hoffman |first=Jordan |date=January 23, 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, Affleck starred opposite [[Robert Redford]] in the outlaw drama ''[[The Old Man & the Gun]]'', his third collaboration with Lowery.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/casey-affleck-robert-redford-star-the-old-man-and-the-gun-david-lowery-1201741324/ |title=Casey Affleck and Robert Redford Join 'The Old Man and the Gun' {{!}} IndieWire |last=Calvario |first=Liz |website=www.indiewire.com |accessdate=January 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he directed, wrote and starred in the survival drama ''[[Light of My Life (film)|Light of My Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://infotel.ca/newsitem/casey-affleck-coming-to-osoyoos-to-direct-movie-he-wrote-and-is-starring-in/it39263 |title=Casey Affleck coming to Osoyoos to direct movie he wrote, and is starring in |website=infotel.ca |accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/casey-affleck-light-of-my-life-survival-drama-1201856529/ |title=Casey Affleck Directing, Starring in Survival Drama 'Light of My Life' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=September 10, 2016 |newspaper=Variety |language=en-US |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] on February 8, 2019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/casey-affleck-elisabeth-moss-movie-light-of-my-life-among-berlin-world-premiere-additions-1202538698/ |title=Casey Affleck-Elisabeth Moss Movie 'Light Of My Life' Among Berlin World Premiere Additions |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=January 21, 2019 |accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref> and received positive reviews from film critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/light_of_my_life |title=Light of My Life |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Affleck next starred in ''[[The Friend (film)|The Friend]]'', opposite [[Dakota Johnson]] and [[Jason Segel]], directed by [[Gabriela Cowperthwaite]], based upon a true story revolving around a couple, whose best friend moves in for support, following a cancer diagnosis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/jason-segel-dakota-johnson-casey-affleck-gabriela-cowperthwaite-brad-ingelsby-the-friend-1202546034/ |title=Jason Segel, Dakota Johnson, Casey Affleck To Star In 'The Friend' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> which had its world premiere at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/ |title=Toronto Film Festival: \u2018Joker,\u2019 \u2018Ford v Ferrari,\u2019 \u2018Hustlers\u2019 Among Big Premieres |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Brent |last=Lang |date=July 23, 2019 |accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref> Affleck will next act and produce ''[[The World to Come]]'', directed by [[Mona Fastvold]] alongside [[Katherine Waterston]] and [[Vanessa Kirby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/casey-affleck-sets-world-come-production-banner-1183706/ |title=Casey Affleck Sets 'World to Come' With Production Banner |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Alex |last=Ritman |date=February 7, 2019 |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Relationships and family ===\nAffleck was introduced to actress [[Summer Phoenix]] by her brother, [[Joaquin Phoenix|Joaquin]], in the late 1990s.<ref name=\"bostonmagazine2006\" /><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/feb/15/features.magazine |title=Summer time |last=Vernon |first=Polly |date=February 14, 2004 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> They began dating in 2000,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3613144/Here-comes-Summer.html |title=Here comes Summer |last=Forrest |first=Emma |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> and acted together in both the 2000 film ''Committed''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.popmatters.com/review/committed/ |title=Committed (2000) |newspaper=PopMatters |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> and a 2002 stage production of ''[[This is Our Youth]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/casey-affleck-on-the-emotional-road-to-manchester-by-the-sea/5111408.article |title=Casey Affleck on the emotional road to 'Manchester By The Sea' |accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> The couple became engaged in January 2004<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /> and married on June 3, 2006 in Savannah, Georgia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1198239,00.html |title=Casey Affleck, Summer Phoenix Wed |date=June 5, 2006 |work=People |accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref> They have two sons, Indiana August (b. May 2004)<ref name=\"telegraphgarratt\" /><ref name=secondson /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20146470,00.html |title=Baby Boom|work=People |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915013414/https://people.com/people/article/0,,20146470,00.html |archive-date=September 15, 2015 |date=December 27, 2004 |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Atticus (b. January 2008).<ref name=\"secondson\">{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20171855,00.html |title=Casey Affleck Welcomes a Second Child |date=January 15, 2008 |website=People |accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/film-tv/affleck-brothers-strike-gold-silver-3958603 |title=Affleck brothers strike gold on the silver screen |work=[[Birmingham Post]] |location=UK |date=June 5, 2008 |first=Alison |last=Jones |accessdate=August 18, 2014 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053035/http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/film-tv/affleck-brothers-strike-gold-silver-3958603 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/01/see-divorce-document-casey-affleck-and-summer-pheonix-make-split-official-filing-for-divorce-6820534/ |title=Casey Affleck and Summer Phoenix make split official filing for divorce |last=Metro.co.uk |first=Claire Rutter for |date=August 1, 2017 |website=Metro |accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref> By November 2015, they had privately separated.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gloucestertimes.com/news/local_news/damon-s-manchester-by-the-sea-begins-production-in-namesake/article_b99a812a-321c-56c3-9371-e8d2830ef6ae.html |title=Damon's 'Manchester-by-the-Sea' begins production in namesake town |last=Writer |first=Taylor Rapalyea Staff |newspaper=Gloucester Daily Times |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/acclaim-raining-down-casey-affleck-223510792.html |title=With acclaim raining down, Casey Affleck tries to enjoy it |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> They publicly announced <!--through their representative--> their separation in March 2016.<ref name=separation>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/article/casey-affleck-summer-phoenix-split-10-year-marriage |title=Casey Affleck & Summer Phoenix Split: Inside Their 10-Year Marriage |first=Chancellor |last=Agard |work=People |date=March 16, 2016 |accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref> On August 1, 2017, Phoenix officially filed for divorce, citing \"irreconcilable differences\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2017/08/01/summer-phoenix-files-divorce-husband-casey-affleck/528256001/ |title=Summer Phoenix files for divorce from husband Casey Affleck}}</ref> and it was finalized later that year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/871526/casey-affleck-responds-to-summer-phoenix-s-divorce-filing |title=Casey Affleck Finalizes Divorce From Summer Phoenix |last=Fisher |first=Kendall |date=August 4, 2017|work=E! Online |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Affleck has said it was an amicable divorce and that they remain friends.<ref name=\"wtfpod.com\" />\n\nIn 2016, he began a relationship with actress [[Floriana Lima]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.com/movies/casey-affleck-girlfriend-floriana-lima-ben-affleck-manchester-by-the-sea/ |title=Casey Affleck's New Supergirl Girlfriend \u2014 and Ben Affleck! \u2014 Join Him at Manchester By the Sea Premiere |first=Jodie |last=Guglielmi |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=December 2, 2019 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n===Alcoholism===\nIn a 2016 interview, Affleck said that he had been sober for \"almost three years ... My father was a disaster of a drinker, my grandmother was an alcoholic, my brother spent some time in rehab&nbsp;\u2013 it's in our genes.\"<ref name=\"wtfpod.com\" />\n\n=== Political views ===\nIn 2008, Affleck filmed an episode of documentary series ''[[4Real]]'', in which he visited the [[Pawnee people|Pawnee Nation of Oklahoma]], and remarked upon the progress they had made due largely to \"their own resourcefulness and determination and their character, and not because of the goodness of our collective heart.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=465238 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312030348/http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=465238 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 12, 2008 |title=Aborigines' plight inspires US actor : thewest.com.au |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> During the [[United States presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]], Affleck supported [[Hillary Clinton]]<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Tuitealo |title=CASEY AFFLECK ARREMETE CONTRA DONALD TRUMP EN EL FESTIVAL DE CINE DE MORELIA 2016 |date=October 24, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AhMM7XMrf4E |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> and characterized [[Donald Trump]] as \"a dangerous fool.\"<ref name=\"setoodeh\" /><ref>{{Citation |last=AP Archive |title=Actress Michelle Williams on Trump victory: 'It was a very hard day to be a mother' |date=November 19, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7NbieCiRnIw |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, multiple financial contributions to Trump were made by Affleck's production company, which he co-founded with [[John Powers Middleton]]. In a statement, Affleck denied involvement: \"I had no knowledge of it, was never asked, and never would have authorized it ... The policies of the Trump administration, and the values they represent, are antithetical to everything I believe in.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Katie |last=Hasty |title=Casey Affleck Is \"Appalled\" His Production Company Donated To Donald Trump's Transition Team |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/katiehasty/casey-affleck-appalled-production-company-trump-donation |website=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=June 11, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\n\n=== Animal rights activism and veganism ===\nAffleck has been a [[veganism|vegan]] since 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/casey-affleck-on-the-cover |title=casey affleck on the cover \u00b7 NYLON|publisher=nylon.com |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> He has been involved with [[animal rights]] campaigns for both [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.peta.org/videos/casey-afflecks-exclusive-interview-with-peta/ |title=Casey Affleck's Exclusive Interview With PETA |newspaper=PETA |language=en-US |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.peta.org/blog/casey-afflecks-latest-role-saving-bears/ |title=Casey Affleck's Latest Role? Saving Bears |date=April 25, 2016 |newspaper=PETA |language=en-US |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=PETA (People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals) |title=Casey Affleck Exposes Mutilation of Cows in Dairy Industry |date=September 17, 2012 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kWscTrpBVOM |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref> and [[Farm Sanctuary]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/inside_track/inside_track/2013/01/casey_affleck_rustles_support_farm_bill |title=Casey Affleck rustles up support for farm bill |website=Boston Herald |accessdate=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Veterans ===\nIn 2017, Affleck supported the 37th Annual National Veterans Wheelchair Games<ref>{{Citation |title=Casey Affleck National Veteran Wheelchair Games shout out video |url=https://www.facebook.com/NickPalmisciano/videos/casey-affleck-national-veteran-wheelchair-games-shout-out-video/10158945871555577/ |language=en |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref> hosted by [[Paralyzed Veterans of America]]. In January 2019, he attended the 4th Annual [[Veterans Awards]] as a presenter.<ref>{{cite web |title=CASEY AFFLECK PRESENTED THE MENTAL HEALTH VETTY ||url=http://vettys.org/casey-affleck |title=Casey Affleck |website=AUSV |language=en-US |accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1995\n| ''[[To Die For]]''\n| Russell Hines\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1996\n| ''[[Race the Sun]]''\n| Daniel Webster\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1997\n| ''[[Chasing Amy]]''\n| Little Kid\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1997\n| ''[[Good Will Hunting]]''\n| Morgan O'Mally\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1998\n| ''[[Desert Blue]]''\n| Pete Kepler\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1999\n| ''[[200 Cigarettes]]''\n| Tom\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1999\n| ''[[American Pie (film)|American Pie]]''\n| Tom Myers\n| Uncredited\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1999\n| ''[[Floating (film)|Floating]]''\n| Prep #1\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2000\n| ''[[Drowning Mona]]''\n| Bobby Calzone\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2000\n| ''[[Committed (2000 film)|Committed]]''\n| Jay\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2000\n| ''[[Hamlet (2000 film)|Hamlet]]''\n| [[Fortinbras]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2000\n| ''[[Attention Shoppers (film)|Attention Shoppers]]''\n| Jed\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2001\n| ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]''\n| Virgil Malloy\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2001\n| ''[[American Pie 2]]''\n| Tom Myers\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2001\n| ''[[Soul Survivors]]''\n| Sean\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2002\n| ''[[Gerry (2002 film)|Gerry]]''\n| Gerry\n| Also screenwriter\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2004\n| ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]''\n| Virgil Malloy\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2005\n| ''[[Lonesome Jim]]''\n| Jim\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2006\n| ''[[The Last Kiss (2006 film)|The Last Kiss]]''\n| Chris\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2007\n| ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]''\n| Virgil Malloy\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2007\n| ''[[The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Fo