{"title_page": "Subnautica Below Zero", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 video game}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{Sources exist|date=April 2020}}{{Confusing|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Subnautica Below Zero\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = [[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]\n| publisher = Unknown Worlds Entertainment\n| director = Charlie Cleveland\n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|Cory Strader|Brian Cummings|Scott MacDonald\n<ref name=\"Crew\">{{cite web|last=Jeremy|first=Hugh|title=The Crew of Subnautica|url=http://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/the-crew-of-subnautica/|publisher=[[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]|date=December 17, 2013|access-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417144732/http://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/the-crew-of-subnautica/|archive-date=April 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n| writer = [[Tom Jubert]]\n| composer =\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[MacOS]]}}\n| released = \n| genre = {{hlist|[[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]|[[survival game|survival]]}}\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Subnautica Below Zero''''' is an [[open world]] [[Survival game|survival]] [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game developed and published by [[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]. It is the sequel to ''[[Subnautica]]'', which was released in January 2018.\n\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' was released in [[early access]] for Microsoft Windows and macOS in January 2019. \n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' is a [[Survival game|survival]], [[Adventure game|adventure]] game set in an [[open world]] environment and played from a [[First-person (video games)|first-person perspective]]. The player controls a researcher researching the local environment and nearby alien facility, on planet 4546B.\n\n== Plot ==\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' takes place two years after the ending of ''[[Subnautica]]''. Alterra has placed the Vesper Station into orbit around the planet 4546B for research. The story opens with the Player being told to head to the nearby Mountain Alien Facility to locate Serik Jevov (Jeff). The player then encounters the voice of one of The Architects, letting the player know that Jeff is gone; the Alien Facility then gets locked off and requires a White Tablet to enter. Afterward, the Alien Facility is  struck by a meteor and begins re-routing its power to Sanctuary. The player is told to get to the escape ship back at base, however, the ship takes off, and the player has to take shelter in Research Base Zero. After the meteor shower triggers an Avalanche, the ice breaks below the player causing them to have to swim out into open water, and head to a Lifepod launched by Sam Goodall on the Vesper Station, just before The Vesper is struck by a meteorite damaging its communication ability. \n\nShortly after, the player receives a message tracked to the Alien Sanctuary Site in the Twist Bridges. Once the player is exploring the Underwater Alien Facility, they are threatened by an Alien voice saying that its storage medium is failing. As the player reaches the inner of the Alien Facility, it notes that is has found an \"adequate storage medium\". The player offers their PDA for the consciousnesses to transfer into, however, it transfers into the players Cerebral Cortex. The Alien Voice then lets the player knows its name is Al-an.\n\nAs the player approaches Rocket Island, their PDA informs them that repairing the communications tower will reestablish contact with The Vesper, requiring the player to explore the Mercury II wreck, a ship that crashed anywhere from 30 to 100 years ago. After The Player repairs the communications tower, they are told the ship that took off at the beginning of the game crash-landed in the Glacial Basin and that they have three objectives: Find Jeff, extract a sample of the Kharaa sample and retrieve research data from Research Base Omega.\n\nIn the Glacial Basin, the player finds the crashed escape ship. The player can locate Jeff's base in the Glacial Basin and is informed that Jeff is most likely in another sector. The player is then told to head to the Leviathan Genetic Research Program to receive a sample of the Kharaa Bacterium and send it up to The Vesper. As the player explores the Glacial Basin, they find a Cache with one of The Architect body parts.  A while after the player sends the Kharaa Bacterium, they get a message saying that it never arrived. The player then gets a supply drop in the Lilypad Islands leading them towards Research Base Omega. Throughout the player's adventure, they find two more caches, each containing one of the other parts to The Architect's body. When the player arrives in the Fabricator Base, they are told that they are able to construct Al-an a body and transfer his consciousness back into it.\n\nThe Player gets contacted by Sam to be told that The Vesper's supply of Enzyme 42 deteriorated overnight and that they need a sample from a nearby Sea Emperor Leviathan. As the player sends the Enzyme up to The Vesper, an Architect shield covers the planet causing the rocket containing the cure to explode. The player then calls Robin and the Mission director about what happened, Jeff then joins the call and says his intention to hold the Vesper crew hostage as they are most likely exposed to the Kharaa bacterium, alongside The Player being trapped on the surface. The Player then learns from Al-an that they need to head to the Mountain Alien Facility \n\nAfter the player receives the White tablet to enter the facility, they head to the Alien Facility and enter it.  The game ends with The Vesper station being blown up.\n\n<!--== Plot == how are there two different plots? That needs explaining for inclusion.\n\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' takes place two years after the ending of Subnautica. Alterra is funding a smaller company called XenoWorks, which the player works for. The player heads down on a shuttle to the surface of 4546B trying to \"cover from Alterra satellites\" to find their sister, Sam. On the way down, a meteor crashes into the player causing their lifepod to deploy and them to crash land in Sector Zero.\n-->\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/ Official website]\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 video game}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{Sources exist|date=April 2020}}{{Confusing|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Subnautica Below Zero\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = [[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]\n| publisher = Unknown Worlds Entertainment\n| director = Charlie Cleveland\n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|Cory Strader|Brian Cummings|Scott MacDonald\n<ref name=\"Crew\">{{cite web|last=Jeremy|first=Hugh|title=The Crew of Subnautica|url=http://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/the-crew-of-subnautica/|publisher=[[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]|date=December 17, 2013|access-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417144732/http://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/the-crew-of-subnautica/|archive-date=April 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n| writer = [[Tom Jubert]]\n| composer =\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[MacOS]]}}\n| released = \n| genre = {{hlist|[[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]|[[survival game|survival]]}}\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Subnautica Below Zero''''' is an [[open world]] [[Survival game|survival]] [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game developed and published by [[Unknown Worlds Entertainment]]. It is the sequel to ''[[Subnautica]]'', which was released in January 2018.\n\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' was released in [[early access]] for Microsoft Windows and macOS in January 2019. \n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' is a [[Survival game|survival]], [[Adventure game|adventure]] game set in an [[open world]] environment and played from a [[First-person (video games)|first-person perspective]]. The player controls a researcher researching the local environment and nearby alien facility, on planet 4546B.\n\n== Plot ==\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' takes place two years after the ending of ''[[Subnautica]]''. Alterra has placed the Vesper Station into orbit around the planet 4546B for research. The Player is told to head to the nearby Mountain Alien Facility to locate Serik Jevov (Jeff). The player then encounters the voice of one of The Architects, letting the player know that Jeff is gone; the Alien Facility then gets locked off and requires a White Tablet to enter. The Alien Facility is then struck by a meteor and begins re-routing its power to Sanctuary. The player is told to get to the escape ship back at base, however, the ship takes off, and the player has to take shelter in Research Base Zero. After the meteor shower triggers an Avalanche, the ice breaks below the player causing them to have to swim out into open water, and head to a Lifepod launched by Sam Goodall on the Vesper Station, just before The Vesper is struck by a meteorite damaging its communication ability. \n\nShortly after, the player receives a message tracked to the Alien Sanctuary Site in the Twist Bridges. Once the player is exploring the Underwater Alien Facility, they are threatened by an Alien voice saying that its storage medium is failing. As the player reaches the inner of the Alien Facility, it notes that is has found an \"adequate storage medium\". The player offers their PDA for the consciousnesses to transfer into, however, it transfers into the players Cerebral Cortex. The Alien Voice then lets the player knows its name is Al-an.\n\nAs the player approaches Rocket Island, their PDA informs them that repairing the communications tower will reestablish contact with The Vesper, requiring the player to explore the Mercury II wreck, a ship that crashed anywhere from 30 to 100 years ago. After The Player repairs the communications tower, they are told the ship that took off at the beginning of the game crash-landed in the Glacial Basin and that they have three objectives: Find Jeff, extract a sample of the Kharaa sample and retrieve research data from Research Base Omega.\n\nIn the Glacial Basin, the player finds the crashed escape ship. The player can locate Jeff's base in the Glacial Basin and is informed that Jeff is most likely in another sector. The player is then told to head to the Leviathan Genetic Research Program to receive a sample of the Kharaa Bacterium and send it up to The Vesper. As the player explores the Glacial Basin, they find a Cache with one of The Architect body parts.  A while after the player sends the Kharaa Bacterium, they get a message saying that it never arrived. The player then gets a supply drop in the Lilypad Islands leading them towards Research Base Omega. Throughout the player's adventure, they find two more caches, each containing one of the other parts to The Architect's body. When the player arrives in the Fabricator Base, they are told that they are able to construct Al-an a body and transfer his consciousness back into it.\n\nThe Player gets contacted by Sam to be told that The Vesper's supply of Enzyme 42 deteriorated overnight and that they need a sample from a nearby Sea Emperor Leviathan. As the player sends the Enzyme up to The Vesper, an Architect shield covers the planet causing the rocket containing the cure to explode. The player then calls Robin and the Mission director about what happened, Jeff then joins the call and says his intention to hold the Vesper crew hostage as they are most likely exposed to the Kharaa bacterium, alongside The Player being trapped on the surface. The Player then learns from Al-an that they need to head to the Mountain Alien Facility \n\nAfter the player receives the White tablet to enter the facility, they head to the Alien Facility and enter it.  The game ends with The Vesper station being blown up.\n\n<!--== Plot == how are there two different plots? That needs explaining for inclusion.\n\n''Subnautica Below Zero'' takes place two years after the ending of Subnautica. Alterra is funding a smaller company called XenoWorks, which the player works for. The player heads down on a shuttle to the surface of 4546B trying to \"cover from Alterra satellites\" to find their sister, Sam. On the way down, a meteor crashes into the player causing their lifepod to deploy and them to crash land in Sector Zero.\n-->\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://unknownworlds.com/subnautica/ Official website]\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Bgardener32", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:edited some wording for clarity. It needs additional work from someone who has played the game.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subnautica_Below_Zero"}
{"title_page": "Charleston Orphan House", "text_new": "== History ==\nThe Charleston Orphan House was established in 1790 by [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], South Carolina's city council as the first public orphanage in the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scencyclopedia.org/sce/entries/charleston-orphan-house/|title=Charleston Orphan House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The council rented a house on Market Street from 1790 until construction on the orphan house building was complete in 1794.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Murray, John E., 1959-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/783150297|title=The Charleston Orphan House : children's lives in the first public orphanage in America|isbn=978-0-226-92409-0|oclc=783150297}}</ref> The orphanage was within Calhoun (Boundary), King, Vanderhorst, and St. Phillips Streets.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=Newton, B.|date=1961|title=The Charleston Orphan House: 1860-1876|url=|journal=www.jstor.org/stable/27566370|volume=62|pages=203-214|via=JSTOR}}</ref> \n\nBefore the Orphan House was established, [[St. Philip's Episcopal Church (Charleston, South Carolina)|St. Phillip's]] and St. Michael's parishes provided for destitute children. They ordered men who abandoned their families to pay child support and paid women to care for young children who did not have families. When Charleston was incorporated in 1783, the city had to take on the burden of caring for these children. The city hoped establishing an orphanage as a centralized site of care would save on expenses.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nBy 1861, the Orphan House was staffed by 39 employees who cared for 360 children.<ref name=\":1\" /> Residents of the Orphan House were often poor white children with living parents who could not afford to care for them. Orphan House children typically received a few years of school before being hired out as apprentices, farmers, or domestic servants.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1951, the children were moved to a new site called Oak Grove Plantation in [[North Charleston, South Carolina|North Charleston]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/news/brief-history-of-orphan-house/article_b3ecb71d-dd38-5cdc-bd29-37b52864b9cc.html|title=Brief history of Orphan House|website=Post and Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Architecture ===\nGentleman architect [[Gabriel Manigault]] designed the orphan house's chapel in 1802.<ref name=\":0\" /> Architects Jones and Lee remodeled and enlarged the building in the 1850s.<ref name=\":3\" /> The building was demolished in 1956 to build a Sears Department Store and later the [[College of Charleston|College of Charleston's]] Joe E. Berry dormitory.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Notable Alumni ===\nAndrew Buist Murray and Christopher Memminger\n<references />\n<br />\n", "text_old": "== History ==\nThe Charleston Orphan House was established in 1790 by Charleston's city council as the first public orphanage in the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.scencyclopedia.org/sce/entries/charleston-orphan-house/|title=Charleston Orphan House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The council rented a house on Market Street from 1790 until construction on the orphan house building was complete in 1794.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Murray, John E., 1959-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/783150297|title=The Charleston Orphan House : children's lives in the first public orphanage in America|isbn=978-0-226-92409-0|oclc=783150297}}</ref> The orphanage was within Calhoun (Boundary), King, Vanderhorst, and St. Phillips Streets.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=Newton, B.|date=1961|title=The Charleston Orphan House: 1860-1876|url=|journal=www.jstor.org/stable/27566370|volume=62|pages=203-214|via=JSTOR}}</ref> \n\nBefore the Orphan House was established, St. Phillip's and St. Michael's parishes provided for destitute children. They ordered men who abandoned their families to pay child support and paid women to care for young children who did not have families. When Charleston was incorporated in 1783, the city had to take on the burden of caring for these children. The city hoped establishing an orphanage as a centralized site of care would save on expenses.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nBy 1861, the Orphan House was staffed by 39 employees who cared for 360 children.<ref name=\":1\" /> Residents of the Orphan House were often poor white children with living parents who could not afford to care for them. Orphan House children typically received a few years of school before being hired out as apprentices, farmers, or domestic servants.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1951, the children were moved to a new site called Oak Grove Plantation in North Charleston.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/news/brief-history-of-orphan-house/article_b3ecb71d-dd38-5cdc-bd29-37b52864b9cc.html|title=Brief history of Orphan House|website=Post and Courier|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Architecture ===\nGentleman architect Gabriel Manigault designed the orphan house's chapel in 1802.<ref name=\":0\" /> Architects Jones and Lee remodeled and enlarged the building in the 1850s.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Notable Alumni ===\nAndrew Buist Murray and Christopher Memminger\n<references />\n<ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n", "name_user": "CatherineStiers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable Alumni", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charleston_Orphan_House"}
